Street}}Stapleton Hall Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you move again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We lived there for - twenty-five years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you'd come there in 1909?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Roughly, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You stayed there twenty-five years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that brings us up to 1934?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 1934. No, it was - not 1934. Couldn't have been because we were - dad went - living in the other house in 193
4. No, we came here in - let me see, I was nine - 1889 - it was 1890. And - that makes ten years' difference, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you stayed twenty-five years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that was until 1915?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then you moved again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We moved
 across the road to another house at number seventy-eight. Tregenna. In the same road. And lived there - and lived there and of course I married in between but my people lived there until 1934.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember why the family moved from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Lower Clapton{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh they moved because they wanted a bigger house. And my grandfather, my mother was an only child, and my grandfather bought this house for her a because it was so near Stroud Green station and my father had to get to the Prudential. Which was in the
 City, yes. He was - his great - his own grandfather was the founder of the Prudential, very old family, and there were five generations living all in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}North London{\*\xmlclose}
 at the time my second child was born. My great - great-grandfather was alive and he married again at ninety-two, he married again, and died at ninety-seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When they moved across the road in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Stapleton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  Hall Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, why did they move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because they wanted again - mum didn't like the tall house, she wanted a lower one, this was a - not so m
any stairs, much better arranged the house. More suitable for - labour, which you could get then easily then. We - we had three maids and one got fourteen pounds a year, the other got eighteen and the other got twenty. But they - they - well money went so
 much further then of course they were kept, doctors were paid for, in fact they became like the responsibility of the employer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So they needed a bigger house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Needed a bigger house, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I had three sisters - there were six of us - and two brothers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did they come, who was the eldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 My - the eldest was a brother. He was eighteen month older than I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So he was born in 1888?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You see, I was born in 18 - 1889 so he must have been born in 1887. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who came next?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Then I came next of course, eighteen months later. And two years and four months later came my sister Dorothy. And fifteen months later came my sister Hilda. Yes. And then seven years - in 1900 my sis
ter Phyllis was born. And in 1907 my brother Wes was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Just a year before you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How he was twenty when he married so he would be - it was eighteen months a
fter he was married Freddie was born, so that'd be twenty-one and a half. He'd be twenty-three, another eighteen months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He came from Clapton. And he was - an actuary in the Prudential.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was that the only job he ever had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's what he started doing from the beginning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. He wanted to go like his brothers, he'd got Naval blood in him, we came of a Devonshire family. He wanted to go to sea but his father died when he was - his fath
er was only forty-five and he was told he'd - it was his place to look after his mother. And he started in the Prudential at a very young age, fifteen. And was there until he retired at - fifty-nine. And he travelled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 All his life he worked as an actuary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he have any other job - even a part time job?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh no, no, no, except that he belonged to the - except that he belonged to the National Guard - during the war. The 1914 war. Yes. He tried to get into the Army, tried to get 
- but they wouldn't take him of course, he was - getting past the age. So he joined the National Guard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So after the war he went back to .....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh he was - he was - when I say he joined the National Guard, that was a part time job, he never left the Pru - oh he never }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 left}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  the Pru, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was he ever out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Never. Oh no. No. Not with his influence - not with the influence he had behind him anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 My mother was a 
year - let me see - she was just over a year older than dad, so she was born a year earlier in June 11th. His birthday was in September. Fifteen months difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He was twenty-three when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. And she would have been - yes, she'd be about twenty-four and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She came from Clapton. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Had she any jobs before she got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. No, she was at school up 'til nineteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did she ever work after she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So all her life she never worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, she never worked, no. No, she had people work for her. Because her parents saw to that. Although my father was only a young man on a small salary. Her people were well off and they - they bought her the house in St
apleton Hall Road, that was in her name. the second house was dad's. And - they provided her with a couple of maids and all coal and light bills were paid by them, for the first ten years. Gave them a good start. Too good a start, better to have bought th
eir own. I believe in people buying things of their own. Well they just have to but the things you don't value them I don't think the same as if you had to struggle a little bit to get them, then you value them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Her parents paid for the house and the servants for the first ten years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 For the first ten years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother ever take any part time job at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, no, she - her health broke down, I think she had the children too quickly and then she suffered from what they - she 
went to every brain specialist I thin, in London, her father took her, for what they called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 neurasthenia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
. They wanted her to - to have a trip round the world which he would have paid for, but she wouldn't go. But then - that went on for about twenty years 
I know, her nervous complaint, terribly highly strung she was, bless her, but - then she developed cancer of the breast and - and that - the minute she found she'd got that she forgot all about the other. I think she had too much time on her hands you see
, intelligent woman and I think her life of ease was bad for her. I think it was bad for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What happened after she got cancer of the breast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well after she got cancer of the breast of course things were getting more -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How many rooms were there in the house in Stapleton Hall Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh let me see - there was one, two, three on the top floor. Then there were two flights down, there was mother's bedroom, three four, five. Two bedrooms there. And down another couple of flights of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 stairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , o
h it was a tall house, five - there was the study and the drawing room, no - yes, the study and the drawing room, and then down another flight of stairs, funny they do - funny arrangements, a bathroom. So when you go in the front door at fifty-five I'll t
ell you what you find. When you go in the front door at fifty-five you've got the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 dining}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 room, which was our dining room. Behind that, the kitchen and the scullery. Well you go up the first flight of stairs and facing that is the bathroom, with a toilet i
n it, it's also a toilet down on the ground floor. Then you go up two more flights of stairs and there's two rooms. And - which was mother's bedroom and my bedroom. Then you go up another two flights of stairs and there's three rooms. Nursery. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 'Cos we were all young - pretty young together in the beginning you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
And now at that house if you pass it and look at it you'll see as you look up, at bar across the top window there. Only we had three up there but they - the people we - dad - when he - when we le
ft there dad was the first one to do it, he turned that house into three self contained flats. And that was - used to be our nursery and they had two bars removed but the other bar's still there. It brings back memories when I go by, I think - and - and t
hat was the - the house, but of course we wouldn't - when we moved again over to the other side we had still more rooms.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But in the first house there were about five bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It were about one, two, three - four. No, there was one, two, three a
t the top. Then there was mum's bedroom, four, and then - yes, there five bedrooms. Five bedrooms, two sitting rooms, a study. Kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It was a big house wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh they all - those - all big housed in Stapleton Hall Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Only to - servants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No relatives - no, we had an auntie come as companion to mum when her nerves broke down. My father's sister, she was there for about two 
years until she decided to get married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there ever any lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. I don't think they would have had lodgers in those days, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And apart from that auntie there weren't any relatives living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. Of course visiting, my dear }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 granny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  used to come quite regularly from Clapton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And your mother had help in the house didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 
Was her father - they paid for the first ten years, dad paid for it after of course.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How many servants were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
At different periods, sometimes we had two, we always had two. But - sometimes we had - there was three. With mother's - mum's companion, we used to have a companion, a mother's help. A mother's help because she used to make our underclothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who were the two who were always there, what were they called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The cook general, a cook general and the house parlourmaid. And they wore uniform you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And occasionally there'd be a mother's help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 There'd be - most times, most times. Until mother died practically there was a mother's help all the time. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did they all sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well they slept upstairs of course, where our nursery was, their bedroom was on that floor, their two bedrooms wer
e on that floor. And - our nursery was at the front room, they had the two back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When there'd be a third woman working where would she sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh she always - she - she used to have - now where did she sleep - at the top, in - I think they - can'
t remember but - shared them I think, yes. Two of them shared that was right, the two of them shared and she used to have a room go herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So there were just the two servants' bedrooms on that top floor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes, and they used to share, that'
s it, shared - two shared. And then she'd have one to herself. That's right, she had the one behind the nursery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did they all eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They - the servants you mean? Oh well, the - the one that looked after us, mother's help, of course always a
te with us. Always, we had our meals - we had - with the children, yes. Except on Sunday, except on Sunday when they would - dine in the kitchen. Or - and we had dinner with the family, always had dinner on Sunday with dad and mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Even the small ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, always. Except the babies of course, if there was a baby in arms she'd be with the - with the nurse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And the other two would eat in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there any special room where they could sit?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, th
ey used to have a - they used to have an evening a week out. A day a month. And every other Sunday. Used to have to fit it in. Wasn't too bad you know. And dad was very punctilious, I mean they had to be up early, it was usual for most because they had to
 
get the breakfast room or dining room ready for breakfast, all dusted and done before breakfast. But - he wouldn't let them sit up one minute after ten o'clock. He used to say to us when we were growing up, if you get anything you - get it yourself. If yo
u want anything to eat when you come in you get - do the washing up yourself. Maids have got to get up early in the morning and they've got to go up to bed at ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother supervise all the housework herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh she did a lot of supervising, she was a very good supervisor too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would she be the one who would actually tell them what to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She would say do this room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Of course they eventually had their regular duties you see that would go au
tomatically really. But if she was entertaining or anything like that of course she got her own shopping list ready and that sort of thing. And she had an at home once a month when - oh soppy isn't it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 It's terrible when I look back now, an At Home once a month when anybody could come, they - she'd have it printed leave cards - used to leave cards then. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
- And - she'd have this at home and the clergy would come poor man, he must have drunk about twenty cups of weak china tea. I think. Yes, every afternoon of
 his life because they all had their at homes on different days, and the clergyman would always come. He always came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So almost every day there'd be an at home for him to go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 For him to go to poor man. No wonder he got stout. I always look back and laugh at the funny things, they tickle me now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you feel at ease with the servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, we were ever so friendly. That - dad would have been angry but they used to shield us right and left. I'd be late in perhaps - I'd be a quarter
 of an hour late in you see, and dad'd go out - I remember one maid in particular who was there when I was courting. Mabel Massingham her name was, she was a sweet girl. He used to go out and he'd say, is Miss Gracie in? Yes sir, I think heard her go up t
o
 her bedroom a short time ago. I'd come in a quarter of an hour later, she'd be round the side entrance. Yes. You're father's been inquiring for you, I told him you were in bed, be quick and get upstairs and get your hat off. Oh yes, we were - ever - ever
 
so friendly with all the maids, they were all very sweet, we had - she had a cook generally occasionally they were a bit autocratic you could say. I'm not having you in my kitchen, you know, my - it was always my kitchen, never ours. But taking them as a 
whole the girls we had were nice girls from respectable homes. We had one or two bad ones.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What would usually be the reason for them leaving?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh there'd be various reasons, sometimes - perhaps one'd have a sick mother and they all - she wanted -
 wanted a job in the country, they liked a change sometimes you know. Or else you'd get somebody try - offer them more wages. Used to get that sort of thing going on. And - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 specially}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  the Jewish fraternity, they were very good - if they heard - you happened
 to know them and they knew you'd got a; good servant, they'd try to get them away. But actually we kept our servants a fair time. There was a period we went through when the - Queen's Jubilee was on, Queen Victoria's - when they got a bit out of hand, th
ey got - they had a lot of - of course they kept them in concentrat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 ion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 - like the concentration camps really it was I think, Alexandra Palace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They kept who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The - coloured soldiers that had come over for the - had come over for the - Jubilee. An
d - oh yes, proper concentration camps they were. We started concentration camps, we were the first person in the world to start that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They bought the soldiers over for the Jubilee?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They brought the - all those in the Indian and African - all th
ose that belonged, that were serving under the British Empire. They bought them over for the Jubilee and concentrated them, and these girls - some in Alexandra Palace, which I was forbidden to go up, but went. And - and of course the maids were supposed n
ot to go. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 Well they left a whole lot of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8657389  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 
illegitimate babies behind them - when they went.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So there was a bit of trouble with the servants over that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Over that. A lot - a lot. 'Cos you see, you couldn't really - you couldn't follow them about and 
that sort of thing, of course the mere fact of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 forbidding}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 them to go was the thing to make them go. It was silly thing to do. Because I went up and peeped at them too. But of course dad would have been very angry if he'd have known.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The servants would call your father sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh, sir - madam.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They'd call your mother madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, mother - madam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did they call you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Miss Gracie. Usually Miss Gracie, or master - master - Master Ron or Master John whatever it as you know, Master Wes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother give any moral guidance to the servants do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, a great deal. Yes. In fact I think there was a bit too much interference with the servants really, I mean, they used to take - they would - wore their own cloth
es when they went out of course, but sometimes mother would tell them, oh that's most unsuitable, and that sort of thing which of course I just don't think was the proper thing to do, but it was usual in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And of course they would be forbidden to do things like go up to see where the soldiers were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes, you - well - not much - there wasn't much - rulings on when they went out so long as they - were back at the proper time. You let them go at the time that they were suppo
sed to leave and - as - if they got back in time there weren't any questioned asked. Remember on one occasion only my mother going - she went - they'd gone up to the Lochs in Scotland and came back unexpectedly because the weather was so bad, she met the 
maid going out dressed in her best clothes. Then of course the - the balloon went up, yes, and she was given notice. They used to love to do that, try mother's clothes on when she was out. Poor things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It was hard to stop that because they'd be in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
They'd be in the house, oh yes. Oh yes, you had to - they - sometimes, after, when it became so much - so much more difficult to get maids the majority of people were glad, when the modern - modern work saving devices came in, because you neve
r had your house to yourself, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And it was a big responsibility I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Not only was it a big responsibility but you also never had your house to yourself, I mean, if you got - if you got a luncheon party or dinner party you had to stop 
talking when they came into the room because - you might be talking about something you didn't want them to particularly know. And of course gossip was rampant. All passed on and exaggerated of course. But really the majority of people I knew who had serv
a
nts were glad really when more modern saving houses came in and they were able to do without them - living in. So as you could do with daily labour. I mean to say the daily help too, always Fridays. We always had a char woman come in on Fridays. To do the
 real rough work, the real rough work. But - yes, and as the - really hard scrubbing work, 'cos the houses were very hard to keep clean, they hadn't got the modern saving devices you've got now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But your mother would give the servants moral guidance really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But in their free time would you say they were allowed to do more or less what they liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Absolutely what they liked, there's no question about that, anybody who says otherwise isn't telling the truth, and I mean I 
had a pretty wide experience really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When could they go out of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I told you they used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On their free time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On their free time, they'd leave at ten, after they got the breakfast things out of the way. They leave at te
n o'clock and they'd be home at ten at night. If they got the day out. The evening out they got out at half past five. Clear up the afternoon tea only and then they'd be in at ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They didn't do too badly I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Well it was only that they were under jurisdiction for greater part of their lives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On a working day they worked the whole day didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They did the whole day because we had bells from each room down on a large bell thing down in the kitchen with the name of the ro
om, and so the bell went they'd have to run and answer it, usually there was always somebody who had to do a lot of running about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of thing would you ring the bell for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well, might be for anything you might want. You might want a - som
e more fresh water in the bedroom, because of course in those days you - you had the large were basins that you washed in, you might want - you might have had an extra wash and want that emptied or something of that sort. And - well - an of course they an
swer - you always had a - a maid dressed in a black frock in the afternoon to open the door. The front door.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So really they couldn't pop out during the day to anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not much chance, no, not much chance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Or the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I told you, they always had an evening a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But other evenings they couldn't really go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 
No, not other evenings, they - they always had something to do, they'd either got some lights to clean or - 'cos it was - we had a lot of superfluous unnecessary stuff you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Silver and glass and stuff, a lot of it never used but it still had to be washed and kept clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So they might sit in the kitchen doing something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, oh they'd do that, sometimes they'd sit down and read. Oh th
ey could read if they weren't doing anything, in the - I mean they didn't - sometimes cook would have something that she wanted to prepare for the next day. And then perhaps she'd do it in the evening you see, she wouldn't have to do it the next day. Oh y
e
s, they read and they had their own books and that sort of thing. In fact I think some of the servants in those days were better educated than they are today, because they never read - never hear any - even the children don't read like they used to. So th
at - in some of them - improved themselves enormously, now an old lady has just died, here. She was ninety three. She started as a kitchen maid at fourteen. And she went right up to housekeeper in Lord somebody's house. My }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 word}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  she was worth - you - you nev
er meet that woman without she'd got something interesting to tell you. Wonderful life, 'cos of course she met all sorts of people in - you'd never have thought that she come from an entirely uneducated family because she was so - self educated. You see, 
s
he's like this woman that's just written this book. Yes. Yes. I mean, and there again you see that if you've got it up there, I've always - I agree with my dad in saying you can't keep a good man or woman down. They show it sooner or later. You find this 
- it - it comes out. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did the housework go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
In what way? Now first of all they'd be up the first thing to do when they got up in the morning was to go downstairs and get the breakfast room or dining room whatever dad was having - going to have his breakfast, clean }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 dusted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
. And of course there were black leaded grates that had to be done in those days. And it was really hard work. And it had to be done so you could see your face in it. And - that prepared for breakfast. Well then, after that
 - and cleaning the - sometimes they'd do that at night - clean the boots. Right through the family. They were left outside the - they used to take their boots off, leave them outside the bedroom and then they'd take them downstairs and clean them you see
.
 On one occasions - it's another funny bit - on one occasion, not when I was grown - quite grown up, oh about to be married - we had - we had got a new maid and she came to me she said, Miss Gracie, can you tell me where the master's boots are. So I said,
 where the master's boots are, there, I said, you've cleaned them. Oh, she said, I thought they were the little boys. He only took small size, my dad. He had tiny feet you see. Yes, I thought they were the little boy's.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So they might have to do that in the mornings sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But anyway they'd get the dining room ready?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
They - they'd get the room where we were going to dine, some call in the morning room, some had it in the dining room, according to the number of sitting rooms you'd got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And they'd serve up the breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then they'd serve up the breakfast. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 
And then of course dad would go off to the office, when we were younger the - our nurse, parlourmaid, house parlourmaid would get ours. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And clear it away. But - and t
ake it down to the kitchen and then the - I don't - the cook general and her between them they'd do the washing up. Then they'd the bedroom work to do you see, while cook gets on with preparing the lunch. They'd have the bedroom work to do which meant tha
t
 they'd got to go up and the beds needed some making then, they were nearly all feather beds. They all had to be stripped. Windows opened certain period of airing and that - the rules were laid down, pretty much the same everywhere. And then having made t
h
ose they would - dust of course. Dusting, all the dusting had to be done, that was done the morning's work was done, well then they'd go and change their dresses. For afternoon. Cook'd have a pretty easy time in the afternoon. She had the easiest - she'd 
the hardest jobs in the morning but really the easiest in the afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They'd change their dresses before they served the lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They'd change their dresses before the lunch, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then they'd serve up the lunch?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, they'd serv
e up the lunch and wait for the afternoon tea you see. Or visitors to call. They wore striped cotton frocks, all provided by the household, striped cotton frocks and caps in the morning and black frocks and frilled aprons in the afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The cook as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
All the - yes, all changed their clothes, all got into - into a black gown in the afternoon. Even the cook. But she used to have a little white ruffle, she'd be like a dowager by the time she was finished. Another funny thing I'll tell you one
 day we were without maids, I forget what it was over, without and they were both dismissed and we - went down to the Registry Office and ordered - they asked for two more. They sent us two sisters together. It was the funniest thing you ever saw. Smart -
 
wasn't in it. They came in, so mother said to them, go upstairs and settle yourself in and then will you come down and serve tea? Presently the strains of a violin came down - the strains of - the strains of a violin came downstairs. She said, where on ea
r
th is that coming from? Waiting for afternoon tea you see. Goes upstairs, there's one of them - it's an easel up in the bedroom with music on it and there she was playing away and the other one sitting back in her chair with her feet up on a - a cushion, 
ottoman cushion. So she says, what -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What happened t- those two?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh they went faster than they came in. So she said, what on earth is this? Oh she says, madam, I must do my practice in the afternoon. She dismissed them straight away, straight away. She said, well you needn't to unpack your boxes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And they went straight away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They went. Of course we were growing up then so we had to carry on until we got some more in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So in the afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They had a certain amount of leisure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So the cook would have prepared the dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
She would have - she would have got - after dinner you see she would have - after all the washing up was done, which they do between them, the washing up they do between them. Then she'd more or less t
he afternoon were - was hers. And until - because we had - we had another meal later because we overfed ourselves in those days. There used to be not only be a cooked breakfast, there'd be a cooked luncheon. And then afternoon tea and then cooked dinner i
n the evening.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So would she have prepared the evening dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well she - she could do it in her own time. As far as cook was concerned she more or less had charge of the kitchen. So long as the food was there and served up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It would depend on what you were having?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, exactly, it would depend on what we were having. And - at washing day Monday, when we had a washerwoman in, at fifty-five, our wash house was down below stairs, right down, with a flight of stairs }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 leading}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  up into the gar
den from the wash house, where they could hang the clothes out. Now that day we nearly always had cold dinner. You see, make it easy for them. And Fridays we usually had what I call a - I used to call it butterboy dinner but - it was boiled mutton and cap
er sauce 'cos it was easy. So they - because they - that was another half day because they would - we had the woman in to do the charring and the evening there were all the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 lights}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  to clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But every other day in the afternoon the cook would make the afternoon tea and they'd serve that up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then what would they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Then - then after that the afternoon'd be more - cook had more or less that to herself, not to go out, to read or do any needlework of her own 'cos sometimes they had
 needlework and darning and that sort of thing of their own to do. But then she could probably retire to her bedroom. You wouldn't see anything more of her until it was time for her to prepare for the evening meal. The housemaid nearly always got tea. Coo
k
 didn't have anything to do with that. No, no. Just a matter of making tea and very thin bread and butter you know. And they had the same food as we had. There was no difference made in our house or not in my grannies or anybody that I visited. Now we hea
r a lob about I read in books all that nonsense - perhaps some people did do it, I don't know, but not in the middle class type of people that I met.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So when your mother or the cook was ordering the food she'd order enough for the servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 For -
 for - and the servants. And the servants. And - dad would cut the - off the joint on Sunday for the maids, exactly the same as - if - he was cutting off for us. And they'd come in and take it on the tray and take it outside you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was all the housework done in the morning - all the work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
The majority. Except the bright cleaning and things like that - that was done in the evening. Yes, that sort of thing. Oh yes, the house - maid part of the housework was done by - after luncheon time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said the woman came in on Mondays to do the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did she spend there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 All day. All day. And all we had to pay her was five shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did she have her midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes. She had her midday meal and 
tea. Yes, and then - then - and one of the maids had the ironing to do afterwards, what ironing there was to do, yes, and in those days we'd wear as many as four or five petticoats all having to be got goffered you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that ironing would make an awful lot of work during the rest of the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well it would make a lot for Tuesday and Wednesday, they were practically occupied doing that. Yes. Practically the whole - she'd be - 'cos there were a lot of girls. 'Cos where there were girls there we
re more, naturally. And - yes, she would on Tuesday and Wednesday, she'd be practically ironing all day. Apart - I expect she got her ordinary little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 duties}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  done. Oh they worked hard. Badly paid and worked hard, there's no doubt about that. But they had good homes I suppose some of them had bad ones but - no, of all those that know -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Most of them would eventually get married wouldn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, a lot of them got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did they get to meet young men to marry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well their days out 
you see. They went out every other Sunday, then they went out daily, they met people, they - they went to theatres and things like that. Music halls mostly because they were two houses a night, you see, from seven 'til nine the first house, then from a qu
a
rter past nine 'til quarter past eleven. So they used to go to first house. And of course the public house, another thing you see in those days, that was the curse of that period, the public houses were open all day and all night if they wanted to, there'
s
 no restriction on it. And the consequence was that a great deal of drinking went on because drink was cheap. You could buy a - a half pint glass of beer for tuppence you see. That I deplored, that was bad, but honestly there was a lot of drunkenness but 
it was usually at one period only - on Friday night, the night they got paid. Friday and Saturday night you'd hear them coming along singing, in their drunken songs, which rather spoilt things. Of course -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 My husband's aunt said that then you used to see people lying drunk in the street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh you did. You did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 
You don't ever see that - well, you do once now and again, very, very occasionally. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh you did, there was a lot of drunkenness, that was the great }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 curse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  of the age, the drunkenness, and it was because it was so cheap. It was - and of course they was - as you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396938\charrsid8657389 say,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 they hadn't a lot of places to go to, well they also went to the music halls, they'd get up in the galleries for six-pence. They - but I don't suppose, they - they met more people in a pub you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And occasionally the maids would acquire a boyfriend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. And - and perhaps the mistress would be very interested in her courtship and - would help her towards getting her trousseau and that sort of thing, if she was a good se
rvant, of course everything depends on what they - what value they gave you as to how you treated them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If everything was all right the mistress wouldn't disapprove?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. Oh no, at least some mistresses might have done, I believe my mother-in-
law was rather a bad mistress. She pulled their hair down if they did it fashionably. Make them scrag it back off the back of their head - to the back of their head. Of course, she had a lot of sons and - maybe that was the reason. Another funny part, I'l
l
 tell you what she did once, she was living over in Harvey Road in Crouch End and she wanted a maid to be with the boys, my husband was one of a lot of brothers. And they were all grown up and her husband was a very handsome man. Well she put an advertise
m
ent in the paper - good cook general wanted, slight affliction not objected to. My dear, you never saw - there was a queue around the hall and back again. When I think of that day, I had to call in in the afternoon, 'cos I was married and got a youngster 
t
hen. And never have I - I don't know who - what on earth was wrong. And I saw this whole crowd of - and in the she took one with a - some - with a wonky eye. So - I said to her, what are you frightened of? Pulling her leg. What are you frightened of mum? 
Frightened of losing dad? She says, certainly not. 'Cos they were very devoted. She said, certainly not, it's not daddy I'm afraid of, it's those boys of mine. I'm not going to have any more good looking servants here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Had she had a bit of trouble?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I think she had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who did they mending of the family thing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh usually the mother's help or - the - which was the - one who did ours any rate, did all the mending.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever do your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. We were taught at school. We were tau
ght at school and we'd have - we'd have prizes for the best darner and that sort of thing, but we didn't have to do it at home. Although we weren't allowed to be idle. We did knitting, we did crochet. We did quite a lot of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 crocheting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would it be useful knitting and crocheting or just decorative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh no, no, no, useful in as much as we'd make all the doilies for the table and that, because they used doilies a lot and chair backs and things like that. Oh yes, and petit point work. A lot of artistic
 - a lot of artistic crafts we learnt really. And dad would say if he saw us sitting doing nothing, can't you find something to do? Couldn't bear to see you sitting idle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you never actually did the mending of the clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, we did in latte
r years of course, as the servant shortage became a menace, we had to. And mind you we could do it because we'd learnt at school. In all good schools of course you all - except for the one. When we first came here there was only one council school, they c
a
lled it the tin school. It was in Stourbury Road. Where I - when that went I was still quite small, they put on the - they built Woodstock Road which is now there, that's a lovely school, Woodstock Road. That was the first good council school there was. A
l
l the other schools were paid schools. All had to pay for all of them. There were no - no schools except that one. But they ran it on - grammar school lines and it - both boys and the girls, instead of having houses they had what they called forms, forms 
o
ne, two - a, b, c, and d, for the - the one. And then there'd be another form you see going de, f, go, all according - graded according to intelligence. In the schools I went to we had to being home - every night with our home work we had to bring home wh
at we'd got to do, how many hours or minutes we'd got to take on it and had it signed by our father to say we'd done it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You bought this home with a piece of paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Bought home a form, typed out. Typed out - the mistress had done, form mistr
ess. History, supposing we got history, arithmetic and English. Well that - that - that time that we should take you see, an hour and a half, which we were supposed to leave it once we'd done that hour whether completed or not and she - at the end it had 
to be signed by your father or your mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How many hours would it run to in an evening?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
About - well you see there - you went to school in the mornings from nine 'til one. The afternoon you could either stay at home and do your homework or go 
to school and do it, you see. So that would be another three and a half hours. That's how they did it there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 But when I went to Cusacks College it was different. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You went all day to school, that is you went from nine to twelve. And back again two - two 'ti
l four. Well then you'd have three perhaps - three hours, two and a half, three hours homework to do when you got home in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Although you knew how to do mending and so on you never had to do it in the early days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Not in the early days anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about pillowslips and tablecloths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 All done - all the - bought really. They were all bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who would be responsible for repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of repairs? Do you mean structural repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Something wrong with the roof?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh well then you sent for the builders to repair - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would your father ever do anything of that nature himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He would - he made a bit - he didn't know anything about - about that sort of thing, he was definitely a ma
thematical man, a professional man. And the schools where like that. At school there where I went to notice outside for the daughters of gentlemen only, that meant professional gentleman. Then you'd have another school in which they'd take }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 trades people\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  
daughters and that sort of thing, lot of silly - that's snobbery. But they did keep them - they kept them a certain selectness about them, it didn't mean they looked down on the other schools but simply that they chose people who wanted their children to 
be academic sent them to a professional school you see, and those who wanted them to be more useful sent them to - they all had to pay and the fees were very much the same. Not that - not - not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But if you were a tradesman yourself, a shopkeeper or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You couldn't - you couldn't enter them in a professional school. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So he'd no hope of becoming a professional man himself had he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - well he had because even then they had evening classes. You see they started evening class
es, they - you had all private tutoring, all sorts of - lot of private tutors about in those days. Lot of people wouldn't send their children to school at all - until they were really old enough to go to university. And a lot of the people lived around he
re because it used to be a wonderful neighbourhood for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 There was usually a sort of servant who was responsible for the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes, responsible for the children, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What would you call her, was she a nanny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well we never called them nanny, we used to call the - Wes's one we used to call her Nurse too that's all. Nurse. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What were her duties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well her duties was essentially to look after the babies. She'd look after - she'd look after the needlework f
or the baby. Oh yes, she'd look after that, she would do all that for the - for the child. That - everything - and she'd - it depended if - if the child was very young and on the bottle or anything like that then she would look after - see to all that, ye
s
, until the child was old enough to take table meals. And then - and then of course she'd simply go down to the kitchen and get what she thought the child should have. And bring it up - up to the nursery. And then she'd take the child out, you see, perhap
s for a couple of hours in the park.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was she on duty }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 all}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  day as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Practically - no, she had two hours in the - in the afternoon off. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did she have any other regular off time like the other servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Yes, she went out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What happened on her day off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh then - then - usually - you see you must remember that - time I remember I was the eldest, I was growing up, usually mother herself would look after the - the baby or those that weren't able to - be left entirely on their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Until what age would the nurse be looking after the child entirely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Entirely? Ooh - - until he went - until he went, 'til he actually - entirely, until he actually went to school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 During that time when the nurse was looking after the child what time would you spend with your parent, when would you see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
What the - what the baby you mean? Oh well, mother's going probably, bathing time, perhaps in the morning. In the morning she'd see him bath - and of course she'd see him perhaps for an hour or two before the evening before went to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This would be regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
It'd be regular, yes. And of course they'd be brought down if they had visitors or anything for a short period. Nurse'd come down with it if it was in arms. And stay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother ever help to dress you or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - she - I suppose she did in the very early age. To some extent. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 
Yes, she certainly chose our clothes and she certainly went out with us and bought it as we were getting older of course, she went out and bought our hats and our underclothing and all that herself. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Most of the shopping you see, but then you'd be getting - shops delivered in those days, she'd simply - send one of the maids down we'll say to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 Wilson\rquote s
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 on the Broadway. It was a wonderful shop in those days. Or down to Halls, we've been there a great number of - years, and still is at Stour Green Road, and - they send up anything she wanted, a dozen or so of anything she wanted and then she'd choose it,
 yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would she ever actually dress the children in the mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I've known her to, yes, I've known her to, especially if they haven't been well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about bathing in the evening, would she ever }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 come in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  and wash you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sometimes, sometimes, not often - not very often, nearly always the maid did the bathing and she'd come in afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your mother did see the children every evening regularly before bedtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh always saw us once a day, yes. Very often before we went to school too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would she or your father ever play games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, some - but not so much games but we - dad'd sing, we'd have musical evenings and of course we - all learnt the piano and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But when you were very small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Playing games - I can remember dad tickling me, yes, oh yes. Oh yes. And I can remember youngsters of course, younger than I, they used }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 clamber}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  on his knee. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would your mother and father ever actually take them shopping with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh y
es. Often. Often. Oh all of us, she'd take all three 'cos we were all close together, if we were going out to - if we all wanted new shoes for school and that sort of thing she'd take the three of us there and let us have some sort of choice. Not entirely
, she didn't approve of what we chose, w- couldn't have it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ever take you on outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. We went six weeks every year directly school broke up, we'd go down a greet deal of our school holidays was - spent in Dawlish in Devon. Dad wo
uld hire a couple of ponies for Fred and I, we were the - earliest ones there, and - a horse for himself and we'd go out riding and that sort of thing, oh yes, we - we had a lot of holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you go for outings as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sometimes. Yes, I can 
remember going on the boat with dad many times to the - all the way - all day down to Cliftonville and that sort of thing on the old Royal Sovereign. Oh yes. And he'd go to school sports and that, of course we had open air school sports. Yes, and they'd g
o in - take us perhaps up to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 High}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 gate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Woods where we'd play rounders and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you saw your parents before bedtime where would you see them, in the nursery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Down in - usually in the dining room, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he children have any little tasks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
All of us, oh yes. Yes. We wouldn't get our pocket money until we'd done them. Oh various little tasks we had to do, now let me think of some of the things I had to do. Perhaps it might be - it might be something to do with needlewor
k, it might be - crocheting, it might be petit point or it might be that dad had given me something to read - something to read and then tell him afterwards but at times - and sometimes, when we got older, we'd have to do some dusting. And he'd go round w
ith a silk handkerchief to see whether - with a white silk handkerchief.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 To give you a bit of training?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Oh yes, we were a certain amount of help I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about the little boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not the boys so much. No, they didn't have an
y tasks to do, not even clean their own boots. Not at - not while they were at home. Of course - they did later on because the servant question began. Then they had to. And they did it very well when they had to too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever have to shine the cutlery or this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, see our mum wouldn't - they thought we - - probably think we'd be at some harm or other if we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did you go on being given little tasks to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Right up 'til the time I got married. All the tim
e I was at home, I think, and - and they got more and more after I'd gone because the servant question began to get worse and my sisters had more to do at home than I did. For instance, I was never allowed - never did a bit of cooking although my husband 
said that I was the best cook that he'd ever come across. I'd never cooked an egg before I got married. But my sisters did - as time went on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If some of your younger brothers and sisters were at home after they left school did some of them actually have to do the cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, the girls did, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And what did the boys have to do to help out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I couldn't tell you that at all. To begin my brother Fred wasn't brought up at home. When we came to 55 Stapleton Hall Road, which was from a little house into a big one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Fred was the oldest boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Fred - yes, my - the eldest one. He fell very ill with inflammation of the lung and mum had got me, a baby, you see there was only eighteen months between us, another one on the way, and grann
y came up one day and saw her and she said, you can't go on like this, I'm going - I'm taking the boy back with me. And - she grew so fond of him, 'cos mother was an only child, and every year it was put off and put off and he finally stayed with her alto
gether, so he was brought up with her after he was about two and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So in a way you were the eldest?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I was the eldest of them. They all said I was spoilt but I wasn't. Yes, I was the eldest one at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And after the youngest by left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 
Yes, after he left school you see, he - he was at school until very late and of course he was going into the Prudential any way, he was at Torrington, he was - he started at Torrington when it was a small school in Torrington Park, afterwards 
of course it became the big college, it was still there when he left there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
He - when he was at home, no, he didn't have any duties 'cos dad had - mother died when he was quite youngish - before he left school. And he - dad had a housekeeper. So she did everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were quite small at home did the older children help the younger children with things they found difficult?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, we played about, get up - got up to - got up to all sorts of mischief but we didn't have any tasks to do. No. 
I can't ever remember helping anybody. We were all too near. You see there was only eighteen months - but there's only two years and four months between Dorothy and I. And only a year and three months between her and the next one, we're all too near an ag
e. Oh no, didn't - didn't help - didn't help in that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were the younger children expected to help the older children in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 
Dad - in fact, dad used to separate us up when we got older and were at our final schools, instead of sending us all to the same school he sent me to - me to the Stroud Green, Hornsey High, Dorothy to Holloway college and Hilda to Owens. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 All different schools we went to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Why did he do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because he said we put our heads together and made each other l
ate fore school and he thought we were better with separate reports. So he divided us up. He was that type of man you know. Went to all different schools - finally. He said, one won't get the other into mischief.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were at school what time }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 did}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  you have to go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh early. When were very small - when we were very small we were all in bed by half past six. And then - and then I went to school, we'd do our homework, we were given a - according to two and a half hours or three hours whatev
er it was and we did our homework, perhaps we wouldn't be finished until eight. We'd have to be in bed by nine, I can never remember being up any later than that until I got really - passed into - into my teens.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who put the children to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh maids when they were small, but we put ourselves to bed - well - to bed when we got older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At what age would you say you started putting yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - I should say about ten. Yes, about ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the children share a bedroom or a bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, we shared a bedroom. We had this one great big bedroom, all separate beds. Because we used to wake up and - youngsters it's terrible to get them awake now, but we'd wake about half past four or five in the morning and we'd start singing a r
ound, and old dad'd come up, rush upstairs, I'll knock your heads together if you don't give off - stop that noise. We used to do - start singing, see one - one starting and the other going on and then the other one. I bet it was a terrible row we made.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you all had your own beds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 All had our own beds, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did your mother and father sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They slept underneath - they slept together in the - in the bedroom, front - front bedroom underneath. And when they moved over to Staplet
on Hall Road they didn't so much after mother got so ill. She then - 'cos the bedrooms there - it was a bigger house altogether, every bedroom had a dressing room. Well - dad slept in the second bedroom with my brother and mother slept on her own in the b
ig bedroom and then there was a dressing there that - that she used to wash herself in the mornings 'cos her toilet used to take her a long time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But in the first house all the children slept in one room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In one - one big bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, no, 'cos Wes wasn't born, we were living - we were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And the eldest boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
He was with grandma. Yes. So that the - yes, four - four girls - of course it was three girls for a great number of years because there so many years
 difference between Hilda and Phyl and then Phyl came along. By that - by that time she was seven when I married, I was the first to go, she was a little bridesmaid. And by that time we did - did - did Phyl sleep in our room - then - yes, yes, she did. Sh
e was in mother's room until she was about three. Yes, she slept in mother's room and then she was with us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then the youngest little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then the - he - he used to have a bedroom to himself on a - of course when he was very young, but -
 later on he - he used to sleep in - with dad and he shared the bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said there was a bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Bathroom. Never been without a bathroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How often - did the children use the bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How often would they bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well probably they'd - twice a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they bath themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When they got older - older. Of course when they were small they didn't bath themselves. But when they got older oh yes they }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 bathed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  them selves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About twice a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember what days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Usually Friday was the favourite time. Yes. Friday was the favourite time and Monday or Tuesday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When would clean clothes be given out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Every Sunday morning, little piles. Little piles. Yes. Yes, every Sunday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said there was a dining room didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. A drawing room and a dining room, we dined in the dining room. We used that most of all, the drawing room wasn't used a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 fearful}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  lot except for entertaining. 'Cos we had a piano in both.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At what age did the children start eating with the grown ups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh well we - I suppose - you see with - Phyllis started very early 'cos of the servant question was getting worse and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 worse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  of course when she came along. She practically dined with them from the time she went - oh about seven or eight. She did - but, we started }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 dining}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  with them regularly I should think - oh probably when we were nine or ten. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So before that where did the children eat their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the nursery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 There was an exception to this on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On Sunday we always came down to dinner. Always for dinner on Sunday and it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you mean the midday dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I mean - yes - because you see the big meal on Sunday was always midda
y. Not - we didn't late dinner, we had supper. Usually something cold, but - 'cos the servants were out, some of them were out anyway. And - we had this big dining room table that I told you of, that we made a stage of on one occasion, it had got lovely }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 little}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 ridge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  underneath it. Oh how we've }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 laughed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 at that since we've been grown up. Well dad would say, if we didn't - didn't eat fat, you've got to eat your fat with your meat. You've got to eat your fat, you won't have any more, and I'll bring it up again 
tomorrow, you'll eat it tomorrow if you don't eat it today. We were getting the fat somehow and putting it underneath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What happened to - then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The maids - they were all in - all in - we always had them on our side, they'd clear it all away for 
us afterwards. We were only talking about that it's funny, Dolly and I the other evening, what we used to dad, dad used - and we had a cane you know. We had a cane at the end of the table and then when we used to get - but - he used so say, speak when you
're spoken to. We weren't allowed to chatter at meals you know. And - wait for - if you wanted a second helping you had to jolly well wait to be asked if we wanted. You couldn't grab like the kids do now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On Sunday you ate in the dining room, when you were small and ate in the nursery was any adult with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, always. Always. Well I mean, the maid or whoever was in charge. And she was especially chosen you know for her - for her job. We were taught table manners.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She taught you table manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. See 'cos mum wouldn't engage anybody who hadn't been trained, not for that particular post. And - oh yes, we were trained in table manners, we were trained in courtesy too. That was my dad always said, courtesy costs nothing, and it o
pens the door to many opportunities. And we were taught to respect out elders whoever they were. I mean, it wouldn't be any good me going home to my father like they do today and saying the teacher did this or the teacher said that, he'd say, well - you d
eserved it or she wouldn't have done it. Never supported you in - insubordination in school. And he was right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you'd be able to sort of put up with life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, yes. You - you - even if it seemed to be unjust you were taught that they were ol
der than you and therefore you were - you had no redress. You jolly well put up what - can't be cured has got to be endured.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It seems hard at time but life is like that anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I think that you've got to learn to take rebuff. You've got to,
 I mean, this business of the parents running up to the school every time that - there's something radically wrong with it. All wrong. Of course the schools are different now, the teachers themselves are so coarse and loud and vulgar, I hear them at Woods
t
ock Road there, it wouldn't have been tolerated when I was young, the teachers were properly trained. We used to have pupil teachers but they were of course under the jurisdiction of the more fully trained teachers. No, as a matter of fact those days - as
 
far as scholastic things are concerned, I think we've retrogressed not progressed. Definitely retrogression. Because there's no thoroughness in it, I mean, a lot of science has been introduced to a curriculum - that was already too big. They don't teach E
nglish - properly, they don't learn parsing and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 analysing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
, you can't ask a child today why she's written that sentence. Why she hasn't used an adverb, she couldn't tell you. Even at the good schools. That's the educational standard, instead of going up, all
 going up the scale it's been a process goes up and leaves down. That's been a sort of - middling sort of business had education and I think it's going on today. The same thing. There's no - the teachers for the - I've got two - two nephews, both teachers
,
 and - they say the same thing, that it's most important thing is the first teaching. And the teacher should be highly qualified who first takes the primary schools, but they're not, not today. Used to have to do seven years training you see. But not - we
 want - that's what we want because the foundations all wrong.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But in your case the nurse would teach you courtesy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, manners and table manners and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you say courtesy you mean seeing that other people had what they wanted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Not - not always - not grabbing for yourself, you learn to see that somebody else was satisfied first. Well manners, just ordinary good manners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When the nurse sat down at the table with you did she have her own meal as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 O
h yes. Oh yes. Oh yes. At the same table requisite, exactly the same as ourselves. Mother'd go round sometimes to see if the table was properly laid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because you were supposed to know how that should be as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Exactly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did they use for cooking in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What - in what way, what do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well gas or a range?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh a range, great big range. They had a gas stove later on, I know there - well we had a gas stove in the other house too, we had both, but mostly the - it was range cooking you see 'cos we used to roast our meat on a stick you see. You turn a key.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 As a rule - breakfast was at eight o'clock. Eight o'clock for us, because we had to be at school at nine. And nine o'clo
ck for dad because he didn't have to be at the office 'til ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And what about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
And mother usually took a - most of the time mother had her breakfast up in bed. Either - even later on than the girls, my sisters, did it for her, when 
the servants began to get scarce. Even then she had her breakfast in bed. Didn't get up much before eleven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What food would you have for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - cereal and - porridge as a rule to start with in the winter. Some sort of cereal later on, w
hen the hotter weather came and - sometimes, it would depend how old we were, some - the older ones would probably have egg and bacon. The same as dad and mother had or a - perhaps a boiled egg. Toast and marmalade, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What would you drink with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh it depended, we could have what we liked as far as that was concerned. When we got older of course we got - some of them liked chocolate, some of them liked coffee but - I never drank coffee I always had tea. And milk for the younger children o
f course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would breakfast be different on certain days such as Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, practically the same. Not much different. Sometimes they'd have kidneys or something like that and a few more changes on Sunday when there was more leisure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When was lunch eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Usually one o'clock, in the midday. Because we'd got to get back to school you see by - because we'd got to get back to school by two.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your father come home to lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Never. Only Saturday he came home to lunch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So there'd be the mother and the children for lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. And the maids themselves. O anybody else we happened to ask or come to see us you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of food would you have for lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh all sorts of things, some days we'd have - as I
 tell you got a boars head and boiled that a with caper sauce and perhaps another day - steak and kidney pudding. All with sweets afterwards you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 Plum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  duff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And Sunday lunch would be different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. A little bit more - a few more extras,
 of course tea'd be the great thing on Sunday. Oh yes, even after that big dinner, always tea, there was watercress, there were - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 shrimps}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , prawns, winkles. Oh dear - and trifles. All for tea, oh yes. All this for - the tea'd be later on Sundays, six o'cloc
k you see, we'd have tea at six and - we never knew who was going to pop in on Sunday, people - visitors and relations had a way of popping in on Sunday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But though you had a big tea on Sunday you still had a later supper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, no, no, no. No. N
o, you see, really it was a sort of high tea and going to bed on a Sunday night you could have a sandwich or - a cup of tea or cup of coffee or anything you fancied.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that was why it was really a big tea on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, on Sunday. It was really as much for the servants sake as anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But the rest of the week there'd be afternoon tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Afternoon tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you have for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Little tiny thin slivers of bread and butter that you could blow away like that and -
 fancy cakes and of course very often a homemade cake, we had a homemade cake made every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your father wasn't there for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So would that be your mother and the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That'd be mother and children, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The children who weren't at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Yes. Mother sometimes wouldn't have it herself. She wouldn't always have afternoon tea, she had a cup but she wouldn't have anything to eat with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time would the evening meal be during the week;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About seven. Between half past six and seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would your father be there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Unless he was going anywhere then the family would sit down, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of food would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh, steak, chips, sweet, cheese and biscuits and that sort o
f thing. Just the ordinary meal like we'd have now on a Sunday, only in the ordinary - that the sort - and chops perhaps some nights.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If your father was going out, he wasn't sitting down to dinner, when would he eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well he'd probably have it 
out. Probably be dining out with somebody and when he came in he'd probably just have a - a hot drink and a sandwich if he wanted it or he might not have anything at all, depending what time he came in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And on Sunday there was just the high tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother or the servants make any bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
At one - in the early days, yes. But - not for a long time, bread was so good, you could buy - go to the bakers and buy it hot, tuppence ha'penny a two pound loaf. And they'd weigh it and if 
it didn't quite weigh right they used to call it the dunican and he used to put a piece of - nice crusty bread on it. We used to love it. That's right, yes, well that's how they started it. But - they used to - sometimes actually gone - of course towards 
t
he end when servants got so difficult we used to have to go and give the order in at the grocers and do a bit of shopping for mother ourselves, when we were growing older, and - the times I've been up there, got the bread all hot, then weighed and this du
nican - as I call it, crust, used to come home and put thick butter on it. And - used to love it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So only in the early days did they make any bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh very early days, yes. They didn't think it was worth it because it was good and the milk was g
ood, they used to bring it round in the big urns you know and you go to the door with a jug and they'd - bale it out in a pint can into that - it was thick with cream. And in the park, Finsbury Park, of course the seasons were different then, we used to h
a
ve real winters and real summers, and in the park they had two beautiful peacocks on that island and - lovely swans in the lake. And the boats were painted every year, a different colour. Oh it was pretty. And of course every Sunday it was church parade -
 
the whole of that drive round the park was filled with victorias and traps and carriages and the ladies would get out all beautifully dressed after coming from church and parade round that lake. But it was beautiful, you know, we had - it was much nicer, 
you go in and see a lot of hooligans there now, it seems to be so tragic. See it like that after all those years. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother or the servants ever make any jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, we made that. Oh yes, granddad'd go up to the fruit market, Covent G
arden, and he'd bring home great big baskets of fruit and they'd make that into - bulk of it and make jam.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who would make it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh the cook generally. Mother would have sometimes. Oh yes, I've known her to do it, and at - at Christmas time anothe
r extraordinary thing she always used to insist on doing - we'd make our Christmas puddings a lot of them and they'd - they'd boil them all in the copper, downstairs in the wash house, well they used to boil them in there. Well she wouldn't let anybody to
u
ch a Christmas puddings, not until she became very ill, poor thing, she had to give it up the latter years of her life, but previously to that she'd - do all that mixing on - about a month before Christmas. Make her Christmas cake and make her Christmas p
uddings, and they were puddings too I can tell you, beautiful. Put plenty of brandy in you know to keep them and they'd sometimes we'd have one on the top shelf of the pantry, the pantry was very big in those days, the following Christmas, still there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did she bottle any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
She didn't do that herself, no. Sometimes we'd - if we got a good cook we would - who was fond of a little bit of extra work she would. But we nearly always ate fresh fruit, we didn't do a lot of bottling. Gra
nddad would come up every Saturday, we used to listen for the bell to go, we had a big bell that rang - at about eleven or twelve o'clock - about twelve o'clock on Saturdays. He was a darling, we'd all rush down there and he'd be with a great big straw ma
r
ket bag. One bag full of fruit. And of course we'd be on the fruit and me grandmother'd say, oh - dad, I wish you wouldn't do it, they won't eat any luncheon. Pears, apples, grapes. Oh we had good food. Oh we were brought up on good food. So that's why we
'
ve worn pretty well. Good constitutions. Yes. Introduced when you're young. Yes. That's it - that's what the doctor said to me, you've got such good bone structure. When I - when he was examining me only lately. But it is - I think it is that, it's the ea
r
lier - and you see, there were no fertilizers used, it was all natural food. It doesn't matter what you spend now you can't get the quality food we got then. You see, animals them - selves are not fed the same. They're introducing all this tinned meat but
 you know real - you can't get real quality in meat without any fat. You can't. It's impossible. People won't eat it so there you are. They'd rather kill themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ever do any pickling in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sometimes. Yes, grandma did most of 
it. She - grandma lived over in - Clapton, in Cricketville Road she lived there I don't know how many years. And - she had one maid, there was only just her and granddad and old Lizzie her maid, and - she'd do the pickling, she'd do most of that and she'd
 bring it up for us you see. And at Christmas, the turkeys, we used to have - she used - granddad used to have two turkeys from this Costers Farm in Norfolk and they'd be delivered at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 granny
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  and she'd feather them, pick them - and stuff them, get them all
 ready to put in the oven. Then she'd cook one and they'd bring one up to us. So the maids never had anything to do like that at Christmas time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was any wine ever made?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. We'd - but dad wouldn't let us drink wine until we were fair age an
d he - he was very - he used to warn us very much against drinking port. I remember when we first began to go out to Christmas parties, he used to say, now, port, I don't want you to drink port. A little drop of light wine but he used to tell us how much,
 
we did do what he told us. Because he'd say, there's all - and he'd have warned us against all sorts of dangers when we first began to go out with boys. Watch they didn't drop tobacco in your glass and that sort of thing. Yes. We were warned of all that. 
Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It was your father who would talk to you about things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh dad would say that, and my granddad too. And I'd say, oh I can take care of myself. And he'd say, no you can't - there's no girl yet that can take care of herself, under 
certain circumstances. And he'd warn you of the dangers and he - in a sort of delicate way, not all this pornographic stuff we get stuck on the television, which is a menace, absolute menace. And he - he watched the literature we read too. Because I remem
ber reading the \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 and having to hide it, only - used to lock myself into the toilet and read it there and then hide it. See, 'cos he would have been horrified. Of course that's a classic and there's nothing in it like you know the youngsters use t
oday. But he was particular - about the literature we read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And some wine was made in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, we didn't make wine. Oh no, no, no. We didn't make it. Oh no, it was always bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you'd be allowed to drink some?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, at Christmas time, when we were getting - when we were getting older. I think I had my first glass of wine when I was twelve I think.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you never made any wine or beer in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Bo. Oh no, we didn't do anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother make any herbal medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - brimstone and treacle. Yes, we had a big white bowl, china bowl, and it used to be made - brimstone and treacle. And it was on the top shelf and they'd make enough to last twelve months you know for the lot of us. And it'd
 be covered over with a - with a sort of net cloth, on the top shelf of the pantry. And put - and then we'd have - we'd be dosed with that and there wasn't that other awful stuff that I never could take, wait a minute - oh dear - dad used to give us -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Castor oil or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh no, I couldn't touch that ever. Even in hospital they had to stop that game with me, I used to vomit it up directly it touched my mouth. No, what was the other stuff, there was brimstone and treacle - oh licori
ce powder. Horrible stuff. We were dosed - you see - when we've had our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 bath}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 bath night}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  every Friday night. We used to have a dose of some open - opening medicine. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your mother made this herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 With a big wooden spoon. Yes, she used to
 make it. Or granny. Or granny. Or - she did most of it don't worry, mum didn't have to do much. Grandma did so much for her. She was wonderful, we went away one year to Devon and when we came back every curtain in the place had been replaced with beautif
u
l - because there were a lot of white Madras curtains in those - all - from top to bottom, it did look a picture. Everything - and a huge dresser we had in the kitchen and - she'd - she'd replaced, I think she said it was ninety-one slightly chipped artic
l
es, she'd thrown them all away and replaced them with all new ones, oh she was a wonderful granny. Oh she was beautiful granny, I loved my granny. I nursed her for her last two years, she died with pernicious anemia in the end, 'course it's curable now, b
u
t it was incurable then. And she was an angel, absolute angel. No beggar ever went to her door that was turned away and granddad used to say to her - Ann, you're imposed on, they send - 'cos there's so many of them came, one sends the other and some of th
em are jolly sight better off than you, she'd say, I don't care John. If one of them's genuine I'm satisfied. The was - she was the sweetest thing. So sweet - and so beautiful to look at.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you grow any fruit or vegetables in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. - 
We didn't have such a - well the - 78 was larger but we preferred it as a garden - with a big lawn and flowers. Then the garden at 55 was - got large laburnum trees in. They were - practically filled it and at the top of the garden when we went there gran
dpa had a - a proper brick built slated roofed - summer house built for us, for we children. Like a dolls house. And the floor was covered with coconut matting and we'd stained glass windows in it. Which occupied a lot of the garden you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It must have been beautiful?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
It was really, I've never seen anybody else with one like it. Not since. He had built specially for us. And we could go out there and make as much noise as we liked you see. It didn't make any different to anyone in the house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said your grandfather bought and vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, every week - every week. Meat - fish - vegetables - fruit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever have any tinned or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No - don't ever remember having anything tinned in t
he house at all. Not - not - don't ever remember it. I don't think we would have done because - they were such believers in fresh food. You see. No - that came later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who looked after the garden then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh we used to have a man come in to do the garden. - Me dad was no gardener.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How often would the man come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh about - sometimes - it depends, sometimes - sometimes in the year he'd come several times a week and in the wintertime perhaps he'd only come just once a to tidy up during the week or to a do a bit of pruning of the trees. That sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they keep any sort of hens or anything like that in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. But we always had a dog.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was that just a pet or a guard dog?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 A pet, No, a pet. Pet. They were pets
 too. We had one dog, dad used to take him out on the - we used to do cycling. He used to cycle a lot, I used to go out with him sometimes cycling too when I got older. But he went off one day, every Sunday morning he used to go cycling and - Chips, that 
was the name of our - that little fox terrier - followed him one day, and he was going a long way and he ordered him to go back at the top of Sloane Park. That was about ten o'clock on a Sunday morning. At half past one when he came back that dog was }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 sitting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 in the exact spot, up there, he'd waited all that time. Instead of going back he'd sat down there and waited for him to come back, for thee and a half hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How many times would you say did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At midday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At midday. Midday. We weren't allowed meat at night. Not as - not as children. Not as youngsters no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they think it was bad for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh they thought it was bad to go to bed on. Keep you awake at night. Too heavy to digest you see. Oh no, chi
ldren never had meat at night but we - not until we got - of course when we got really older that was different. When we get up into our teens. Our teens. But before that they didn't like us having meat at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But everyone had meat at midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At midday, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you ever remember any tinned meat being used?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Generally speaking did the children, the parents and the servants have the same food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 
More or less you see, I mean there might be something for instance -
 roast pork, which was a very, very nice dish in those days, with apple sauce and seasoning and that sort of thing we did, mother'd be very - very reluctant to let us eat much of that because it was so hard to digest. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Too rich you see. They watched your food for richness and another thing they did in the nursery when we were very young, they used to have a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 plate}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  of bread and butter on the table, a plate of plain bread and again they wouldn't let us eat jam on butter. With butter at the same time. Too ri
ch. When we were little. So we - either had to have bread and jam or bread and - bread and butter. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I've never heard of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I know, but I can remember it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Also of course the children when they were very young would have different food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And as far meat was concerned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very little meat, it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 minced}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  chicken or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said that the other two servants ate in the kitchen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And the servant who was looking after the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, ate with the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were the children allowed to talk at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. No. Children were supposed to be seen and not heard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would your father ever address a remark to you though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. You - like you can speak when you're spoken to, oh yes. You wouldn't start a conversation, not while - not while adults were }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 tiling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  at any rate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 More or less what was on the table, yes, oh yes. You couldn't grab it though. Like they do now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could you have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
If you wanted to. I suppose if you got really piggish and they thought you were - upsetting your inside they might say, oh that's quite enough, you've had quite enough of that. But not otherwise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What if something was left uneaten on your plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He'd say - he'd be very angry about that, he didn't like it, he used to say, you'll eat it - but they never did bring }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  up, I never remember having to eat it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They weren't really strict about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. No, no. But he'd stop you - he wouldn't let you have any sweet. You wouldn't eat that first course you wouldn't have any }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 sweet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  to follow. And of course everybody likes - when they're young they like the sweets that
 follow. So we used to manage to get rid of it somehow as I told you - putting it under the table. Because we all had table napkins you see, it was quite easy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If there was something on the table out of reach like the salt, could the children ask someone else to pass it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You didn't have to wait?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, you didn't have to wait, you could ask - you could ask for the salt, but you mustn't reach across and get it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - you could ask, y
es, I - well if you - if you asked a bit before you'd hardly got your mouth empty, he'd - dad would say, you wait until everybody else has finished. But you could ask for a second helping, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were the children expected to hold the knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Got to hold your knife and fork properly - proper manners he'd say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you expected to sit up in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sit up straight. Not loll. Not loll.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If he was you slouching in a chair would he say something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, he would, yes. He'd say, sit up properly there. Or - are you tired, he'd say, you can go to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At meal times would it be your father more than your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, more so - when - you see, when we had our meals all together it was dad 
who - who sort of watched - saw how we behaved ourselves. Mother would sometimes but she wouldn't have to because dad'd be too quick on the ball of that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He wouldn't let you get away with anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, wouldn't let you get away with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could toys or books be brought to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. No, no. And even my son - we were talking about that the other night, in this modern age. I mean Clifford is now twenty-seven, twenty-eight nearly, but when he was at - at - school, at St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 
Aloysius}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ' h
e went, when he was at school - that's on the Highgate, up the Highgate Road, yes, that's right. Yes, he went there. Of course he's - now he says he used to be proud of the school he's now ashamed of it, they've got - reduced to - to such a common lot the
r
e now. But however, he - came down one morning with a book in his hand to read, and he was getting on then, he'd be about sixteen, and his father was at the table and he - he was doing what he always did, he'd got his newspaper propped up against the - su
gar basin and was reading it. So he said, he took this - he said, I say young man, I don't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 like em}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 - I don't like reading at - I don't like my youngsters reading at table. He says, you're doing it dad. She he said - he never read his paper again at table after that, he said, it isn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 
if air}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 to expect a child go do something - not to do something that he sees his parents doing. And he left off smoking for the same reason. Didn't want Clifford to smoke. So he cut it out like that. And Clifford doesn't smoke. I
t is right because you - it isn't fair to say to a child, what I do's one thing, what you do is another. There - it's a way to lose their respect really. Later on, terribly - he would and remember it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not until e
verybody had finished. And not 'til - everybody had to be finished, you weren't allowed to get down from the table until mother and dad were ready to - to rise from the table. Then we'd all go. Of course what we did in the nursery I don't know, I can't qu
ite remember but - when we were dining with mother and dad - if you said please can I leave the table he'd say no. Wait 'til every - 'til your mother's finished or - wait until I've finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you always have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes,
 more or less. More or less. Mum and dad always had exactly the same. They always had their own armchairs and it was sacrilege for anybody to sit in dad's chair when he came in in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who served the food up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh maids. Oh yes, she just - she walked round, served then went out, she didn't stay in the room. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother served the vegetables then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, we had the vegetables in vegetable dishes on the table. But they were put on the table, we helped ourselves as we got older.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But a small child might be helped?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I'd be helped then, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So the maids would have put the food on the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Table and its distributed there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who would be served first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Mother. Always. Mother }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  always served first. Father - dad - dad - in fact it got - it got to the state where mother put her - put her foot down, later on when we were grown up, dad always had his last, he was always the last to cut it }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 off}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  and the consequence was that he'd - often his would be more 
or less cold. So - mother said - she - she got very angry about it after some time and she said, listen, this has got to stop. You'll carve off yours - Fred, you're }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  carve your dinner off first and send it out to be kept warm in the kitchen. And so the m
aid used to come in and take his out. Because if we were all sitting down together and especially we had different - by the time he'd served you see, his was cold. So that's how they used to do it in the end, they used to have his cut off, then he would s
erve mother first and then us. And not in any particular order. Those nearest to him - whoever was sitting nearest to him he'd serve first probably.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were very small you had all your meals in the nursery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Nursery, yes. Except on Sunday dinner time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On Sunday dinner time, would it be a special occasion to go down and eat with the grown ups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, it would, well I don't know that we particularly appreciated it. We knew we'd got to behave ourselves anyway. And we had to have spotle
ssly clean hands of course and - made our - tidied ourselves up after having come from church or wherever we'd been. Had to be on our best behaviour. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you ate in the nursery the nurse supervised your meals there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And she ate her meal with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who served it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh she did. She - what used to happen is you see, she used to go down to the kitchen and bring it up from there, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would your mother or father ever come in during that meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I can't remember - they might have done of course on the odd occasion. But not as - it wasn't a ritual thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I suppose they would be eating at the same time would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. They probably the same, we might have ours a little earlier. I don't know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were having your meals in the nursery at that time did your mother and father take an interest in what you had to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. They wanted to know what we had to eat definitely. To be quite sure we were getting the right sort of food, of c
ourse, and getting enough too or not too much, as they case may be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they take an interest in how you behaved at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very much. Oh yes, very much how you behaved and how you spoke to. Don't gabble. No, no. No, no, no. Say that again slowly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At that time the nurse was teaching you table manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But later on when you were in the dining room your father would?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, every time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say your mother was an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh she was easy to talk to. Easy - very easy to talk to, she - she was - she could get angry sometimes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 erratic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , but she was very easy to talk to. Everybody found her so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that she showed affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Yes, she could be angry but she could always show a lot of affection.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She would hug you and kiss you or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, never went to bed without mother - came and kissed us goodnight. And dad usually did too, unless he was too late in, it meant waking us. And of course he
 came up every morning when we were very young, to the nursery. Kissed us before going to the office, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 As you grow up they would put their arms around you would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Not every five minutes like some of them do now but on occasions when it - some reason, or if you were going away. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you had any worried could you take them to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It would depend on the worry, it would depend on me personally. You see, I think you've got to take the individual character i
nto account because - some people find it easier to talk to a friend than they do to their mother. Probably because it's something very personal. - Personal things - in that sort of thing. But most things I could talk to my mother about. I'd go and talk t
o her about the different boys I knew and that sort of thing you know. I'd go and talk to her about things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I suppose a lot of girls couldn't talk to their mothers about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 A lot of them couldn't but the majority I knew did and I kn
ew a very large family that lived in Tollington Park, there were nine of them, and they had a very, very - typical Victorian father who kept them very much under but they could go and tell their mother everything. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Everything. Mrs Hobb died when I was sixteen, first person I knew to die, but she - they - those girls used to go and tell her everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you also say you could tell your worries to your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If they were very deep ones, I think I should - if my mother was alive, and of course
 she was alive until long after I was married, my children were born, I think I would have taken to mother first, mother would have taken it to father. To dad. Although I had one sister who - used to take everything to dad. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 No, I was very close - perhaps I was - I can't hold myself up as an exact example because I was very, very close to my mother, even when she was angry it didn't make any difference to me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But - and so that I would go to her first and as I say she would pass it on to dad. In most things she was very understanding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the main you weren't frightened to take your worries to either of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I wasn't frightened. I was never frightened of my mother or my father, ever. Any period.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about this nurse when you were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could you go to her with a worry about something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well I don't know. I don't think - I think I would have found it easier, but it depends - some I could and some I couldn't. It would depend on the person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because in your family they changed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They changed quite a lot. Really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that usually these nurses were quite easy people to talk to?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. I think that usually - most of those that we had were kind and easy to talk to, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they show affection to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well - as far as I'm concerned I can't remember very much myself but - personally because I was the eldest and I was sort of going away from it when the other - when the younger children were there, but nurse Stude, which was one of the las
t nurses we had for Wes, my young brother, oh she loved him like a mother. But in fact it got so much so that when he went to further schooling, when he went to school, he was going in the upper form mum thought it was better to - you know, to get rid of 
her, and let him be at home with us because he - he got too affectionate then being with her. Well she had him from - she took him from a baby you see and she really worshipped him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh respe
ct - probably to do what we were told. I mean - I don't think I can ever remember going and complaining about the maids at all. But I never remember doing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Towards them? Do as
 we were told really, and treat them - treat them with proper respect. I mean, I wouldn't have though that my father said I'd got to do something and I objected to it, I might say, oh dad not that, or something like that, but if he insisted I shouldn't di
spute the matter. That would be sufficient. Even though I might disagree sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you wouldn't stand there arguing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. Nothing like they do today, I wouldn't have done that at forty-five. No. I wouldn't have done it then, not because I 
was frightened but because I should have thought it was - well it was just }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 disrespectful}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
. You listened even though you didn't take any notice. If - if it was something you didn't want to hear but usually when you ask advice you want the answer that you want. And if you don't get it you haven't necessarily got to take notice of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did your parents expect you to behave towards your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sisters and brothers should love one another. And my mother used to say, 'cos she was a
n only child, she lost her only brother very young, she used to say, what I'd give - everything I've got to have a sister. Don't quarrel. Oh no, she couldn't bear to see - hear us quarrelling amongst ourselves. Although we did from time to time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you say they would really like you to show love towards one another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. I think that's why we are an affectionate family now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were brought up to think that was the right way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes, you - oh yes, definitely, and there was that 
feeling that - it didn't matter whether they got married and went far away - you wouldn't lose contact, not with your own flesh and blood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And they expected you to show respect toward the nurse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, you've got to treat the servants properly 
and - as I said - told you before dad used to say, ten o'clock sharp. They used to go to bed you see, 'cos they'd got to get up early in the morning. And he said - it didn't matter what we wanted, if we wanted anything after ten o'clock we'd got to get it
 ourselves. Yes. And not expect them to - he wouldn't have - he'd say - he - he'd - he'd come outside and see if they were they and say, it's time you girls - to the maids - time you girls were in bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He said this because they had to get up early?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well they've got to get up early. They've got to get all the - the room ready we were having the breakfast room or dining room or whatever it was, all ready for breakfast and had to be done out. Practically done out every day. Swept and dusted and - of 
course it was harder work in those days than today, because it was all done on hands and knees. There wasn't any of the Hoovers or - oh yes, terrible hard work, and they loved work, they loved making work in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did the nurse expect the children to behave towards her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh she made - they were supposed to - supposed to obey her. And if they got out of control she complained. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If the nurse had a bad day or something and she was very cross with you, would you think of going to your mother and complaining about her?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Might. Depends on what she did. It would depend largely on what she did, as a rule they were pretty - pretty reasonable, they didn't take it out on the children, you'd have to get a very bad - bad servant for t
hat to happen. Because I think if they took up - if they took up the job with young children in those days they were really fond of children or they would have taken some other type of job you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would the nurse tell you how you were to behave towards your brothers and sisters?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes, she would, she usually - she usually came with a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 reference}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  where she showed she understood 'cos we never had servants without references, no. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 
Some of them would bring written ones but mother often wouldn't have them because they could be written by friends you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
But as we nearly always got ours through an agency. We nearly always got - were any amount of domestic agencies round here in those days. We nearly got out - we nearly always got ours from the same agency.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And the agency would have spoken to the previous employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 To the previous employer. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you would be unlikely to get anyone bad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very unlikely but if you took a chance you might. For instance, my sister Hilda when he
r babies were small, of course servants were beginning to get scarce then, bit more scarce, she took one who came and knocked at the door and wanted the position and - oh well afterwards that she'd been there - Hilda had grown quite fond of her, she - she
 seemed to be such a nice girl. A knock came to the door one afternoon, it was her late mistress, and she'd come to say that - she thought it was her duty to tell Hilda that the girl had been dismissed because she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 contracted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  venereal disease. Now poor Hilda
 was so terribly worried because of course toilets and that sort of thing. So of course after that she never took one without she got - very special references.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It just happened that the girl seemed all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She seemed ever so nice, ever such 
a nice - in fact Hilda really was - was upset at having to part with her, of course, her husband insisted on her going there and then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Of course they didn't know so much in those days and they weren't sure about her infection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. But you see, it shows, she was with young children, it shows she wasn't quite fit to bring up young children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you were hit by another child or by one of your brothers or sisters, would you be told to hit back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. Not told to hit back again. Told that y
ou come and reported and your father would take it in hand. You weren't supposed - to dish out punishment. Of course the natural tendency is to - I remember on one occasion, we were growing up then. And my sister and I - I was just - I wasn't engaged but 
I
 was about to become engaged, any rate she was two years younger than I and I tore up some letters from a boy she had, she went and got mine and tore them all up. I went for her and tore her hair. Goodness knows what - oh there was a terrible to do. And -
 dad gave us a big lecture about that. He said, you don't - you don't return evil for - by evil.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would it usually be your father who would come in on a thing like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, always, because mother would take it to him you see. She'd probably feel it was a bit beyond her you know, she'd take it to him.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you think you could say what kind of people your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Particularly - first of all, truthful. That was my father's great }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 fetish}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . That whatever you did you 
mustn't be ashamed to own up to it. And - it - as he used to say - and - he'd rather have a thief than a liar. 'Cos there was - you could lock up the thief but you cold do nothing from a liar. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 Truthfulness}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  first of all. And then - oh well, it's generally - I should say dad's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 idea}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  and mother's idea of life was to be honest, truthful and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 whatever}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 you did to do your best, and you can't do more. I mean, it's - my father was a very successful man in - exams, he was an actuary as I told you, but he didn't insist 
that we'd got to pass exams. We - we were to do our best, and nobody could do more than that. But nobody was more pleased than he of course when we got good reports.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But he wouldn't press you to do things like that, he thought things like truthfulness and honesty were more important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He thought they were more - he thought all through his life and he carried it out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 He thought integrity was - he said that - that sort of character bought it's own reward. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In fact he's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 quoted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  it many times, my dear, honesty is the best policy. That was his attitude to life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 As well as that what do you think he hoped maybe for the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well, no, well of course he hoped for the girls they - that - which of course we all disappointed him, we all chose our ow
n - he - I think he - I don't think he was in a hurry for us to go, that was why he was upset when I wanted to be married so young. But - I think he wanted us to make good marriages, he never thought of us going into business, but my two sisters did go. O
f
 course I never did, because the woman's - suffragette movement was in full force and when - when they were grown up and he thought it was better to get them a job which he did, good jobs most of them, they were in charge before they were there five minut
e
s, in the Prudential. But they - Hilda stayed there until she married but my sister Dorothy soon left, and - got her own job in the Bank of India, which she stayed in 'til she married. He wanted Wes to be an actuary of course. Freddy was brought up with g
randma but he had him in the end - and here still. He - in the end when he was about eighteen he had him - articled, he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 paid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 for his articles with Gilbert and Howe. And he became - it's still there you know, Gilbert and Howe in Crouch End still. And he took his articles and passed as an auctioneer and surveyor.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But what would you say was really important to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 More character than anything else. He believed in good character. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So he considered truth and honesty important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Truth and straightness Yes. He wouldn't - and he also -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And your mother too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh mum too. He also thought that - that - you couldn't keep a good man down. In other words, if a man had - had - talent, in any way, sooner or later it would sow itself and you just couldn't keep it down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would any of the nurses have any influence on the children in giving them an idea of what was important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Don't think so, not really. I don't think they were sufficiently sophisticated really, the ser
vant class, very few of them would be able to do that. I mean, it - for instance - if a servant was to have a bad - some of them might have had a bad influence in some families but in that case it got to the parents ears of course they would be dismissed 
you see. But - I can never remember any - any corruption going on in our household.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She too would encourage you to be truthful and honest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes. Because that would be something that would go into - would be part - would be part 
of the interview and engaging her which of course mother would lay down. And - she'd say if she find any of them deliberately untruthful you must report it to me. She didn't give them - she didn't give them ever the authority to chastise us. Never. Not ev
er.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She was to tell your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. They would deal with chastising us if necessary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that the nurse would have similar attitudes about things as your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Usually. Usually. Some of them might - might - not have had
, but they didn't show it. I wouldn't like to say they were always a hundred percent with them because I don't suppose they were for a moment.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But they would uphold your parents views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, oh yes, they would do that, they would never teach 
us to disobey our - I can never remember them doing so, I have known them, as I told you before, to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 shield}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 us. Covering up, if it was late - late in or anything like that, but - oh no. I don't think we would have - I think we would have resented it. I believe we ourselves would have resented it if they had. U know I would have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did your parents think about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - I never heard my father - I was only saying so the other night, my son occasionally comes out with a b---- you know, 
and I said to him, don't do it, don't swear, I'm not used to it and I don't do it while you're here. Of course quite harmlessly, he was just talking about politics and that sort of thing. But I never heard my father swear in my life, never once, because -
 and he probably did when he was with men but he wouldn't have done it in front of women, it - we were a lot of girls you see, there were four girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So he wouldn't do it in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. And he always said the same thing about swearing, he used
 to say, you know - 'cos my husband swore, the one thing that I - hated most of all. He'd been in - he'd been in the Army you see and he'd got the - bad start - but - he used to say, you know, when a man swears it's because - he lacks vocabulary. There's 
eight million words in the English language and if you can't express anger - with proper words then it simply shows your vocabulary is limited. That was the attitude he took.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did the nurses think about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I never heard - they would have been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 dismissed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  immediately if they'd have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What if they had heard one of the children swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I never - I don't think they ever did. But I can't tell you what the action would be, I - I probably didn't know what swear words were. I used
 to see sometimes - you used to see them, of course children were like - they're just the same as they are now, you'd see things written on the payment and that sort of thing, and you might go in and ask what it meant. And then you be told - that's not a 
word at all. That's not a word.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The nurse might say that to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, she would say that to - or she would report it to mother - mother that we'd mentioned it. And what should she do. And mother would say, ignore it and I'll speak to her. Direct
ly you made a fuss about the attitude would have been that the child couldn't possibly have known what the word meant and directly you make a fuss about it you're stamping it on the child's mind. The thing is to dismiss it and simply say well it's not a w
ord at all, simply silly. That would be the attitude.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When he grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You - you weren't allowed to join in because you were dismissed to the morning room or the nursery or the study or whatever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they ever talk about anything serious in front of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Very seldom. Until we were getting older of course, when I got into my teens yes. But - not when I was young, no. No, we rather resented it, always being sent out when grown up people were talking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they ever sort of draw you into the conversation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
If it was childish, depends, if they were talking about somebody else's youngsters you know and - perhaps their prowess at school or their - parties or anything, yes, you'd be joined
 - you'd join in then but it would always be conversation that you would be interested in. They tried to keep you as much as they possibly could, which I think perhaps was wrong, I don't know, blind to the ugly things in life. There was a tendency to - th
ey'd to watch your literature so that you didn't get a wrong idea of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I suppose they would never talk about anything }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 unpleasant}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  that was happening in the neighbourhood or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, not in front of children, not until we were getting older
 and then of course the - you hear them now and again talking about - I suppose what one would call gossip.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you did something that your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well it would depend on what it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If it was something that was definitely naughty, like lying, what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - lying. Oh we - well lying - we should be punished in some way, I'm trying to remember - you see, we very seldom lied to - to mum and dad, very seldom. But if we did it would be - it would
 be something like supposing a birthday was near you wouldn't get any presents, if you had a party you would have to cancel it. That sort of punishment. Very seldom - very seldom were we hit. Very seldom. My mum might do a slap occasionally. But never str
uck any, we girls anyway.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Suppose you had done something very naughty and you were to be punished by cancelling a party or making you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 suffer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  in some way, who would decide about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Both of them. Mum might try to put in a good word for the child, but dad, if he said a thing he meant it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then both parents would stand together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Then it would be forgotten you see. Once the punishment was over it would be forgotten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember how often you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I can't - can't remember - we had our share of it of course. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 
Three girls all much about the same age, we were bound to - yes, we were bound to get in - in some sort of trouble some time or another. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
And - sometimes we'd be in a hurry to get out and wouldn't - would
 want - miss a meal, we wouldn't be allowed to do it. We'd have to stay, never mind if we'd made an appointment or not. Just told you've got to stay until you've finished your meal. You've got to wait until we leave the table - weren't allowed to leave th
e table until mother had got up. If we were at the table with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were small children were you often punished for naughtiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I can't remember being punished much, no. I don't think we'd so - I think we were - I don't think we were su
fficiently naughty. Mind you, dad had a - a dad had a cane you know. He had a cane, but I don't ever remember seeing it very much. I might have had it once or twice, I don't remember it anyhow. Mother was more inclined to flourish the cane. And she'd say,
 pass me. And - still standing at the door there with that cane and - pass me. And of course I refused to - pass me. And as you went by you'd get a flip round the legs. But - not often. Very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you ever punished by the nurse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, sh
e'd sometimes - sit you on the chair and say you weren't to move when you were very young, that's sort of thing, but not - they weren't allowed to really. Not punish, not what I call punish. They would report it to the parents and they would say what puni
shment was necessary, they didn't delegate out to maids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The maids would just sort of tick you off?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, I'll tell your father when he comes in, or I'll tell your mother and she'll tell your father when he comes in. Funny thing, they used to say
 they'd tell dad, it was always a sort of worse thing although he - yes, than telling mother, I suppose familiarity breads contempt. That's what it is. Where father would only have to give a look, it wasn't that he ever spared us but a look'd be enough. I
 suppose that we - we valued his approval perhaps more. As I say, familiarity breeds contempt and I think with your mother all day you don't feel quite that - that feeling of awe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And he was higher and more important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Of course he was. He to
ok on - they don't do it today the fathers - but in that day his - his word was law. But he never gave - I never remember him being unfair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you didn't resent anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, we didn't resent - I can never remember - I often talk to the girls, m
y sisters, and they say the same, they can never remember him being unfair. You see, if he found himself unfair he was big enough to come and say so to you. He'd say, I'm sorry I made a mistake.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That is the sort of thing he valued in life anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Anyway, you see, truthfulness. We were lucky in our family, very lucky in our father particularly so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember a particular occasion when you were punished for something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. I remember - what was it about - I can't really proper
ly - I know when dad's been to the Highlands for a holiday and we'd been left at home - with a little aunt - with my father's youngest sister and a couple of maids in the house and - he'd forbidden me to go somewhere, I forget where it was. Might have bee
n up to the Alexandra Palace or something. Anyway I disobeyed him. And he bought me back the most beautiful brooch from the Highlands. I never got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He told you about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He told me about it and - mother had brought it down to give it to me, he said, oh no, she's not going to have it. He said, for }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 deliberate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  disobedience. And I never had it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And that was the only punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That was the only punishment on that occasion, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you feel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 I - I've known what - he used to shut - if we very, very - troublesome we'd be shut in our room sometimes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Made to stay there to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The time he kept back the brooch from you, what did he do with the brooch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I never know. Never know to this day what he did with it because I n
ever saw it again, but the - my two sisters both had theirs. I never had mine. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Don't know, I suppose I was a bit - I believe I howled a bit at the time but I don't think I was resentful. Not a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 suffer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  a little bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes. And I don't think I would have done it again in a hurry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because it was a punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. Definitely. I think children resent unfairness. I don't think it - I think most children know when the
y're being - when they deserve punishment. And I don't think they resent it then, I don't think any children do. I think where there's terrible - delinquency comes in is because children are punished unfairly. And - oh inconsistently yes, where - just for
 the sake - just because you come home cross from the office, they - cuffing children about or turning them out of the room and telling them to go and play. I think children - resent that inwardly. In their subconscious. They know it's unjust you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that you got your ideas about how to behave later in life from both your parents or more from one that the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I think - a little of both - a little of both, mum wasn't - she got ill later and she wasn't much for an example as a g
irl you might say because her health had broke down and she was often away trave}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
ling and that sort of thing. I should say - development of character was mostly based on dad. I should say so. Because - and yet - and yet you know I loved my mother so dearly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She and he agreed on most things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
He - on most things, although they didn't always agree on everything, in fact they had - they drifted rather apart in the latter years of life, but they didn't allow it to affect the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were small they stood together on things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that the various nurses you had had an influence on this sort of person you later on became?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Don't think they had any at all. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you feel about the nurses, did you feel fond of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well I don't - I liked most of the maids we had, yes, most of them, I can't remember any of them being - being what I should call disliked by the children, no. I think they're all pretty nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were the childrens' birthdays made into a special day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh nearly always, yes. We always had a - you know, a special cake and - and parties and perhaps new frocks and that sort of thing and we'd have, the three of us was so near each other, we'd probably have all - all fro
cks alike. They'd bring up a roll of silk and they'd be made up you see alike, so that we were always - all the same although it was one birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So it would be just one's birthday but all three of you would get new frocks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. No, on each birthday. On each and every birthday, oh yes, birthdays were kept up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you get presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Sometimes - oh presents always. Sometimes when we got older it would be they'd perhaps book seats at the theatre or something like that you see. Oh they a
lways celebrated birthdays. Birthdays and Christmas. Pantomime every year at Christmas when we were small. On Boxing Day. Always Boxing Day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On the birthday would there be special food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, you'd have extras of course or - jelly - as my little Pat used to say, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 jellimonges}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would guests }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2320564\charrsid8657389 come}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  to tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Oh we'd have a - little party - children's party, yes. That and at Christmas time we kept it right up until long after we were married too at Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there anything special on Christmas Day?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
The family would be there. All the family. Married ones, single ones, sweethearts on and on. Perhaps when we were engaged we'd go over to our future in-laws for Boxing Day. But always Christmas at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So the girls would stay in their own homes and the boyfriends of fianc\'e9s would come to their house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Boyfriends would come - this house, and then we'd go to theirs perhaps on Christmas - on Boxing Day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And a married daughter and her husband and children would come to your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, we stayed with dad always. I was the first to be married you see, the others didn't get married 'til soon after - after mum died. But - as long as the home was going as a family we went home. With - with the children. Oh yes, w
e'd sit - sit there on Christmas night with - circle in the drawing room singing songs until about four or five in the morning. I remember one Christmas we were still singing in the morning, Little Brown Jug Don't I Love Thee, at the top of our voices. An
d
 dad had - I think he was going into the office because sometimes he'd go in on the Boxing day, 'cos he'd get three days off for that for going in for that, and - I remember - it was - it was in fun, the drawing room door was wide open and the staircase f
aced it and I can see him standing with a great big sponge filled with water that he threw at us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because you were singing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. He said, don't you think I want any sleep? But he was laughing. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any musical instruments in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - well we had two pianos. One - two. We had the - one in the drawing room and one downstairs in the dining room that we used when we were learning. I took it with me when I got married. And it was lost in the - in the last war. Down at the d
ocks, it was in the dock fire, in storage, it went up and they never have me a penny for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did all the girls learn to play the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We all learnt to play the piano. Some got on better than others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Freddy had to learn the violin but he hated it and he threw it in - he was going through Central }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7828773\charrsid8657389 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ark one day, threw it in the lake. And his music with it. He said he wasn't going to learn any more. There in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7828773\charrsid8657389 F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 insbury Park lake, violin and music in his music - he one of tho
se gig sort of - like a brief case - a music case it was really. And he threw the whole lot in this Finsbury Park lake.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you all had to try and play something really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We all had to do something, well we used to have these - these childrens' a
ffairs and we were all expected to do something. Dolly used to sing and she sang very nicely. She used to sing at Alwoods concerts at the Atheneum. She had quite a nice strong voice. The Atheneum, it used - it's gone now but it used to be in Tolling Road,
 
not - previous to the Muswell Hill one. There used to be one in Camden Town, the Atheneum you know and - she used to sing there. But - we always had these musical evenings and I'd play the piano, she'd sing and sometimes I'd recite poetry. And - did Hilda
 do anything. Oh she'd sing, yes, she'd sing too. Freddy didn't do anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So in the house you played the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. And Dorothy sang.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And Freddy played the violin until he threw it in the lake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 'Til he threw - yes. He played it? That awful noise he used to make you mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did anyone else play anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. But - we had - a very musical side of the family we used to visit where they all did something, they had a - a quartet. One played the cello, one played the violin, the other one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was relatives of yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. My father's - father's relatives. And - my mother hadn't many, she was an only child as I told you. But - - these were dad's relatives, they lived at Highbury at Elwell Lodge and one used to play the
 violin, one played cello, one played the harp and one played the piano. Oh very talented. And one of them married - married Augner - Augner the big musical - music publishers still in existence of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So two of the girls sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother and father do anything in the way of music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Mum used to play the piano. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7828773\charrsid8657389 
Sometimes she used to - and she used to play, play it very nice, she didn't play it a lot though, she - my father used to sing sometimes too.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh sometimes. Especially at Christmas time and times like that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 One of you play the piano while the others sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Oh yes, all round the piano singing together, oh yes, we'd do that, we'd have musical
 evenings now and again. When we'd have friends who could sing too you see. Hilda Hobbs used to bring her violin, she played very beautifully.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you'd make a whole evening of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We'd make an evening - oh that's the sort of amusement you had, 
you tot - musical evenings or you got up some sort of a show or other you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I can't remember that particularly, dad now and again come out in the garden and play rounders. But not - I should say 
no. I should say as a - as a general thing, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the nurses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I - he'd take - I used to play cribbage with him when I was quite young. Oh yes, I did play }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7828773\charrsid8657389 cribbage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  with dad sometimes, he was fond of - he was fond of cards and games of that sort
 but my - and he was a great chess player. He used to go down to the Hastings congress every year. He was great chess player and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did any of you play chess with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. I - we learnt the moves and that sort of thing but he was too good of cour
se. He used to play table matches with Americal, where they cabled the moves from one to another. And my mother hated it, she couldn't bear to see the chess board come out, she'd say to me when I'd be about fifteen, come on, go and get your hat, we're goi
ng out to the music hall or going to a show. I'm not going to watch him staring at that board for three hours without moving.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What would he be doing on his own, working out moves in his head?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, he'd - you see, perhaps Ian Lawrence another grea
t chess player, he was an international player - they used to sit there I've seen dad - dad astride across the chair with his arms across the back, you know, the wrong way round. And - and stare at the board and there they'd be working out these - moves.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It was all right for you and your mother to go out together off to a show or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, wouldn't ask him, no we'd be off. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She'd just say to you, come on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, go and put on your - a hat Gracie, we're not going to stay 
and watch them. She couldn't bear cards either. She hated that, I don't know why but she - I love cards but she had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7828773\charrsid8657389 detestation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  of them. Yes she was fond of - of the theatre, very fond of the theatre.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You and she would go on your own to a musical show?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How would you travel into the West End?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh we - well we had the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7828773\charrsid8657389 Marlborough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  House right near you know, which was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 theatre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  when it was first built.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You'd walk over there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh not walk over - we used to ride ov
er, we'd get a tram from the bottom of Finsbury Park and - then go down by tram. Unless anybody had come and got a victoria or anything and then they'd drive us you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It would be all right for the two of you to go in on your own to the show?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 Went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 all sorts of places on our own mum and I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your father played cable chess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
He - he'd play chess sitting there and he'd also cable. They'd - they - they'd play in a match with America you see. Well international, what t
hey called international chess. And he would - he would cable his move then they - the other chap would cable in return.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where would he do this from - from home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 From home, from the Post Office of course he'd cable them. Oh he'd write all the moves down you see. And then cable them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then come back home again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
And then come - and then come back home again to stare at the board a bit longer and work out the next one and wait for the cable from America to come and then cable back again. Mad as March }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 
hares}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of year was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh about - I should think - well I was born in 1899, it'd be in the '90's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was in the 1890's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. And - he was a wonderful chess player and his grandfather was champion of England of draughts. Very mathematical of course.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And or course your father was an actuary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would a telegraph boy bring the cable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes. Sometimes he'd go to the office. It would depend. Sometimes he'd go
 to the office. They used their intellect in those days, see they had nothing else to do. Except get in mischief.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the nurses ever play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I suppose they did. Yes, ludo and snakes and ladders and - oh yes, oh yes, we'd have all those games, what I call table games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You in the nursery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. And - we had a ping-pong table too. That we used to play ping-pong. At - oh that'd be when I was - be - that'd be - again'd be in the - about - I was married in 1908 - it'd be in 1900's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Which room was the table in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh we had a ping-pong table up in the nursery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was this when there were no more small children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, they were still small - they were still - Phyllis was still small and so was Wes. It wasn't a ver
y large one you know, it wasn't a full sized table, it was a - oh I don't know what size you'd say it was - about the size of that one only square.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you sat it up especially for the game of ping-pong?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Or was it there all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no. It folded. Folded, oh yes, put away, folded.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And the nurses and the maids would play with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, they'd play that - as I say, and they'd play all these silly ludo and snakes and ladders. Those stupid games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Lot of books but they were all good books, Dickens - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 Zola}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , we had Zola there. Yes. We had Zola, that was pretty advanced, really, yes, we had Zola. We used to have Dickens, we had - of course Alice in Wonderland. I've gust give
n my - to the gentleman next door, he's got two little boys, I've just given my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 Morocco}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 bound, most beautiful thing, there's an Alice in Wonderland that was given me on my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 ninth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 Christmas. When I was nine years old. The engravings, all the early engravings, it will be worth something some days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said there were a lot of books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, and - but dad used to keep his bookcase locked. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You weren't allowed free access to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not to his books, no, we had our - we ha
d our - escritoire at the top open where we could put our own books and things but - dad's books were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 sacrosanct}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you get new books for yourselves, did people give them to you for presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We had them for presents. Dad was very - as we 
got older we nearly always had - chose, he'd ask us what we wanted you see and we nearly always chose books. We all enjoyed reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Providing your choice was all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. He would buy it. Oh yes. We - we were all of us very fond of reading, great readers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would there be newspapers around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, but at - we weren't allowed to - I used to get them on the quiet sometimes. Say there was spicy murder on or something that I wanted to read but - we weren't allowed to - not a
s far as dad's permission was concerned. Except the leading article. And he used to - 'cos he - the Daily Telegraph, or the Times, one or the other we had every morning, he'd carefully take that page out from the newspaper and say - you can read that, it'
s educational.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would this be a bit difficult for you girls to understand because it would be about politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 A matter of politics yes. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You knew enough to understand it did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. 'h yes. And he'd talk about those sort of things, that when we were growing up with that. No I think as a family}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389  we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  were politically }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 mature.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . I think we were, looking back now and comparing what goes on today I think that we were - probably because of that leading article. He would explain to us, you se
e, now and again he'd go down and explain the economics simply, in simple language you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you knew who the ministers were and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes, we know all - all the ministers, we know all those all right, we'd go with our 
little flags waving, we'd know all the flags. And the different countries. And of course we had a collection of national flags ourselves that came out every time there was any Royal occasion or any special visitor, out'd come the flag outside the window. 
Yes, I suppose really in those - and that's probably why I'm still politically minded, my son is very politically minded that - yes, genetics I think at work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You couldn't sit down and read the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 rest}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  of the paper in front of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Because he - 
he'd - he'd take that leading article out of the paper, and he'd give it to you to read. And then say, do you understand it. And then we'd have some little conversation about it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would there be magazines around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sometimes. The 
women's magazines you know, mother'd have them from time to time. Some of them might be - very similar to what they are today really, some'd have recipes in - patterns for frocks and hats and all that sort of thing, women's stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would the children be allowed to glance at them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, we used to be - we used to be able to cut out the pictures 'cos they were nearly always coloured - cut out the pictures and put them in a scrap book.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember your mother or father reading aloud?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 R
eading? Oh father was an inveterate reader. In fact, after he retired, he retired at fifty-nine, he'd only had schoolboy French but he took up French and German and he was - he read nothing but novels in French and German. And he - he was fifty-nine when 
he retired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Mother was - she had bad eyesight dear, she couldn't - she would have loved reading, she used to read when she was young but she couldn't do much reading. That's why she used to go out to theatres and things li
ke that to - and - long holidays, and that sort of thing, after her nerves went to pieces. And so really and truly she didn't do much, when she was very young she used to do all sorts of needlework but she couldn't even do that you see, her eyes were so b
a
d. She was continually at the special - there's a big specialist in Cavendish Square and Harley Street, for the yes, she'd been to and they all said the same, that it was caused - that when she was a baby about three months old her brother who was a littl
e
 bit older, the one who died you see, took the pepper pot and peppered her eyes and - terrible thing it was - he thought he was powdering her. He'd watched grandma powdering her you know and he thought he was powdering her and of course she was blind then
,
 she was only two months old. She blind for about six months. But she got her sight back again. And after when she got to school - of course she's always had - had to wear glasses all her life, the specialists all said the same, that her eyes would get no
 worse than they were. But the cause of the trouble was the scars behind the back of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 eyes,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 with the burning, they burst you see, the pepper burnt them. So of course that was a dreadful thing to happen. Poor little boy, he didn't know what he was doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother or father ever read aloud to each other then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well I never heard them. I used to read aloud to my husband. I read until he went to sleep every night, but I never heard mum and dad reading aloud to each other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your mother didn't enjoy that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I think she'd rather go to the theatre and hear the experts. She loved the theatre.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ever read aloud to the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. Used to read to them. I mean, dad'd say - perhaps he'd bring a classic home and he'd 
- ask us to read that chapter and perhaps we'd read it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would that be a sort of test?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
It would be a sort of challenge and then he'd - if - if you didn't - pronounce the words properly he'd correct you know, very nicely and gently but he would. But actually -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But reading aloud for pleasure wasn't a thing in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the nurse ever read to you?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sometimes. Fairy stories and things like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not u
ntil I was getting on. I can remember my - I was only a little girl - I remember my grandfather Fulford dying 'cos he died at forty-five, very young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He died when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 A little girl, I can remember it because I remember the mo
rning he died the canary died. 'Cos that worried much more because I didn't know much about - I only remember seeing him once. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 
I can remember seeing him once, I couldn't have been more than three, it shows you how good memory is, because I remember going i
nto that kitchen and - and I know the gentleman I aw was the one who's photograph was always on our mantelpiece, and him picking me up in his arms - and holding me up in the air and looking at my dad who had taken me one Sunday morning and saying, Fred, y
ou'll never be dead while this child's alive. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I was so like him. Real image of him, they always say I was too when I grew older. Fred, you'll never be dead while this child lives. It struck me as a curious thing to say and it stuck in my mind, I was only th
ree. It was true, oh yes, because - everybody knew that - even - even now if I meet anybody that ever knew dad they say, my word, aren't you like your father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you remember the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I can remember the funeral because I can remember it bec
ause I remember it had - a thing I'd never seen, except I might have seen it casually in street and take notice - and not take notice and I remember they had - the horses had plumes. Black plumes and black palls - across their backs. And my grandmother al
l - massed in crepe, black crepe. I can just remember that so they must have come from a house to pick dad up. Dad and mum up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You didn't go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you in black?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. They didn't put us in black.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they put any of the children in black?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. I think Freddy, I can't remember but I think Freddy wore - they sewed a crepe }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 armband}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  - band on his - oh his overcoat. On his overcoat I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you think if you had been older you would have been put in black?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I w
ould have been if I'd have been about fifteen or sixteen. I never went to a funeral, I went - first funeral I ever went to was Mrs Hobb, that's my friends mother, and - I wore black then, I wouldn't have gone to a funeral without. And my mother always - a
nd another thing I always remember a funeral for, my mother always wore a pair of most beautiful diamond }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 earrings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
, she always wore them, but she always took them off when she went to a funeral. She took her diamond rings off and took off her - her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 earring}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . She never went to a funeral with them on, that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 another little - little touch of respect I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You remember your grandmother wearing a lot of black at your grandfather's funeral, a lot mourning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And your parents were in mourning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, they wore mourning for six months. Six months mourning. They didn't agree with it later but of course - as they - as they got older they really didn't believe in it although they still did it where they knew that people - knew of - woul
d appreciate, were still old fashioned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At the end of six months would they go back to their ordinary clothes suddenly or gradually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. No, they'd grey or heliotrope. Either grey or heliotrope. And I - I used to like the heliotrope it suited
 my mother so much. I used to love her in that. Yes, a lavender shade. A grey or that sort of lavender - mauvy - lavender.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they buy special clothes for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh they did. Always for a funeral they had new clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And new black clothes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, new black clothes. The - the tailors were rung up and they knew they got a lot of orders that way of course. Then they just supplied - he guaranteed to supply you with in so many hours you see. Twenty-four or thirty-six hours for what mo
urning you wanted. Oh yes, they always wore black - black crepe, always crepe. Thank goodness they don't do it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you taken out visiting neighbours or friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sometimes, yes, sometimes. If other people had children as a rule
. But as a rule if any of their friends had children then we would be taken out. At various times, and of course to relatives. We'd be taken from time to time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who would take you, both your parents or just your father or just your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, ge
nerally my father or my mother, never both of them together, I don't remember going out with mum and dad together except on holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I wonder why that would be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I don't know, looking back on it I don't know. I know mother used to make me laugh,
 when I'm thinking back in years afterwards, because dad would come in and he'd say - he'd call her - sometimes he'd call her Bibby, a nicknam}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 e, he'd say, Bibby, what about}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  your hat and coming for a walk round the houses - a bit of prom}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 na}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 de}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . She'd say, wh
at on earth do I want to walk round the houses for, I see enough of them all day, and - no, I'm going so and so, I'm going somewhere - go off to the theatre or somewhere, he wasn't very keen on the theatre and music hall but she was you see. He - he liked
 more serious things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So they went out separately quite a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, except on holidays, we used to go away for six weeks holiday - and then they'd do everything together you see, during that six weeks. But as the years went on we cut it down, the
y cut it down to a month and he would have a fortnight on his own with Fred my elder brother, or my younger brother later on, and they'd go off for a fortnight on their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So generally speaking you can remember being out to visit people with your father or your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Or - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you ever taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, I went shopping with mother quite a lot. We all were at different times. Not with dad shopping, but mum shopping.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You had quite a few nurses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever have any contact with their homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, sometimes. Yes, sometimes, but it was - used to be very much against mother's - that was the only thing they used to deceive her in. And she only found it out when my - 'cos we never had any fevers, we h
ad the ordinary measles and - that sort of thing. But my - two younger - both my younger brother and my younger sister one had scarlet fever and one had diphtheria and they both could trace it to the fact that they'd been taken home by one of the maids. I
n both cases.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How would this happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because they lived nearer you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they take them out for a walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, they'd be going out to go to the park and perhaps wheel the pram down and go into - and visit her family, quite understanda
ble, but some of them didn't live in too salubrious neighbourhood and - mother wouldn't have approved of it you see, they were supposed to take us to the park.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you think that was how they caught that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Almost certainly it was. Absolutely certain with Wesley that it was that. And he got scarlet fever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the nurse at that time say to you don't tell your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can't remember 'cos I wasn't the one that was taken, so I can't remember. Whether she said so - I - I should think probably
 she might have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I suppose she must have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The child would have come out with something, I think probably she did. Yes, I think she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But definitely your parents wouldn't have approved of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, they wouldn't have ap
proved unless, of course, they were - they'd have know, if they - we met one or two maids that came out of very respectable }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 homes,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  you know, men on the railways who got - and if they'd have asked if they minded her calling there mum probably would have said, no and said, take a parcel or something.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And she wouldn't mind the child being on contact with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. So long as it wasn't - well I suppose there unduly as a rule the - the - type that took you home they were more or less in the pram then
 you see. Wouldn't take them walking so much 'cos the child would be more likely to talk. Oh they had to have permission. I don't say if they'd have said, could I call in at mother's for so and so, and so mother would probably have said yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember ever going to one of the nurses' homes yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. I can remember calling at the - one or two maids' homes on occasions. On occasions. For mother - with a message from mother, perhaps they were on holiday or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you did that what did they call you, how did they address you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh Miss Gracie always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you went there they knew who you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And they called you Miss Gracie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not Miss Fulford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Miss Gracie, I was alwa
ys Miss Gracie. But you see there were so many of us, I was really Miss Fulford 'cos I was the oldest, where the others actually, you see, there was Miss Dorothy, Miss Gracie, Miss Hilda.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But if you had been out somewhere with friends and they had introduced you to someone they would have said, this is Miss Fulford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Oh yes. In fact at one - at school they used to call us Miss Fulford, that was the funny part about it, even at school. As we got in the upper forms it was always Miss Fulford
. Yes. I was only saying how funny that was the other day. It struck me as comical, teachers always - when we got - after we got out of the fourth form.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you would be fifteen or sixteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Be fifteen - it was always Miss Fulford. I remember whe
n I met - when I'd been to that prize giving that I was telling you about, a gentleman saying, Miss Fulford, remember - now what was it she actually said - you've got the gift of words. Cultivate it. But it was Miss Fulford, I can hear him saying it now.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But when you called at a maid's house with a message or something like that they would say Miss }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 Gracie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - always - It was always Miss Gracie, I suppose the maid had always spoken of us at home like that because she always called us that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you enjoy this, meeting a different sort of people and seeing the maids home and where she lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I don't remember particularly enjoying it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you very curious about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Not really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You did sometimes go out with just your father on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. I remember him taking me down on the boat too, when - I was quite young then, ever so young, taking me on the boat on the Royal Sovereign down to Cliftonville, down to the - to Margate on the Golden Sovereign. And
 I remember climbing onto a stool and falling and hitting my mouth and the terrible row there was when I got home. My mum was so angry with him for not looking after me, well then I - I - but I don't think this ought to go down. Father was winking his eye
 and lifting his hat to a lady on the boat. And he said, I'll never take any child - my child - never take that child out again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because he was doing this you fell?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. Horrible child I must have been. Beastly little child. Telling mum, yes
 he was winking at a lady, and raising his hat to a lady on the boat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And was it true?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Oh yes, that was true, that's why he said he'd never take me any more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he hold it against you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, you see, he was rather attractive to wo
men as a matter of fact. I think mum had a little bit of that to put up with the in the first year she was married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Nothing big but he would raise his hat and look at them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, yes. Oh he didn't pass a pretty - girl easily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Even though you were a small child you were aware of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh I was perfectly aware - I can remember what I felt like, you know, people wouldn't believe it, but to this day I can remember what I felt like when I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 climbed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  on that stool, and I really fell because I was looking at him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I suppose you would be resentful because he wasn't giving you his full attention?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It might have been, there might have been a bit of that in it. Any rate, it wasn't to make me - when I got back I went - my face 
was right up here you see. And he had to give an explanation that I'd fallen. And then mum asked me about it afterwards and she said, where was your father? So I said, I don't know, there was a pretty lady - there was a pretty lady on the boat he raising 
his hat and winking, I can remember doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They might have been arguing bout that all night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He - possibly they were. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Children are funny aren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Awfully funny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They do notice things don't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, much more
 than you think they do. Got to be awfully careful what you do - if a child is - is sharp. Because some children are not so sharp as others. I was observant, I think most children are observant but I was particularly observant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I'm sure it's not good to do things like have rows in front of children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh no. Oh no. I know, because I remember that row, there was a row, and it did go through the night and I was in the bedroom next door and I remember crying myself to sleep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because you knew there was trouble?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Knew I'd caused it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember any special outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, I think the outings I remember most of all - one or two - one or two to the office, when they had - they had the Gondoliers there, you know, done the office staff and that sort of thing but -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was that actually held in the Prudential building?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. They had their theatre their and - their own theatre you know. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In that big building in Holborn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I can't remember whether 
it was there or - or right near, I think it was there. Yes, I think it was there, the concert hall was there. Near Holborn Station. They had wonderful shows. Beautiful shows there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would the whole family go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. I was the only one favoured in
 those days. Later on of course when I married and Wes was growing up he went but of course he was in the Prudential, he went in there later himself. And - I think I - I think - I think perhaps Dorothy might have been once or twice, the one next to me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you went there did your mother and father both go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I went with dad alone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On something like Bank Holidays would there be a family outing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On Bank Holidays - dad would never go out on a Bank Holiday. Nothing would make him go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because of the crowds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Crowds, oh no, hated crowds. Dad was at home, he didn't go out on - you could have your friends at home or you could go out to friends, which we did, it was always - sometimes we'd have friends home, sometimes we'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 go to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  their home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you'd spend it pretty quietly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, pretty quietly Bank Holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You didn't go to the sea or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, never did that at Bank - oh no, Bank Holiday avoided like grim death.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember the nurse going to on any outings that you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Always came with us on holiday, always took one. We used to send the - if we'd got - only one more maid, sometimes we had one sometimes we had two - we'd send them on board wages, they used to call it, the
y'd come back, two or three days before we were due home. See the place was all in order and - aired. And - but we always took one with us. Always. Because we'd always got a baby, or somebody young you see. Always somebody young.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Apart from your actual summer holidays, did you ever go on a picnic or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. They weren't the picnic type. I used to go picnics of course with the church and that sort of thing but - never with the family. Never remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember going to the zoo or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you went to the zoo would the nurse go too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I think I - my only remembrance of the zoo is going with dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were old enough then just to go with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Just with him, I'd be about six or seven you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you used to go away every year, in the beginning it was six weeks every year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then later it went down to a month?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Why did it go down to a month?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well dad - dad would finally
 decided mother - mother too, I think it was her idea as much as his, that when we was getting older, of course the idea was to get us all away, well I suppose it's a nuisance having a terrific amount of young children in the house, in the early days, she
 
wanted it at home, she said there was time she wanted to get ready for school uniforms and replacing and all that sort of thing and so he used to go with my elder brother first of all, on a walking tour perhaps of Devon - or something - or up at - to the 
Lake District. And then later of course, after I was married and Wes was growing up he used to go away with him. In the same way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then you'd all go down to the country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, we'd all go down - well right up until the - I think we went away ri
ght up until - when did they start - girls start going on their own - aunt Dolly left home and - Hilda - no, you see, we all - we all married }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 within a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  few years of each other so really it broke up, it broke up when we got - the last holiday I remember us taking all together was the year before I was married. In 1907. When we went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 Scarborough.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 And he said he would never tale us all away together again, it was such a lark. We went - we went to a hotel on the front but it had a back entrance and front entrance. And one led into one street and one led onto the front, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 you know Scarborough beaches wind in and out like hat, he could never - he said he could never find us. Never knew what boys we were with or what we were doing. And we used to meme in, we wer
e supposed to be in at ten, that year. Getting on then. Supposed to be in at ten o'clock, and we would come in at ten. And we'd make an appointment for - half past ten or quarter to eleven. When we were supposed to be in bed, and go out. He tumbled to it 
in the end, he said he could never find us, he'd never take us to Scarborough again. If he went away he'd go something - he'd take us somewhere where he could see the front and what was going on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When he did tumble to it was he very annoyed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not
 really I don't think, I think he was really a wee big amused. If anything. But he swore he'd never take us again. And of course he never did, I got married to start with, and the following year after I got married - Dorothy and Hilda - no, Hilda didn't -
 
Dorothy went into the Prudential. She'd had a row and left home. And so she didn't go with them you see, she went on her own with a girl from the office. Hilda and - yes, Hilda and - Wes and the maid and Nurse Stude and mum and dad went away next year. Ye
s they did, they went away again. They went down to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there still a small one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, 'cos - young Wes was only - when I got married Wesley was only six months old. You see. Twenty years difference between us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That holiday in Scarborough in 1907 a nurse went along too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Yes, she was there too. No she wasn't - 'cos West wasn't born, a lady - lady's companion was there. Mum's lady's companion was there, she - she'd already got a lady's companion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But in 1908?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, the
n - in 19 - I was married, they went away that year. I was married in the July and they went away in September, he'd never go in August when the children were about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 By that time Wesley had been born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, been born and Nurse Stude went with th
em. Phyllis was of course eight. And - she was bridesmaid, little bridesmaid. They went away, of course they did, they went to the Isle of Wight. I remember because dad said what a small family it seemed, it had gone to pieces all of a sudden you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 There was only two gone wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well there was Dolly and I gone, Fred was no longer going with them, he was going on his own, he always came with us you see before so there was three less. That halved it. And he said - I remember him saying how nice it was. He said it was nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you usually go to seaside places or sometimes to country places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Nearly always to the seaside. Dad loved the country but mother - mother liked the sea. So if she was with us on holiday we always went to th
e sea. He hated - we went for many years and he - how he hated it. Because it was so flat. To please mother we went many years to Cliftonville. It's out - you know, it's part of Thanet. Isle of Thanet, yes. And - it's terribly flat. He loved - he loves - 
he loves country and hills, see, he came of Devon stock and it was in his - in his blood. He adored Devon. He hardly missed a year without he went to Devon, all his life practically.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He'd go down for a walking holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. Yes. And we went 
for about seven years running to Dawlish. The same - same spot every time 'til mother said she was getting tired of it and then she got him - persuaded him to go to Cliftonville. We went there for several years, once we went up to the Highlands. And - to 
Scarborough. That's all I can remember - oh, and once we went to another one, what was it we went to the other one, Seaford once. Didn't like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At a place like Cliftonville or Scarborough or Dawlish, how would you spend the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Most of us w
ould be up in the morning, we were all - all - children - you couldn't keep us in bed, they're not like them now, you can't get them up. But - we used to be out of bed very early in the morning and perhaps in front - that's why he liked Dawlish. Was that 
love - those lovely la}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 nes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 running through the high - a little river running through High Street where the swans were. We used to go out and feed the swans and collect their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 eathers in the morning. And perhaps we'd go across to the farm with a big basin to 
get the cream. And come back. Well then after that we might go - dad would come with us sometimes - we would go - cave searching, or rock hunting, you know, he - he used to be a little bit afraid of us getting trapped in the caves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you'd do things with a bit of a purpose would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, and we'd go out with him in - mackerel fishing in a small rowing boat with a line, and that sort of thing. And of course I don't know what - what we did much in the evenings at Dawlish, I can't remember, I
 think that we used to have a few sing-songs, we generally were - made friends while we were down there. We had friends you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where were you staying - stayed with friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, we stayed at a - a private - a private place, we'd have our own private rooms but they'd do the cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you have the whole house to yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. No. No, we used to go - the landlady was there 'cos I remember Freddy got into row because he flirted with the landlady's daughter. He was only about sevent
een, she'd be about twenty-four. Lily her names was, but - we used to - go down there and we'd have our own sitting room and our own bedrooms and - the maid would go out and do the shopping, they could do all our cooking for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would there be other families in the house as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very seldom. We were the only family as a rule.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So the other family devoted itself to looking after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's right, and themselves. That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you went to a seaside place, what did you spend most of the time doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
What after we went - after - all sorts of things. Listening to the band, of course we all - always loved the band. Used to love sit round that band and enjoy ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you bather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. And of course no mixed bathing. Never did any mixed bathing when I was single, it was all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You had to go to a separate beach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Went to a separate beach and I can remember that they used to - have a horse to pull us out into the sea. In the bathing machines. Yes, o
h yes, I can remember that. And my dad was a wonderful swimmer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You undress in the bathing machine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Undressed in the bathing machine, then they dragged you out into the water, because they were so respectable you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you'd go down into the water and really nobody saw you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Nobody saw you, they'd have a job to when I think of those awful bathing dresses down here, shocking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your legs were bare weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, you'd have little - you had them down here with a litt
le frill. Oh they was funny. Funny little mob cap on their head, oh dear. I used to take mine off, let my hair all go in the sea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you just got straight down into the sea and nobody could see you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And back again and then when you were dressed they'd pull you up again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When those bathing dresses got wet in the sea they would be all heavy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - all clinging things. Oh horrible. When I think of - the - afterwards when I used to go in the university suits, were different you know, and - 
but you know the first time I put on a university suit, I was married, the first time I put on a university suit I felt very - very very - anything but respectable as I came out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What is a university suit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It's an ordinary plain }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ne, you know, like the school ones, with the - with just - just like an ordinary vest and tight fitting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It still came down to your knees?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. No, no. Oh no, no, no. Just - just like the ordinary - gym - a gym suit right be you know. It - it fitted - oh 
they were quite nice but I felt as if I wasn't dressed the first time I wore one. Bare, yes, although really it covered - I've got one in the drawer now. I - I would put it on now, it'd be quite up to date. But there were no bits cut out of it you see, it
 just fitted you that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At what stage did you start wearing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh after I was married. Oh - I should think, yes, about 1910, yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you still have to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 use}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  the bathing machine when you were wearing one of those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, they'd started building them on the beach then, you know, the proper - proper huts. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And it was all right for you to walk down into the sea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, but you always had something over your shoulders. Great big towel or something. And you left 
that off near the sea as you went in you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You wouldn't walk down the beach in just the swimsuit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not - not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 brazenly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  no. You - you'd come out, you'd put that round you and go to your cabin to dress yourself. You wouldn't lay and sunbathe. No. That was later of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It's one area in which things have changed an awful lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh terribly. Yes. I think myself it's gone a little - little far now. I mean, there's nothing very pretty in seeing naked bodies - practically naked bodies lying
 all over the beach. I don't think it's pretty. I don't think the human form you know, except in the very young girl, is particularly pretty. I think it's much better draped.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I think our bodies are much too white to be attractive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, they are 
really, I mean, you go to Spain and you see those girls with their brown figures. They look - mind you, in Spain they're not allowed of course to go about with the sort of costumes, just bikinis and knickers, they have to cover their bodies. But they're l
o
vely to look at. But they're natural, they look as if they blend with the scenery as it were. But as you say, our bodies; are white, they look naked. Well - they really look naked, there's something about them that I don't think is at all attractive and -
 
except in the very - I like to see young children and that sort of thing, they're all right, or even up to about fourteen or fifteen. But I think after that - except in very exceptional cases, I don't think the human body is attractive. Much better with s
omething on it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On the occasions when the nurse did go, would she do things with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh well, you see, she'd do the shopping for one thing. She probably supervised the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 food}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  that they baby had to have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And she'd look after him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Particularly. She was the -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If all the rest of you went to the beach would she go to with the baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Probably. She might do. It would depend. If she - if the baby was sleeping perhaps - because sometimes you want them to sleep indoors f
or a little while, then she would stay. But otherwise she would go down to the beach too, yes, and we'd wander off to various places you know. And of course we had - we had - we had a trap, always had a trap. And - Fred and I used to generally have - we'd
 
have a pony of our own while we were there. We used to go - go riding and that sort of thing. So that really the day was pretty full, and we did a lot of walking. We were great walkers. We used to going to Dartmoor and climbing the mountains there and tha
t
 sort of thing. Oh we - we used to enjoy our holidays in Devon, there's so much to do the there you know, the day was never long. Never long enough. Walk up to the top of - oh what do they call it - Mount something at Dawlish, in - before breakfast. Miles
 up. Yes. But we didn't know how lucky we were, we were only saying so, my sister and I last week. We took it all as a matter of course. But really we didn't know how lucky we were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Saturday? Oh what do you mean, when I was older, when I was grown up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were beginning school, when you were ten or eleven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Saturdays? We used to sometimes we'd go out - some - mother'd go out shopping sometimes on Saturday and we'd go w
ith her, or I would any rate, because I was always the eldest girl, I really did more than the other because I was the eldest, I was older. Not a lot, but two years when you're that age makes a difference, see it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 doesn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  make much now but it made a difference then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So this was all about 1900?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
We generally got something on, something to do with the church or something to do with somewhere we got on. It - it might be a picnic. Really for the church. We might go into Highgate woods with a couple of 
friends and play rounders. With somebody grown up with us, not always our own folks, perhaps some other girl's parents you see. But we went - because we knew a lot of people, a lot of children, from different homes. And I used to spend a lot of Saturdays 
down at Tollington Park at the Hobbs. They were such a big family and there was always fun going on you see, there were five boys - five girls and four boys. So we'd - that's what our Saturdays were like. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 We never did things that when the - I mean nobody ever went when they - when the films first came in, in the very beginning and they had children's - mornings, none of us went. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Wesley or Phyllis were never allowed to go to them. No, they never let them go. Never let them go to any place of amusement when th
ey were small but they weren't accompanied by an adult you see. There was always a sort of - protection there. Too much perhaps. But there was always protection.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But I suppose that was pretty normal for those times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, it was - for those times. For decent families.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were about fifteen about 1905?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I'd plenty of boys then. All the boys in the neighbourhood I think. Because you see, meeting them at church. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 At fifteen I went to the school in Hornsey High. Well attached to tha
t not far away was the boys Grammar School who were also stationers, which was of course in existence in those days still, and having lived in the neighbourhood for so long, and having - girlfriends with brothers and that sort of thing I knew everybody pr
actically you see.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How would you come across the boys, on the way home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well I - no, well we would meet them sometimes through the school. But more often than not - it - they'd be - first of all we'd meet the brothers of the sisters a
nd then they'd introduce other boys and then my brother who was living with grandma at Clapton, he - he used to come up to the parties and bring about six boys with him. And then of course we got to know them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 You were very,very lucky weren't you?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, plenty of - oh there was no shortage of boys believe me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you spend Saturdays in those days when you were round about fifteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When I was round about fifteen, oh usually I'd get up - perhaps I'd do a bit of shopping for mum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On my - sometimes on my own. An - sometimes I'd get the Hobbs to go, one of the Hobbs to come with me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would this be shopping for food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes - sometimes food - sometimes food, sometimes - things like gloves or stockings or a
nything that - little minor things. And - then we'd generally have something to do, we'd either go to a music hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the afternoon would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, in the evening. In the afternoon no. In the afternoon we'd be a bit more at home, perhaps rea
ding. I read a lot - read a lot on Saturday afternoons. I can remember now reading - I used to go up in the park and read and what we used to call the little park then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You would sit on your own and read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then at - that bit now, and then it was
 turned into the American Gardens. And they took away all the - 'cos it was all railed in, that little park. In the old days, it was quite a private place, proper courting - courting place where - where young - young folk went there, boyfriends. And a lot
 
of seats you see were there too, which are not there now. So - oh we passed - then we did - had to be home to meals you see, we'd have to be in to meals, two o'clock on Saturday, dinner. Because dad wasn't in early. And so we used to have dinner - but - a
fter we got out of the nursery stage. Then in the afternoon perhaps we'd read, dad'd go and have a rest - perhaps out in the garden if it was summertime, he'd go out and have a - have a rest in the tent and - mother would go up and have a rest on the bed.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What tent is this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh we had a - he had a tent in the garden, a square tent in which sometimes he'd sleep on very fine nights out there. He was proper outdoor you know, he ought not to have been in an office at all, dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He had this tent in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where he could go and sleep on a hot night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And take a rest on Saturday afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. Oh - people look at me you know when I said he had this tent erected there instead of a swing chair, he
 had a - a swing seat, he had a tent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was inside, a cap bed or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It had a camping bed inside and a camp chair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was this tent used for any other purpose, to play in or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, because he didn't have it until we were
 growing up you see, after he went over to 78. 'Cos we had a summerhouse at - at 55. No, we were all growing up then, it was really more for dad than anybody else, because he loved the - he loved to go out in the garden on a hot night to sleep out there.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So he might do that on Saturday afternoon and you might read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, or else he'd go to bowls. And sometimes he'd go up to the park, he belonged to the bowling club up there, sometimes he'd go up to bowl. Sometimes he'd go down to the Conservative club. 'Cos of course he belonged to that too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then in the evening you might go to a music hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Then in the evening we'd always have somewhere to go Saturday evening, always went to a music hall or theatre. Or - when we were younger, still 
lantern lectures, to do with the church and that sort of thing. Never a dull moment. I can never remember being bored. Like the youngsters are today. Wet or fine, hail or snow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You had a bigger variety of things to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I think you made them, you
 had to you see, you made them for yourselves. And we kept a scrap book, now that'd take up a lot of time, I had three, I got rid of them not so many years ago, I had three great albums of film stars, not film stars, actresses and - all the old actresses.
 
All those - I got rid of them, it's a pity because - nobody seemed to care. But they're beginning to come out again now. And - that'd take quite a long time. Then I had a scrapbook. And then I had another book in which - after I - I - while I was at Cusac
ks College I belonged to a debating society, well I used to make - I used to take cuttings from debates and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How old were you at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About fifteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was around about 1905?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you do this sort of thing Saturday afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Oh yes. Oh yes. Paste up things, if I'd got anything to paste up either in the - actresses - actress album or perhaps - cuttings from the - our debating society.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What do you mean cuttings, about the debates?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, you see, we used to have these debates and they used to be taken down. And the minutes were taken. Well all those I used to collect and write up. Yes. Used to be quite interesting to read some of your old speeches you know after it sound
ed a bit - a bit young some of them but they were interesting. Oh yes -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So there were a lot of things like that to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It - you - you filled your own time up instead of depending on the goggle box which we've all got so keen on now. It's been a
 - death - that's been the death to what I call - initiative in play. It's been the death - it's been the death to good conversation. Absolute death to it. Now you go into a house and - you - you'd sit and talk with people - air your different views, perh
aps to be - you can talk for hours and not get bored. But now - that thing goes on - and you really don't interchange your mental thoughts at all with people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you spend Sundays when you were round about fifteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I used to get up in the morning and go to church. Then I - after -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, usually on my own or perhaps with a friend. Not mother and dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they go separately?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very seldom went at all. Mum did for a time I believe, we - 'cos she wasn't confirmed until just before Dolly was born. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they make you go or did you go of your own volition?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh we were supposed to go. It became a habit and then it became a pleasure because you met the people you knew, the same people you knew. We used 
to - yes, we used to have to go when we were very young and we - we - couldn't say that we'd been when we hadn't because they always put the sermon in the paper and dad used to ask us what the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 sermon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  was. Always put it in the paper. What the sermon was to be. The Vicar -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The local paper was this in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. In the - in - I think it - yes, in the local paper, it would be in the local paper, although I don't remember them often having the local paper, yes, they had the Journal I think. And - they alwa
ys put what the sermon was going to be on the Sunday so he knew the chapter and verse that was going to be used for the sermon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And when you came back he would question you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He would question us. Yes. That's one of the times he found me out tell
ing a fib and he was so angry. 'Cos I said I'd been to church and I hadn't. I did it once, 'cos I knew he could find out after that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And he was able to tell?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, he was able to tell. Well then after church was over we'd go in Finsbury Park for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 church parade}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . This was regular as clockwork.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was the church parade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The church parade was like the whole of that park, right down to Finsbury Park gates was lined with victories and traps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Just going round and round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They w
ouldn't - they'd park them and then they'd walk - the lake - the lake was the parade. They'd all walk round the lake. In all their finery and it would be finery too, some beautiful gowns they used to wear. After that, having done that for about - perhaps 
w
alked round twice, they'd then get into their various vehicles and roll off or if we - myself and the Hobbs, we used to walk - we used to start walking, sometimes with boys we knew, sometimes on our own, but we - go over to - walk all the way to Parliamen
t
 Hill Fields. That's a long way. And always from Finsbury Park we'd come - we'd come right along Hornsey Lane, into Highgate and then along Bishops Avenue right - Highgate. And back again by - back again by two o'clock dinner and we wouldn't leave church 
'til twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That must be nearly eight miles there and eight miles back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I should think it was about three or four. Because you know - if you know the - if you know the short cuts dear, if you know the short cuts. If you go from here - how we use
d to go was this. We used to go from here and we used to go up Crouch Hill, through the pathway, there at the top of Crouch Hill, you know the pathway runs right through to Hornsey, we used to walk through there and - yes, and then come out and go across 
the Hornsey Lane, that brought us out by the - St Josephs church. Yes. Yes. Well they cut through to Bishops Avenue, and straight through to Parliament Hill Fields. You see, not going }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 the}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  way }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 he 210 bus goes, it goes all round the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 From St Josephs church it's a long way up to Bishops Avenue isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Not far. Not - not far as we thought then, far as youngsters would call it today. But we used to do that every Sunday morning and back again for two o'clock dinner. And we'd be back for it too - bec
ause dad would start if we weren't, he wouldn't wait a minute. Not if guests were coming. Guests were late, it was their rudeness, they'd - for them to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 apologize}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . Then in the afternoon - oh we always had something to do. Off again somewhere or other. To tea. Perhaps to friends, to tea again. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 
And - perhaps sometimes, sometimes you'd go to church again in the evening. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
It would depend on what - what was on or who was speaking. 'Cos we really - we used to take an interest in the sermon you know and the service then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said as teenagers there was a lot of pleasure for you in the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
There was a lot of pleasure, things that they got up and one thing and another you know and outings too. Lot of outings. So that - really our - our day was full. The
 weekend went like that, like a flash. My sisters would go - 'cos they - directly they got sweethearts they might go up the river, rowing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they have to ask your father especially if they could do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well they were getting a little bit old
er then, they'd - no, I think they'd tell dad they were going - he'd say, well where are you girls off to this afternoon, you see. And they'd tell him, oh we're going to Weybridge, we're going up the river.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And they would say they were going with their young men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Oh yes, they'd say they were going - they'd tell him they were going. And we shan't be back until about - ten. Well don't make it later than eleven, he'd say. This was when they were older. But he did - he did - never gave them o
pen house to walk in when they liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that you had quite a - lot of freedom compared with your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I think - you know - people never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You always got two and six pocket money when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's right. An buy gloves. Buy gloves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And it was regular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, regularly, provided you didn't misbehave yourself in between, then you didn't get it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Apart from the gloves what you'd spend the money on would be mostly going in for coffee?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 G
oing into a restaurant - yes, or perhaps if you saw - or fancy ribbon you know to sew on something or other to make - 'cos we were rather a vain lot I've come to the conclusion looking back on the years. We spent much more time on thinking about clothes. 
Nothing else much to think about, I mean, there was - people changed their clothes so often. You were always buying little bits and pieces or perhaps a - a pretty - lace collar or something like that. Shawls - to make it look more attractive, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Apart from the servants did anybody outside the family help your mother to look after her house or the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, only the charwoman used to come in on Friday. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 There weren't any friends or relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, - Grandma - oh dear granny, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She did a lot to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh she did enormous amount of help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She used to send up - food and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Food - they used to have - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13974902\charrsid8657389 granddad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  used to fill a great market basket every Saturday morning. And - when we went away I told you we've come back and the whole of the place has been recurtained from top to bottom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 By your grandmother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, grandma. Oh she was wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What happened while your mother was having one of the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
When she was having the children generally - generally grandma - of course grandma had Freddy al together at one time but we'd go down there and stay some of us. At any rate there was always somebody to look after us at home you see when she was having th
e children. She had them all at home. And - and a nurse in the house always for a month. Because in those days they didn't - expect people to get out of bed }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 when}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  they were having babies until a month. And that's the reason why I think so many them were so much - they've got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  many invalids today. So many women going back with prolapse and that sort of thing because they will put them on their feet too soon after childbirth? I'm convinced of it, convinced.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They do that to avert thrombosis don't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, they say that but in averting that they get a - making more - more deaths from other things, that's all. They - a month always. Horrified at the very idea of me getting out of bed under a month. But they would - always a month. Always a month. Nin
e days is much too little. Always a month. In fact you weren't allowed to get out of bed and sit in your dressing gown until ten days. I know, they have you up the first in some cases. The first in most of them today, the first day. But I was allowed to g
e
t up on the tenth day and sit in my dressing gown. But I - you could get up and sit in your dressing gown, but you were expected to go back in bed again. You see, the midwife or the nurse, whoever came, you call - of course I always had the doctor as well
, she was in control. And you had to go back - you had to do what she told you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So your grandfather would regularly bring up vegetables and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Everything. Fish, poultry, everything you could think of, not must vegetables. One bag full of fr
uit and veg., the other one full of all sorts of goodies you can imagine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there anything else that he or your grandmother did regularly like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Let me see, now what did they do, only - only look after us - 'cos we always left - we used to
 send - if we'd got three we used to send a couple of maids away on board wages when we went away and take one with us always. But - what happened was that grandma used to bring her maid up then to do all sorts of things in the house. That's the only - th
a
t's the only other time she would do anything. Then I told you they - when they were first married grandma and grandpa paid all the - two servants bills and all the - light, gas and coal, for ten years, while dad was getting through his exams. Oh enormous
 help. Ten years. Because he was married at twenty-nine years - he was married at twenty and he passed his finals at twenty-nine, so that was nine years. They did that all the time, yes. Of course his salary went up enormously after that, it doubled.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So if your mother was ill or confined to bed some of the children would be sent to your grandmother's?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. If it - if it was nec - if they thought it was necessary but of course we all were in - the house was so big, we usually had somebody who could look after us when we were small.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember what happened when one of your younger brothers or sisters were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I remember Phyllis and - and Wes being born quite plainly. I can remember Phyllis being born because - of course Wes - w
hen Wesley was born I actually discussed it with mum, you see, I was getting on - because I was seventeen. And - but when Phyllis was born I was only ten. But I can remember quite plainly. I can remember being told I - I was likely to have a little brothe
r
 and sister but I particularly remember the morning at school when all of sudden with a maid - one of the maids turns up at the school, we always went home for dinner, turns up at school with a big basket of food. We were to stay at dinner - we were to st
ay for dinner at school because - you're mother's not very well. And then arriving home in the evening and hearing that we'd got a baby sister.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When your little brother was born and you say you discussed it with your mother, you knew then that she was expecting a baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Oh yes, we used to talk to her quite a lot about things, she used to say to me - in fact I was just getting to the age then when the boys I went out with used to come and call for me at the house, they used to allow that, I
 told you when I got there and - I remember Holt Hewitt coming home and - she'd got a black - Chinese silk dressing gown all in - all inserted with valentines lace, oh beautiful thing it was, and he said that - he said how charming she was, well that was 
the night before Phyllis was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 One gets the impression that in those days that was the kind of subject that was taboo?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh well it wasn't. Because mum told me like - and I used to say to her, what - what do you want mum? And she said, well you
 know dear, we've got a houseful of girls, 'cos there four one on top of the other you see, she said, I hope it will be a little boy. And it was and of course it was in the change.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you knew she was expecting a baby and you knew she was actually carrying a baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Oh yes, I knew she was carrying a baby. I knew about a babies all right at that time 'cos I can remember going down and - seeing a poor relation of ours, she was on the stage too and she was going to have a baby and I remember 
sitting at her feet, remember it as plain as anything, sitting at her feet and putting my head on her lap and feeling the baby move and being so repulsed. Sort of - a nasty feeling, so repulsed that I always - that I really - I - I think I was frightened 
more than anything else looking back on it. But I must only be about fifteen then. I'd be about fifteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, we had people that we - grandma - grandma and grandpa Jackson lived quite - my dad
's people lived by. My great-grandfather lived by. There were give generations of us all - all near each other, all north Londoners', all north Londoners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How much did you see of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh quite a lot. Oh yes. Quite a lot before and after. I used to walk all the way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Before and after what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
After I was married. That was during - before the 1914 war you see. I used to walk all the way over from Crouch Hill - with my two babies in a pram, all the way over to Lower Clapton. Every fortnight
 and back again with the pram. To see my dear old granny. I wouldn't have missed for anything. And I used to come back with a great deal more than I went with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Before you were married the family did see a lot of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes, se saw a lot of our relatives. All of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they come to see you or would you go to see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Both. Both. We more - I think it would be more going over there, grandma did a fair amount of coming over to see us and of course granddad came every week. 
Never failed. Every Saturday he was there. And - of course - Freddy, he was brought up with grandma from a tiny - he was about - three. He used to come over and bring his boyfriends so we were never without boyfriends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your parents had friends didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. And they used to come to the house quite a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that was where they saw their friends in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Oh yes. They used to visit them too of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they also see them perhaps at the Conservative club or somewhere like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the early days, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Why do you say in the early days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well because you see mum got to the stage where she didn't go out much and then when dad used to suggest a walk round the houses she wouldn't go. Who wants to walk 
round the houses, I've seen enough of them. Oh I look back on those days, they bring back some memories.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother and father have the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 More or less. Mum had a few friends that dad never knew of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he have some friends of his own?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well she used to meet his friends when she used - she used to go to the congresses and the different does of the office, she used to meet them then. And of course she used to meet his chess playing friends to 'cos they used to come to the house. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where would she see the friends of her own that her father didn't really know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh, at home. They'd call on her or she might call on them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You mean when your father wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. In the daytime. Yes, in the daytime. I don't think either of them liked each other's friends very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your father have some friends of his own that your mother didn't know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh only a very few except office friends of course, he'd meet colleagues at the office that she 
didn't meet, she used to meet them on social occasions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would friends be invited into the home often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 One period a great deal, but after her health broke down not so much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they be offered something to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. She n
ever had a visitor without she gave them something to eat or - most hospital people we were in those days. So were the Hobbs weren't they. The idea of you going - going away without having had something to eat, 'cos there was always plenty to eat there yo
u see. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of things would they offer them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - it may - depends didn't it, who the friends were. Sometimes they'd - 'cos we'd have a hot supper sometimes. Sometimes they'd - as well as midday dinner we'd have hot supper, perhaps he
ight tea and hot supper - they'd stay for that, and another time they'd make piles of sandwiches and bring them up you see, with savouries and that sort of thing. But the maids would do that. See, they'd get that all ready.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they come on any particular days or occasions, these friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh mum had an at home day. Yes, they had an at home day once a month. Once a month, yes. When the vicar would come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did she let people know when she was at home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh you leave a card to the effe
ct that you'll be at home on such and such a day. When you first went to a neighbourhood in those days you know, people came and left their cards on you who didn't know you and you went and - you returned the visit and left your card behind. Silly lot of 
r
ubbish. But it was part of that life and it was done in quite - quite sort of middle class suburbia. Oh didn't - oh - nobody ever went out even - from my age, from the time I was fifteen I had my own printed cards. And my dad said, and I can always rememb
er my dad saying to him me when I showed him the first one, don't like those very much you want a copperplate made you know. Copperplate card. We used to - used to \{ILLEGIBLE\} them to all the boys, what a waste of money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that the friends invited in were mostly your mother's friends or your father's friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh I should think that it was about - I should think it was half and half and I should think it was more ours than anyone. The girls, yes, more our friends. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would friends call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh quite usual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about neighbours, would they call in casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Sometimes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And your parents would go out to visit friends and neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said that in those days people made their own amusements, when your parents got together with friends and neighbours what did they do?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Talk. Or perhaps have music. You might have had music. Oh yes, quite a lot of music when somebody'd sing, somebody'd play an
d - that's really what the - you did when visitors came. And somebody'd recite - dreadful business. Yes. Making them recite whatever they wanted to or not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they ever play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What - mother and father? No. No, mum - mum wouldn't have - s
he would never play cards. She detested them. I think dad would have done if he could - if - if mother had - was - had been willing, he would have played cards when they came, he loved bridge too. But she couldn't bear it. Her idea was to get out if he go
t anybody there who could play chess or cards.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
You know the way people divide society into different social classes or groups, in that period before 1918 did you think of some people as belonging to one class and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. They - 
there was a class distinction. Definitely. There was the working class. The working class and middle class. And the - aristocrats. But you - you was beginning to lose it by the time the 1914 war came really. There was - you got a lot of people who were be
g
inning to make a lot of money, we used to call them the parvenus. They - no breeding, but plenty of money, you see, the money would get them there and you might find quite a poor person who came from a wonderful family, very well bred. Definitely class di
stinction was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And it was easy to tell into which class anyone fell?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 More or less. Usually when they opened their mouths I think that was the - real criterion, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you felt your family were middle class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, were middle class family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of people belonged to the middle class along with yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Mostly - mostly - successful business men and professional - professional gentlemen. Bankers - insurance - especially inside insurance, not so much the agents,
 they came in rather a - rather lower grade, but the - successful business man and the - professional.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of people belonged to the working class then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Mostly the artisan - mostly - mostly - mostly the artisan class, the people who the - 
like the carpenters, these people, they all - they did much of the - the work done by hand, they're really clever men. They are today. They are today and the - the builder perhaps. - Painters I mean, the people like that. Perhaps not the master builders, 
I
 suppose they - well - would have been considered more in the middle class, the master builders, but the actual workmen themselves. Railwaymen. And their families. Extremely respectable, nice class of people but still they were considered the working - an
d considered themselves working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of people did you think belonged to the aristocracy or the upper classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well we were - we were very critical of them then. Directly they started stepping outside their class and marrying actresse
s and we thought they were lowering themselves. Buy really the title people. And those who attended the courts and that sort of thing you know. Debutantes and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You felt as a family they ought to keep to their class did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Y
es, I think there was rather the idea that because they - they thought that you would be happier in keeping with your own class - although, mind you, I don't think - I think a lot of the middle class people did marry into the aristocracy. And some of them
 
had come from excellent families. I mean county families. My own family was a county family. The Fulfords were a county family, none of them worked until my - never did any work at all until my grandfather - my great - grandfather - died. But - the countr
y - in fact - if you really got down to rock bottom - that people considered the county families - were better than the real aristocracy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you say county?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 County. Yes. They - well a county family means - a family that has been supported by the
 estates they've got and - yes. They didn't actually work for their living except in politics and that sort of thing. They were the backbone, they were the real aristocracy, we always thought they were the real aristocracy anyway because most of them coul
d
 trace their pedigrees back for hundreds of years. And they're still known to this day, the sort of people with a pedigrees are accumulated and put into the British Museum you see. Of course there was a lot of foreign blood introduced in the aristocracy, 
well we wouldn't think that was good, intermarrying and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that you were brought up to treat people of one class differently from another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Definitely - decidedly and definitely no. You - you were taught to be ki
nd - considerate - courteous to everybody. I told you, my father was - had one trite saying and that was, court - courtesy costs nothing, but it opens the doors to many opportunities. And he was right. But - although if we - if we were heard talking to th
e servants as if they were dirt like sometimes you do if you're a bit young, we were very quickly reprimanded.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But even the working class people, even if you could gain nothing from them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh treat them with proper respect of course. And you were 
taught it didn't matter who it was and what their class was, a boy was taught to always address his elder as sir. Even though he was a - even if he was a - what was then considered the lower class of person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you ever told to curtsey to anybody?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Only at school affairs. Always did. Always had - if royal were there. Anybody of the royal family were there or anybody of any very great - a notability which they always had for prizegivings and opening certain new wings and that sort of thing. Well
 then you were taught to - oh yes, you went - you went through a long lesson of swinging a leg behind you and - curtseying properly too. You got called over the coals if you didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said the boys had to say sir to anybody who was older than them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there anything that you were supposed to do in that way to show respect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No - only that - just - that when you were first introduced you never shook hands, I can always remember that. You just bowed - an acknowledgement. You only 
shook hand the second time you met them. Little things like that. Silly, all of them but still they - they were part of that period.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any people you called sir or ma'am?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, if they - if they - one - if you were - if you got somebo
dy you were introduced to from the aristocracy, say it was the Lady somebody or other, you'd address her by her title, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But did you as a girl call anybody sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Girls didn't have to, weren't expected to. But the boys were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Apart from the servants did you remember anybody showing respect to your parents in some way, like calling them sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, any - any - any boy who Freddy bought up of his own class, he wouldn't have dreamt of saying anything but sir to dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Or a boyfriend of yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, it would always be sir. Mr Holt in fact made his sons - who were - he was a - an oil merchant as I told you, he made - his sons all had to address him as sir. Even his sons. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the district around here were you lived, can you remember who were considered the most important people in the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Mostly the professional men I suppose. Politicians, 'cos they were all - nearly all titled anyway our politicians - our - our Conservative party nearly always had a titled man.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And they actually lived in the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, they didn't. They used to visit the area, but of course they used to hold meetings and people used to go down to the different - Town Hall to see them. But they were the - th
ey - they were the type of people and I think otherwise it was mostly the professional men. Doctors, bankers - actuaries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you come into contact with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, a lot. Quite a lot. They were in my father's - similar - they were colleagues you see when he met them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Why do you think it was they were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Because they didn't work with their hands. Just - just that. That's the only reason. Because they didn't work with their hands. They - they worked with their brain
s, it was - it was a case of whether you worked with your brains or whether you worked with your hands, if you worked with your hands you were an artisan. And then - then came the - then he went a step higher and was the master man. That was a grade highe
r. Then you came to the professional who was higher still. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about the shopkeepers in the area, they'd be middle class would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who would they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Mostly their own kind. Other shopkeepers. See, mostly of their own kind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about the clergy in the area, who would they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well I suppose really and truly they visited everybody in those days, they - I don't think you could - of course when I say they visited them - the people h
ad the at homes they stayed for some considerable time with if they came. Whereas if - perhaps if they went to visit the other people they wouldn't stay so long and they wouldn't take food of course because the people couldn't afford to give it to them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But they would visit everybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. In fact I think in those days the clergy were much more clerical mind you than they are today because they - they did visit the poor regularly. Oh yes. And it was more - it was more or a religious age really
, there was a lot of hypocrisy about, just going on Sunday and dressing up and that sort of thing but - there was also a lot of good. A lot.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about the teachers in your area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh well the teachers were - considered - at the board school teac
her, they used to call them board schools in those days, those were the state schools - were not considered quite so - well - they weren't considered - I suppose you'd call them lower middle class really. But the - teachers from the high schools and colle
ges were of course looked up to. They were - because it was an educational thing, they - they were well trained and most of them had very good families, or they wouldn't be doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would the board school teachers, being considered slightly lower middle class, associate with the professional people in the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. They'd associated - the better class teachers, not the council school ones. No, no. The better class teachers from the grammar schools and that sort of thing, they'd visit the gi
rls' homes. And that sort of thing. They were really considered on an equal, oh definitely. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about employers, employers in factories or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I say - the - I suppose when they got to be master men you'd - oh I suppose they wou
ld be middle class, they would be considered middle class, perhaps not the top drawer but still middle class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they be friendly with the other middle class people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of people would you say used to go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - all sorts. All kinds, yes, all sorts. Oh yes, the churches were packed and - because I suppose there wasn't a great deal to do on Sunday other than go to church. And of course they used to have the - the poorer used to go to see the nice dresses a
nd the beautiful hats. It was really the church parade business that attracted the - the - people who weren't truly religious went for that reason and because everybody else went, it's the one time in which they did mix, although the - although the - majo
rity of people had their own pew, who could afford it. And the others sat at the back of the church you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What happened with the Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well there would be no class distinction in the Sunday school, you'd all be of the same - little ch
ildren, it wouldn't matter which class they came. They wouldn't have any special teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But you made quite a lot of your friends trough Sunday school didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, one or two I met through Sunday - but you'd be - children were taught t
o be - I think, they were taught to be selective. They usually chose their own kind, you know, people who were on a - one sort of - from a speaking point of view. They were taught to judge by that. Really. Rightly or wrongly - my son says wrongly. But rig
htly or wrongly they were taught to judge by that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say speaking more than clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Yes. Much more so. Because some of those poor people you know, they - they - were quite capable of washing, they turned their children out beautiful
ly dressed. But of course when they opened their mouths you wouldn't be - you could tell that they weren't so educated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there a difference between church and chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. There was a big difference there. Church people didn't like chapel peo
ple and chapel people didn't like church people, Presbyterians didn't like; Wesleyans. Oh yes, quite a lot of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did that tie in with the class thing, which sort of people were chapel and which were church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I think there was a fair scatte
ring. No, I - honesty and truly I don't think that, I think religion has been something that has been handed down and that's of course there were a lot very - very nice people Presbyterians, a lot of very nice people Wesleyans.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The chapel wasn't associated with one class in particular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, no. Oh no. That - that didn't happen. The Hobbs were chapel. I was high church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say that there w
ere different groups, different kinds of working class people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well - yes. I should say there were different class working - certainly the rail men - railwaymen were a cut above - what shall I say - the stevedores and people like that, they were all 
railwaymen, the men who drove the engine, an engine driver for instance would be very much above a stevedore who would be on the same strain with him, but he'd certainly be in a superior class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could you describe the difference between a railwayman's family and a stevedores family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
It would be very difficult because you see, it depends on the individual in that case. Some people would - they would spend it, it didn't matter, the class they came from, they'd spend every penny, perhaps they'd be te
etotalers and keep a very nice home going and that sort of things, another man would spend all his money in the public house. You see, so that it was very difficult to judge. And - of course I wasn't on visiting terms with them so I can't tell you quite w
hat their home life - life was like. Because mine was different you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you think that one group would feel itself superior to the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh certainly they would. Oh yes. It wasn't really until - it's one of the good things, although I'm no
t a great supporter of Trade Unions, it wasn't until Trade Unioni came in that you got a leveling down. You see, when they all belonged to the same union you got a leveling down. Yes, they all felt sort of brotherhood if you like. A sort of brotherhood.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were some families in the area thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Oh yes. And you - you find some very very respectable people amongst the poor. And you could tell, directly you saw their houses. One house would look like a slu
m, another one'd be most beautifully kept. I think they were rather judged, really, the working class people were rather judged the way they lived. You know, from their - from their personal habits and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say there was a distinction of this kind between labourers and craftsmen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. A definite distinction between those. The - oh yes, 'cos a craftsman of course, he was a craftsman, the fact that he could - he could make with his hands something beautiful. Which he cou
ld. Oh yes, apprenticed. All apprenticed to these trades. And he used to see the beautifully turned out work, I mean, the furniture you buy today - well, it's rubbish compared to what they used to turn out then, so much cheaper, because they were very bad
l
y paid. Very badly paid. When you look back on it. And they worked nearly - you see, the ordinary business hours, they were working man, wasn't the house that they have today. It was from eight o'clock, some of them started even at six. Eight o'clock unti
l eight at night earliest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I think - of the go, I should say dad was a little more, to use the word in it's broadest sense - I should say dad was a little bit more 
snobbish of the two. Mum liked people for what they were. If she took a fancy to them it wouldn't matter how much they had in their pockets. Like that. I always say that for her, she liked people for their sake. If they appealed to her she liked them. Did
n't matter what class they came from.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Suppose there were some children in your school who didn't behave very nicely, didn't speak very nicely, and yet she liked their mother, would she still prefer you not to play with the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can't rememb
er anything like that you see, it was very difficult for me to be able to place that because I don't know what would happen. No, I don't know - I can't remember any - I'm just trying to think back, if there was any particular case I can think of like that
. I can't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was it possible at that time would you say to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh I think so. I mean the sort of - if it as - if you get - if you get a chance. At school it was - mind you couldn't keep a good man down, or a good girl ei
ther. Who was very brilliant and pulled herself - I think she could be - oh yes, it was quite possible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She would move from the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Working - working class to the middle classes. I've even known them from the working classes go up int
o the aristocracy. You see, but they were freaks. They weren't usual, they were sort of exceptions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said the aristocracy would occasionally marry actresses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That - yes, they'd marry - oh that was - that was considered - they were always - es
pecially making a marriage alliance when they did that. But - of course - and they weren't considered the real aristocracy afterwards. Because they'd married an actress. Of course some of those actresses have really come up from working class people.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you know of people going downwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, poverty took them down sometimes. But you can never take away the breeding if it was there. I've met them. You can tell directly they - you spoke to them, went into their homes that they'd seen better days
. You see, it's something that you don't lose - really. Unless you take up some vice or other and of course that's destructive in any case.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember any particular person or family who did move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I would have said
 the Holts did really but when I come to see their pedigree they didn't you see, they've really come - both have really come from quite good families. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What would you have said about the Holts?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I would have said the Holts - well dad al
ways called them, he always saw they were parvenus because they - they did get on well and they were inclined to boast about what they'd got, well he - he thought that was ill bred. You see. But they were brilliant. They were clever, all of them, every si
ngle one of them were clever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was he thinking that they had been working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I don't think he'd think of them in that time, he'd think of them in the terms that nasty word common.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That they were common and that they were now middle class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Jumped up. Parvenues in other words.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because they had money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, because they had money. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was meant by that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh that - it's - something - so indescribable. I - I still see it, I can still tell a real gentleman when I see one and a real lady and - there's a - it's a sort of ease. It doesn't matter whether they're talking to the lowest of the low as called or whet
her they're a talking to one of their own kind, they're always the same. They don't change, it doesn't matter who they're talking to, there's the same courtesy shown to the people who work for them, however humble as they would show to their own kind - th
e
ir sister or their brother. You can always tell a real lady, the real one, there's no patronage - in - what I call real aristocracy, no patronage. They don't have to patronize, they don't have to impress you by over dressing or anything like that, they - 
they - they're themselves. It just come natural to them to be courteous. Just a question of behaviour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember seeing a policeman around here regularly when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Making an arrest of anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there a local bobby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh, at every street corner. Half a dozen - I knew a half a dozen of them. Oh yes, used to say good morning Miss, when I came out, yes.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And would you get to know them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes. 'Til they were promoted and most of them were on the beat for quite a long while. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you think of them when you were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I liked them. Oh yes. Always speak to children. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You weren't afraid of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not a little bit, it didn't frighten me to say to I can tell a 
policeman. I used to - I always got on - I always got on well with the policeman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So even though this was London there was still the local policeman you would recognise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh we knew several of them. Knew several of them. I knew one or two
 of the city police too. The - great big fine men, six foot two, six foot three some of them, 'cos they lowered the standard later. But even the Metropolitan police when I was a girl couldn't get in the force if they were anything under five foot ten. No,
 they let - they can be five foot eight now. Lowered it by two inches. Unfortunately. So I've seen - what my daughter-in-law calls the bird brigade, now, because they're so puny looking some of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How do you think policemen treated people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Won
derfully. They were wonderful. Wonderfully. They were kind to everybody who behaved themselves. Of course, they didn't if they got - I mean, they - nowadays think nothing of - if a boy was really misbehaving or knocking another boy about they'd think noth
ing of giving him a little clip round the ear you know. To stop them but - taking them as a whole they were a jolly fine lot of men.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You moved house in the area didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes, over the road. It's enterprising, fifty years in the same road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was your first house rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. No. Both our own houses. Grandpa bought - bought 55 and gave it to them. They never lived in a rented house. Even the one where I was born in Clapton was their own house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember ever feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh no. No. Not at any time. Not at any time. As I told you, I was only ten months old when we went there and grandma and grandpa Jackson were so good you see to them. No, we - I never remember them bein
g without a maid until they were well off and that was towards the end you see, when - mother died in 19 - dad married in 1934 - mum died in 1926. And it was then that they began - that you couldn't get - it was beginning to - you just couldn't get maids.
 However much money you paid. We always had one, but it got to the stage where we had only one. And perhaps a charwoman coming on - on Fridays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you father worked all his life, he was never out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Never. I don't remember him being out of work, not entirely from he started. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So there were never any difficulties like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
When there was someone in the district who, the people disapproved of, a rough family or something like that, was there any special way in which they showed that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well they would - they wouldn't cultivate them that's all, they would ignore them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You wouldn't say hello to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, you wouldn't say hello to them if you - if they were a nuisance, if they were objected to peo
ple simply passed them by. I don't think they - they wouldn't be rude or anything like that but they simply wouldn't know them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember anybody ever being made to leave the district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not very - not - not very - no, not very much. I remem
ber one girl being made to leave school because she'd been - she'd been taking money out of the other girl's pockets and I felt so terribly sorry for her, that's one thing I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 am sorry,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  I felt for that girl because I thought they could have dismissed her wit
hout doing it, they took her before every classroom. Yes. And then expelled her. Thought that was pretty cruel. I thought so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She was a girl of your own kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. She was - I felt sorry for her parents too. It was bad enough to be expelled with
out doing that, but that's what they did. They were pretty hard on you if you - if you broke the rules - at the good schools. More particularly at the good schools than anywhere.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I suppose it had the effect of making the rest of you never steal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well that's it. You see, they wanted - not only that you see, if you didn't do that and it got out parents would take their daughters away because of bad company. I started we started hockey and I got a hockey stick and I came home with my ankle knocked,
 I was forbidden to play that - that terribly boyish game. Hockey. To rough my dad said, much too rough. So hockey stick was relegated up to the attic. And I was told not to play it any more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Hockey is pretty rough isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It can be. Can be. Yes, it can be rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You did sometimes go to the theatre didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Mostly musical comedy. Mostly musical comedy, sometimes tragedy. But - it was mostly - mum liked music, it was mostly musical comedy, 
it's always with her I went, until I got engaged, then of course I used to go with my fianc\'e9.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It would normally be with her, not both your father and mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, never together. I can never remember going to the theatre with them together - 
oh yes, I can. Boxing Day every year we had a - booked seats for the pantomime. And we used to all go to that. After - on Boxing Day. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Ever to any concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. My dad used to take me to - to the concerts at - Sir Henry Wood's concert
s. Used to go to them quite a lot. Those. The Promenade. Yes. And of course we used to go to the office does, to their - they had a very fine theatrical society a that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about the cinema?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh well the cinemas came in of course while I - whil
e I was still - very primitive cinemas but they just started while I was still single. Yes, the silent movies. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever go to any of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Went to them quite a lot, thought they were all right too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When would you go to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well then you see they were open from two o'clock onwards, mostly in the afternoons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So when would you go to the cinema?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Mostly in the afternoon. They were open in the afternoons then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh you, mean while we
 were at school? Oh they - no, I never went while I was at school, not until after I left. No, they ran them - they did start running the Saturday mornings but I wasn't allowed to go, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Why weren't you allowed to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well they were sixpenny - 
we all paid sixpence and all the children from the neighbourhood went, you might get some rough children if you went there. Nobody cares about it now but in those days they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You think that was the reason, that there might be a lot of rough children there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, I think that was the reason they wouldn't let us go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said your father did give you pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. And we were expected to do something for it too. A very little pocket money. Half a crown a week and buy your own gloves out of it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How much were gloves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Gloves, you could buy them for about a shilling. Yes, we had half a crown and we had to pay gloves out of it, our gloves used to be about one and six, but you didn't buy - gloves every week you see. Wouldn't need to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I wonder how much half a crown those days would be worth today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About - ten shillings. Yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Is this when you were a young girl after school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, I got a little bit more after school I think I was getting the magn
ificent sum of five shillings a week. The Holts were getting twelve and six, Morgan was getting fourteen, they had to buy all their - all their own underclothes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But to me that sounds a lot of money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But it - it's - it's only because you're com
paring it - well look at - it's only because you're comparing it with one particular person who gives us more now - but that's considered plenty today. If you - if you - your father and mother buy - buy everything else for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You went to school didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 To the local school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Went - went to the Stradbury and Hornsey High run by the church authorities.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It was connected to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was the name of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Stroud Green High School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What hours did you go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well at - when you were - when - we had an alternative, we could - the hours were really from nine 'til one. Well then you had about three and a half hours homework in which you could either do at home or come tack to 
school and do it. But you had to have that signed if you did it at home, you had to have it signed by your father. The head of the household. To show that you'd only spent the amount of hours put at the side, it was put at the side how many hours you shou
ld put on each subject you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Which did most children do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I think the majority went back. Yes, I think the majority went back, I expect their parents - I think their parents were glad to get rid of them. Otherwise you'd got to - the parents an
y rate had to - 'cos we had our homework, as I say, we had homework, it had to be signed by the parents. And they had to watch and see that the proper amount of time was spent on it or - not too much and not too little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Which did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I used to go back most times.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did all your family did that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Most of us went back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there a particular kind of children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh they were all the - all the daughters of professional gentleman only. In school. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did those hours change as you got older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, they were much the same, you see, it - you didn't - I went to a little - a small school, here in Lancaster Road, first of all until I was about five and a half, six. And then I went to the Stroud Green High, well then we on
ly went in the mornings until we got to about nine. Then all day - then - all day long, you see, you didn't have so much homework, not longer than from seven to nine. Very little homework. And after that you had to do the full three and a half hours.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So even after nine you could stay at home in the afternoon if you wanted to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. We used to do the work at home but then of course it had to be guaranteed that it was done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But all your family went back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We - we always went back, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you followed those hours until what age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - practically - let me see, how old was I when I left the Stroud Green High school. I went from there to Cusacks. So - to Cusacks College in the city, in White Street in the City. That was - I'd be
 about - fourteen, when I left there and went up to the City. Then I was there for about - I might have been nearly fifteen, I was only there for about eighteen months and I left because my - auntie who was only eighteen months older than I, had entered t
he Polytechnic and I - Holloway Polytechnic and I wanted to go with her so I went there. And finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What kind of college was Cusacks College?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh it was a - it was a school and commercial. Both. Yes. You could - either - you could prepare, whic
h I did, a post there in the Polytechnic for the Chamber of Commerce.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was in Cusacks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - yes. Yes. That was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you go there to take secretarial training especially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not specially, no, wanted - just for a - the - more advanced education.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But in Stroud Green High School you followed the same hours in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 From nine o'clock in the morning 'til one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then in the afternoon you could either do three and a half hours at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Or go back and do the three and a half hours at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Go back at two. You couldn't spend the whole afternoon - you had to do some at home, you could only spend two hours at in the afternoon if you went back that left you with another hour and a half to do at ho
me. You see, you'd got to carry out the three and a half hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that you only went back for two hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I - two hours and then the remainder had to be done at home. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your father have to sign a paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, every week. At t
he end of the week to show that the full time had been done but now - he knew of course that we did the two hours in the afternoon and he used to sign for the hour and a half in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time did you do that hour and a half, did you do it immediately you came home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. No. When we came home from school we usually and a bit of a room and then oh a little leisure then tea. And after tea we did it. I should say somewhere about probably start about - quarter past six, half past six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How old were you when you first started school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When I first started with Mrs Halls, the little one, I was four and a half. Yes. That was a nursery school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How old were you when you went to Stroud Green High School?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About six. May have been seven, I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you first started at Stroud Green High School you started at nine?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I - I think I was a bit earlier than that, I can't be quite certain the year I started dear. Oh nine o'clock in the morning, oh yes. Nin
e o'clock. And you had to be there too for assembly, Dr. Linklater was the clergyman of the Stroud - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Holy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 Trinity church used to come in for assembly, and they'd be there very punctually at nine. Actually we had to be there about ten minutes to. Then we'd assemble and - in the playground and go up to the assembly hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You came back at one o'clock for lunch and you went back about two o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you did your two hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Two hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And an hour and a half at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said you went to Stroud Green High School at seven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Somewhere about there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You followed that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 regime}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  from the time you were seven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, until I left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you were going to afternoon school from about the time you were seven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. Of course Cusacks was more like university. You - if you stayed away you stayed away, you must missed - missed the lessons, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 he lectures. Run on the same scale as the university is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were allowed more freedom there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well you could - they didn't - like you staying away of course but - you could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Stroud Green school was a day school and it was liked with the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, it was run by the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Ecclesiastical}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  Authorities.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was it for girls only?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Girls only
. The daughters of professional gentleman only, was a big board outside. Yes, a big board outside. It was very difficult to get in, they - you had to be - I mean, you wouldn't see anybody going there and saying their father was in a profession or not, the
y looked into it very closely. Oh yes, you have to fill in a form and have it signed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If a shopkeeper wanted to get his daughter in and went along .....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. They wouldn't - yes, because it was run - for that reason - for that - professions,
 for the professions only. Got plenty of very good schools that you could go to you know. But of course dad liked the idea that he was a professional man and - and - naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - that was only five minutes away. WE 
lived in Stapleton Hall Road and it was just up the road. Oh yes, it was quite near. Of course I used to have to go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389  by tube when I went to - to Cu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 sacks. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did it take you to get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did I stay at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did it take you to walk there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I suppose about five or six minutes. I think - really near, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What when I first started school? Oh - the maid used to - one of the maids used to come up when we first started school,
 but mostly - most of the time we went alone, it was so near, you see. Practically on top of the place, I mean - there was our house there and just up the road - just across the road - round the first corner was the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said you came home for your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Always. Except when mother was having a baby, - then we'd have it - then they'd bring it to school to us, yes - yes. They didn't do - didn't do cooked meals at the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you think of the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I was h
appy enough school days, oh yes, I liked school. Yes, I was happy there. Get in to - get into mischief sometimes but I liked my schooldays, I made some nice friends too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh some I liked and some I didn't. Th
e headmistress, the first headmistress I had, Miss McArthur I liked her very much, she was so pretty to look at, she was a nice looking and sort of - truly a way of - for liking a person. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 
And Miss Jameson who afterwards - she was an extremely efficient hea
dmistress and she - when she returned, it was long after I'd left, when she retired from the Stroud Green school she went on the Hornsey Council and was a councillor for a great number of years I believe until she passed away. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But she used to tickle, me, a
ll the girls, because she had a way of - of sort of speaking and going - and how we used to name her all sorts of things, poor old Jimmy. We had - oh don't you worry, we had to be - we daren't say it in her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 presence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , we had to be very respectful, she was quite a - disciplinarian.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as being very important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well they - they thought that English was probably the most important subject. English. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 They were very, very keen on English. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 English. All the English, e
verything, grammar, the - proper grammar, they don't teach grammar now, they - they don't know what they're writing half the time, children today. You - you - I could analyse any sentence you wanted ever to this day, absolutely. Don't do it any more. No, 
we used to - they concentrated on English, mathematics - French and history. We had geography of course and - later on - in the top form, biology.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they particular about manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very particular about manners. And if any of the - girls parent
s were to report you for misbehaving in the street you'd only get warned once and your parents would be asked to remove you. 'Cos they were paying you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What sort of behaviour would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I suppose - I don't quite know what to say - t
alking loudly and - rushing across road and perhaps fighting or anything like that, 'cos girls - girls do it just as well as boys if they get the chance, anything like that reported would be looked on with great - with disciplinary treatment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember being conscious of that when you were out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, conscious - especially, you see, we had to wear uniform of course and - especially when we'd got uniform on, that was why we were all so anxious when we got somewhere round about twelve or th
irteen to get our uniform off. And get - and get into ordinary clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that nobody could report you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they very particular about tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very. Very particular I need about tidiness. And - your top blouse on your gym ha
d to be spotless, or - or you'd be called out and told not to come in again until it was washed. And if you said, oh the maid forgot to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 wash}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  it, she - she'd turn round and say, what's the matter with you, couldn't you wash it? Very quickly. Or buttons off or anything like that. Oh no, you had to - you had to look the part.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Very particular about punctuality. I was never late, I've always been punctual, still am. It's a habit. If I make an appointment, it has to be something
 very - very unusual to make me late. Oh it comes - my father was very particular about punctuality too. If you weren't in a minute he'd never let the maids wait for you. They'd have to serve the meal. And if you came half way through dinner he'd say, you
 can have yours when we're finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they particular at the school about ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Very. Very. Oh yes, diction. Yes, practice vowel sounds for - what seemed inimitable time, I expect it's only natural, twenty minutes or so seems
 awfully long to us. And we had to - and of course deportment was very important. Used to have to walk round and round that wretched room with piles of books on your head. First two, then three, then four. Without dropping them. So as to keep - you got st
raight backs and - well, that you walked properly, also they taught us to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 curtsey}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  properly too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Why did they do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Well because we used to - as a rule - at prizegivings we had some of the nobility to distribute them and of course the girls - w
ere expected to curtsey.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh we'd get - detention. That was the favourite punishment, detention. Writing a thousand times I must not do this or I must not do that. And some of th
e girls got in the way and they - they'd stick five pencils in and write five lines at a time. And these girls got up - like little slots they were, like write five lines at a time. Oh dear. Detentions as a rule, that was the usual punishment, detention. 
A
nd - you'd have to do something very bad, they'd send you home. Not to come back until they - your father or your mother had been up. If there was anything serious. I never went - never had that to put up with but some of the girls did. If they were cheek
y or - really cheeky, some could be cheeky you know, could be rude, they could be rune in those days as much as they do today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ever use the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Oh they had no corporal punishment. No. Not for girls. Boys schools they did, but not for - not for girls, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So really the worst punishment would be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Detention. Detention - oh to be sent home yes, but detentions we didn't like because they cut into our evenings you see. The time we did get to ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were your parents interested in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 My father very. Well he - he did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 
Mother would have done it I suppose if he hadn't but he always did, he always wanted to see it before we - homework and that sort of thing, and they used to give you - you had a weekly r
eport, in which they gave you for each of the subjects, a black star - a red star which was excellent, black star which was very good and a - a - a cross which was - medium and them something, I forget what the other thing was, that was very, very bad.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ask what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. They used to ask me what we did at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your mother ask too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh quite a lot, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ever visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well when they had social occasions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would it only be on social occasions they'd visit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, and dad - dad went up to the school once or twice I think if he was particularly interested in anything. When there was a choice you see of whether I should take Latin or French. And then he'd go up you see and discuss it with the headmistress.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He'd go up during the day would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, he could always get off when he wanted to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they meet the teachers then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They'd meet the headmistress and your own particular teacher. Although you'd hav
e a separate teacher for French. And you used to have a - a separate teacher for deportment - and drill. Yes. You had a - a form - a proper form mistress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But a different teacher would come in for French?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. You'd have a different teacher - th
ey'd have a different teacher come in for French and of course for deportment. I think those were the only two. And drill. Yes, we had drill. Swedish drill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In this sort of school all the children came from the same sorts of homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Same sort of background, a similar sort of background, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the teachers }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 single}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I suppose you get it in all schools, I suppose there were some who were teacher's favourites. And who behav
ed themselves particularly well and they were particular - of course they particularly liked the brilliant ones, those who did well at school because of the - it rebounded on them of course you see, on the school. But I can't say they - they - there was a
ny unfair treatment, no. It - it wouldn't matter who you were or where you came from, if you did well you'd get praise of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any cliques or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, we never on that sort - didn't get that sort of thing, no, we didn't
 get it there. Girls - I mean, there'd be - there'd be certain girls in the same form who perhaps would pair off together, different pairs going off together but no sort of gangs or anything like that, like they're - like they're getting today, I mean, it
 was unheard of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember if there were any children who were always left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Never. They never were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 left}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  out of things unless they were deprived of it through some act of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 disobedience}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 or other, then they might be deprived of something they liked doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were the girls conscious of things like they should }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 bring}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  everybody into games and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I - oh yes, oh yes, quite a friendly atmosphere, I can't remember anybody who was particularly unfriendly. Not anybody, no, the
y were - yes, I say certain girls got together 'cos like friends like, you've got interests in common, some like so - some like playing tennis, some like playing hockey, you see, it's sport would draw them together more than anything else.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You went on to Cusacks College afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, after leaving -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How old were you when you went to Cusacks College?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Fifteen I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time did you go there in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Ten. Ten o'clock and left about four. I would be home - you see
, we came - the tube from Finsbury Park to the city was open during those days when I went there, I had - I was - I had a ride on it backwards and forwards for about two hours the first day it was opened. So I used to go up to Moorgate. Moorgate on that -
 on those City tubes. And then. - of course I had a season ticket you see, used to go and then of course white Street is almost opposite }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Moorgate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  Station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What kind of school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 IT WAS - it was more like a Polytechnic. That's the nearest I c
an get to it. So there were always - well I mean there were men there - some - some of the men - of course it was mixed - some of the men was almost thirty - thirty-five years of age. Just like a university it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was it run by the government then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, no, no. It was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was it private?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, it was - run by - yes, Doctor Cusack ran it. With Mr Quinn as his subsidiary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In a way it was like Pitman's college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It's more like that but you can take - you can take the scholastic }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 side}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  at Pitmans I believe you can. Yes, I think - yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were the people in Cusacks preparing for examinations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 All of them, all - all preparing for examinations. Mine was - well they - the - the Oxford - Oxford and Cambridge, which is 
the - the - exams, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Matriculation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  took the place of that later but there was no metric - until after I left school.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you prepared for this special entrance examination?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. And the College of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Preceptors}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . And - there was the Oxford, Cambridge, and the College of and Society of Arts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was it only day pupils, all day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And it was men and women mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You went there on the underground from Finsbury Park?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did the journey take do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - about - I used - let me see, I had to get there at ten, I'm - I suppose - I used to walk down to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Finsbury}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  Park Station, although the green tram was running I used to walk down to Finsbury Park Station, I had my season
 from there. And I suppose it used to - I used to leave home - about quarter past eight to half past eight - about half an hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Quarter past nine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I mean quarter past nine or half nine. Yes, about half an hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 My husband does that same tube journey now every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What - to Moorgate? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did anybody go with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh Lord no. Not then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not even a friend or a sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, no, I was - no, we - we'd been separated up then. Hilda was of course younger, she was three an
d a half years younger, she went to - she was going to Owens so I went up there and Dorothy was at Holloway College.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did you have your midday meal then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 My midday meal when I was at - well, sometimes I used to have it - dad used to give m
e the money, sometimes I'd have it in the City, sometimes I'd come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you say in the City you mean in a restaurant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 On hour own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Oh yes. And sometimes I'd come home. It just depend you see, I'd got plenty of tim
e to come home because you - you go there at ten, you leave about twelve, you don't get back 'til about two. You know, it was the same sort of thing as there is at college. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you had your meal in a restaurant what would you have to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
All sorts of things, whatever I fancied. Sometimes - oh I used to have - mother used to say to me, now you've got to have a proper meal you know. You got a - like lamb and mint sauce and baked potatoes and all that sort of thing you eat today really, or
 roast beef and Yorkshire pudding. And a sweet afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you think of Cusacks College?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I loved it there. I had a lovely time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It must have been very grown up for you after the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I went - I - I suppose I was gr
owing up very fast really looking a back on it now, although I was married - I had put my hair up to be married and put it down on my honeymoon. I didn't like it up. To make me look a little older. But - oh it was nice. There was - you got to know a lot o
f
 males too there. I had some lovely times. Remember going to the - all the big actresses were selling programmes, a big charity affair they had the Coliseum when it was first opened, with a revolving stage and - I remember going with one of the fellows fr
om the Cusacks College there in the afternoon and when I - it was so funny - because weren't really supposed to stay away you know. And old Quinn, the headmaster, he was there and - sometimes he'd come down those main staircases and all around our }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 cloakroom}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 downstairs were mirrors so that anybody upstairs could see you if they happened to be looking at that side. And I remember the afternoon I went to that matinee, I had to smuggle out - a wine coloured velvet frock, rather low necked and - 'cos of course m
other would have wondered what on earth I was doing with it, and dress up there and I'd just got myself }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 nicely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 dressed when the bell went for the afternoon and then somebody said - I overheard a voice say, very nice Miss Fulford. Very nice indeed, but you d
on't propose to - you don't propose to come to class like that do you? And I said, no, Mr Quinn I don't, I'm }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 going}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 to the matinee. But. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Jesus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . don't you think it would have been courteous if }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 had advised me of the fact that you were going to a matinee.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you feel about the teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well they were - there was Miss Underwood. I took it, took it for a hobby although I never used it, who took the typewriting, I rather liked her, she was a great pal. I think of her now and again. Mr Q
uinn would send - not the old doctor, but Mr Quinn, he was really - the doctor was getting old at the time and he was to take - he was headmaster there and - he'd - he'd now and again if you stayed away write home and ask your parents if they knew that yo
u
 weren't attending And he did it about three times in my case. Each time - awfully naughty girl I was on looking back - Miss Underwood, who had to type it, she was his secretary, would tell me and I'd wait for the postman. But I was very unlucky on one oc
casion, the last occasion of all, well I never did again afterwards. When - the post was late and it came after I'd gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And your father got the letter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. He never gave me away. Never came up the school and told me about me - nobody. It so up
set me. He called me in and - he was really grieved, and he said to me - grieved that I could be so deceitful and - it did more good than if he'd been angry really because almost tears in his eyes. He said, I didn't think - didn't think it was possible fo
r
 you to be so deceitful, he said, to intercept a letter addressed to somebody else, did you realize how dreadful - what a dreadful thing that is to do. And he - he was sweet though. I said, I'm going up to see Mr Quinn. He said, oh no, I'm not going up to
 see him. He said, he can - he can think that I've received the letter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So he didn't give you away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. He didn't let me down at all, but I never did again of course, I was too ashamed of myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the teachers there emphasise certain things as being important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, they didn't - wasn't anything - no - no moral teaching there. You'd already leached the age when you should have known, they expected you to, I mean, if you - if you stayed away like they do in the universities 
- I mean, you couldn't deliberately misbehave yourself in the school, get yourself talked about. You got yourself talked about, they'd probably - ask you to be removed. Oh schools were very much - especially paying schools. They were very particular about
 the - behaviour of their pupils because they felt it let the school down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they very particular there still about manners?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, that didn't come into it very much. No, you already - already had got to the stage where you'd either got good ma
nners or you hadn't. You see, it - it was more commercialised than the ordinary school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they particular about punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - no, not particularly - bells went - the bell went at the time was at ten o'clock and the bell went again in th
e afternoon at two. But - if you weren't there well then that was just too bad, you missed your lectures. 'Cos they were more in the form of lectures than anything else. Except the shorthand and typewriting which of course had to be practiced.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they concerned there with your way of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not mixed - you got them a bit mixed there. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - see it depend - you couldn't do very much to the teachers disapproved 
of, I mean, if you - if you started a conversation so as you couldn't - you interrupted the teachers talking you'd be told. You must either listen and; behave yourself or go home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you didn't attend classes quite a lot they'd write a letter to your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. If it went on too often. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they punish the pupils in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your parents show an interest in what you were doing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they show any interest? Always showed interest and dad used to come u
p from time to time and have a chat with Mr Quinn, you see, the head - headmaster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About what you were doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Now and again he would, when it suited him, to come across from Holborn, it wasn't very far you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the other students come from the same sort of home as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well they were mixed as I say, they were mixed and there were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 foreigners}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  there because there was - I remember a - very nice fellow he was too, a Chinese. His name was Sekia. Another one that I went out on t
he Serpentine with. I think dad got a little bit worried - while I was there, because he would - 'cos he would turn up now and again unexpectedly. At - when I was due to leave in the afternoon then he'd say, oh I thought I'd come down and we - shall we go
 and have a cup of tea. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 And then he'd proceed so that I'd have to proceed home with him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Now and again, I think he was a little because he had four daughters you know, a bit of an anxiety one way and another. Yes, I think, sometimes he was, I often wonder n
ow why he used to turn up at that odd moments, but I think that was it, he wanted to be quite sure I wasn't making bad companions. Because of course he knew it was a school of that sort with a lot of older people there you see, older students, older men p
articularly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And a big change from your other school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, a big change from the other type of school, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the teachers single out any of the students from others for special attention or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I don't think so, I don't think they had the time to do it. At - one or two of the fellows there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 private coaching from the teachers - from teachers attending the school, they paid for that, yes. Of course you paid for it all, dad paid for me, it wasn't a government thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 cliques}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  or groups in that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh we were very cliquey really because - as I say it was - cosmopolitan. It was - it was international in a sense and you see we - it - types get together then. We had a debating society there, which wa
s very interesting too because you did get mixed - you know, people from other countries talking, I rather enjoyed that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any students who were very much left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, because it was a different type of school, you made your 
own - really you made your own friends and your own amusements there. It wasn't like the other school that - that was - a group.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 For instance would the Chinese man be left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, if he wanted to join - I mean, it's all a matter of if
 they got anything up you'd always have to pay for it in the form of tickets or something and anybody in the school could buy it of course - buy them of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You went on to another college afterwards?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I went down to the Poly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did you stay at Cusacks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At - at Cusacks I must have stayed about - eighteen months. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Had you taken any exam by then or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I'd taken - I'd passed the - I'd passed the - preliminary. The preliminary - Society of Arts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About what year was all this in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I was married in 1908. So I'd trace it back from there. I went - left the Polytechnic in 1908. In the Easter of 1908.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So from Cusacks College you went to the Polytechnic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 There was a particular reason for you going there wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, because my father's younger sister who was only eighteen months older than I was going there, for secretarial training. She was going in to business, I wasn't but she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you carry on in the Polytechnic doing the same things as you had in Cusacks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Practically the same thing. No difference at all. Taking all the scholastic subjects, English and - mathematics. Not French.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How old were you when you went to the Polytechnic then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8657389  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
- eighteen. Let me see, when I went to the Poly - I left Cusacks when I was about - oh I was - I was about seventeen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time of the morning did you go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Ten o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time did you come home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And - I th
ink it was a bit - I think I've made a mistake, I think I was a bit earlier at the Poly. I think it was nine thirty-nine thirty in the morning, yes it was, nine thirty 'til twelve thirty. And hour and a half. And then from two 'til four in the afternoon. 
They had a - they had a restaurant there, I used to dine there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The Poly was a state thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - no, it started - just like the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Like the Polytechnic today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, Polytechnic is today - it wasn't - I don't know, has the state got an
 interest in it today, they have, for scholarship pupils. Oh no, it's paying. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who ran it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
It was run by the Polytechnic Authorities, I forget who they were, they were called the Polytechnic Authorities, yes, it's run by a body. 'Cos they ha
d several Polytechnics you see, they opened them opened - opened - I believe the Northern Polytechnic was the first one. Then they opened Regent Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So the one you went to is the one that's now on the corner of Kentish Town Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. It was 
in Holloway Road. Yes. In Holloway Road just before - just before you come to the - I don't know if there's now still even - it's just before you come to the arches of Holloway station. They've probably turned, I wouldn't - I wouldn't be supposed if they'
ve moved it. But it was there up until a very few years ago because they used to have the concerts there and we generally had a - sang and - I used to go down to them a lot for the concerts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That was much nearer to you than the one at Kentish Town?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. That - yes, that was near.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And it was boys and girls mixed again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And only day pupils?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, they had a lot of evening classes as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But there was no residential students?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, no, no. Evening classes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you get there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh we used to - that was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 the way.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  They - they used to run a bus from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Stapleton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
, right the way down there, right past the college. Ordinary bus, horse bus. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long would that take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - well on a horse bus about ten minutes, twelve minutes perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you go on your own when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You ate your midday meal in their restaurant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, they had it there sometimes, sometimes I'd go home with Edie and we'd have it a
t grannies and - my grandma 'cos she came from - Upper Clapton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was she still living in Upper Clapton at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. She was older than me don't forget, she's eighteen months older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Wouldn't that be quite a long way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not so far
, no, because all the trams and buses running from there, I believe she came by tube. I think she came by tube. No she didn't, she came from Dalston - station. She came from Dalston station to Highbury. And then from Highbury up on the tram outside the Po
ly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What would you have to eat there, what sort of meals did they serve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh similar to what you had at the other one. Roast lamb, boiled ham, boiled ham or boiled bacon, things like that you know. Fish sometimes. You'd have a menu so you could choose from it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you think of the Poly, did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I think I liked Cusacks, Cusacks better. It was - perhaps it was just as though it was more select I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Cusacks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. More select. But I enjoyed being with Edie you se
e, we were - chums together. And then of course I left there when I - I say I got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you feel about the teachers at the Poly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, some of them were very nice and very efficient too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They were good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, they were go
od I think, oh yes, I think the education there was quite good, they got a lot of the - a lot of their pupils - a large percentage of them got through their exams. That was the chief thing, that's what they were there for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they particular there about things like manners and tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. No. I don't think so. 'Cos I mean - I didn't come - no, you got mixed. Where you get these - these cosmopolitan schools you must expect to get them a little mixed you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So they wouldn't reprimand you if you were noisy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. No. Oh no, no. No, I didn't get reprimanded at - at school, not after I left - not after I left the Stroud Green High.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you did something the teachers disapproved at the Poly what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well you'd simply be told to - to leave the classroom unless you - unless you listen, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ever punish you in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 I don't remember anyone - I don't think - I think when you got to the stage of going there, you either came and did your - you
 did your work or you stayed away and neglected it, that was all that happened. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. They held a lot of very nice - classical musical concerts in the evening, I used to love to go to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were your parents interested in what you were doing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh they were interested all the time, as far as - dad was interested in our education all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they ask you what you were doing at the Poly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, they'd ask you what you were doing, yes. In fact, my dad as car as that was taking an i
nterest in anything, I used to play the piano and my sister used to sing. He paid for me to have lessons right up until I had to leave London because I was so ill when I fell with my first child. Up to I was married. Went on paying just the same, yes, and
 
for me to go on having lessons. I used to have to go out to Winch more Hill. Yes, because my - my mistress - my pianoforte mistress, she was a gold medallist and - she didn't marry until she was about forty and then she got married and went out to live ou
t
 at Palmers Green - Palmers Green but it was more towards Winch more Hill way. But - and I used to go out there - it was all country then. And there was no - no - none of the shopping centre or anything there. I used to go out there every Tuesday for my l
esson - after I was married. Until - until - until as I say, I left London and went down to Brighton.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At the Poly did your parents ever visit the college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh dad - dad and mum used to come - they'd come to the concerts too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ever meet the teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, of course dad would in the beginning. He would have done when he entered me, I don't think he did afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that the other students there came from homes like your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Lots of them. Some came from better ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And some from poorer ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Oh yes some came from - 'cos o lot of them - a lot of them used to come up in their - the same as they did to the North London Collegiate, came up in their victories. Outside the Poly they'd stop and drop the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Did the teachers single out any students there for different treatment from the other?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any cliques there at the Poly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I can't remember any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any students there that were sort of left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you left the Poly did you say it was to get married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you meet your husband there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, my husband had been - he was older than I - he'd been at business for some - he'd been at busine
ss for - no, I knew him before he went to business, I knew him when he was at Brighton College. He was home - Brighton College for - I met him up at Alexandra Palace as a mater of fact, was introduced to him by another gentleman friend of mine. He was hom
e
 from school. That's there I first - and I hated the sight of him. Yes. It's an extraordinary thing, I was ever so young, I was about fourteen then. And I couldn't bear him. It's an extraordinary thing. Well then about two years went by and - what happene
d - oh I met him again. Oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11754187\charrsid8657389 no,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 I was up at the Palace. They'd got a - a fair up there, up at Alexandra Palace. And - I went on the horses there, suddenly somebody jumped on behind the horse I was on and said, hello Gracie. I - I didn't know him. So I said t
o him, who are you? Ah, he said, I know you. So I said - I said, I don't you know you anyway. He said, well you ask Hol Stewart, that was the friend, they were very great friends apparently. And after that - again I wasn't frightfully keen on him. About a
nother year went by and - we had a big carnival here just after the - just before the Queen Victoria - no, it must have been after that, was when - when King Edward - no, it wasn't I was married when King Edward was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 crowned}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . But any rather there was some bi
g do on over here and the carnivals were on and I - I met him - I didn't meet him again them, I was going out with another boy. And one Sunday afternoon I was sitting up - sitting in the park - by myself, about six o'clock in the evening and I heard a voi
ce say, why so pensive? I looked up, it was husband. So he said, you know what I've come to see you about? I said, no. He said, poor so and so. Freddy Parkinson, that was his name. He said - why do you treat him so badly. So I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 thought}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  he'd started, why do y
ou treat him so badly, the poor fellow's in tears. I said, how soppy. Any rate, we started talking then for a little while and he - he ended - he was supposed to have come up and pleaded for Freddy Parkinson and ended by asking me if I'd go out with him t
o a musical on the Saturday. Well I was never - at that time I was not allowed about after about eight - half past eight. So I said to him, good gracious no. He said, not the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 first}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  house? 'Cos there used to be two houses, from seven 'til nine and then from 
nine 'til eleven. So I said, good gracious no. My father'd have a fit if I asked. Do you know what he did? He wrote to my father. I think I was - I thought I was in for - in for a good old wigging. Dad came down to breakfast one morning and he said, Grace
,
 I want to speak to you in the study. I wondered what on earth I'd done. In this study I went, he said, I've had a letter from a young gentleman called Nargrave. So I thought I was in for a - what cheek, what is he writing to you about? He said, now don't
 
talk like it, when a gentle an approaches me in a gentlemanly manner I treat him as a gentleman. And apparently he'd written to ask him if he could take me out to the music hall on the - to the first house in the evening. And I said, can I go? So surprise
d. So he said, yes, he said, I've told your mother to answer it and say that providing he fetches you and brings you home I can't see -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So how old were you when you finished school completely, when you left the Poly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Seventeen. Yes. Seventeen and a half - over seventeen. Nearly - nearly eighteen. Eighteen in the August as I left in the Easter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Of course, I wish had to. Yes, I would have stayed longer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It was only to get married that you left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Ridiculous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  idea thinking you'd be your own mistress, do as you like. What a fancy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you have any more part time education after you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You never went to evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh 
- oh I - not until I was - turned sixty, then I did. Yes. I went back to evening classes. I went down to the - public speaking classes, dramatic classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you have any regrets about your education as a whole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, I can't grumble about my e
ducation, I was lucky, I had - we all had a good education. And we gave our children a good education too, we - had to make a lot of - a lot more sacrifices than dad had to do it but we all did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because you thought it was important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I think i
t's very important. And I think it's awfully important from a - from a mixing point of view too. Because - if you - it's all very well to talk about the state schools but they've really deteriorated to such a degree now that I think for anybody who's had 
a
ny sort of cultural education at all it's not fair to their children. Because the home influence doesn't - you see, a child spends much more time at school that it does at home. It goes to bed early - fairly early when it's young at home. You think of the
 number of hours it spends at school. And then - and children - they're imitative. If they get - if they get with bad company or badly spoken company, I know it sounds snobby but - they pick up all those - that sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 phraseology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  that's not in the dictionary at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
When my little girl goes to school I can imagine her thinking perhaps the books and things we have in our home are perhaps studied and the other children will say to her oh that's silly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Well they did of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8657389  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 
course, you've got that to face too. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
And - I will say though that if you - if you send a child to a school that - that's why I think those - those schools in which they have children of professional classes were quite good because they were more or less of the same taste so that - not
 entirely of course because you're individuals, but - you do like similar sort of things. You get to like good literature - most of you, and you can discuss the sort of literature together. Whereas is you go to a - a council school, specially today, you d
on't speak - you very soon get out of the way, if you're young particularly, of speaking good English for the simple reason that they - nobody else does. And you get the - a child is naturally imitative.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And it's very hard for the parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It's v
ery hard for the parents, they seem to be always nagging. That's what Pat used to say, she always felt as if she was nagging them. But - it's no good because they go through the phase of copying the school children. You may as well pack it up. Trust that 
they'll revert to type sooner or later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You've never worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Except that one time during the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. About six months in the first world war. On the aeronautical inspection department.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In a factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, no, no, no. It was - I used to go out - in a staff }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 car}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 with an officer - examining - most of the time that I was with - the short time I was on the Ministry I used to go about in the - in the side car or a motorcycle at St Albans and places like that w
here they were the factories, I had to write the release notes releasing the - things that they used to - particularly heated clothing for the cold countries for the soldiers, all heated by bulbs you know, they're all heated. Well I used to have to test t
hese bulbs to see if they were - and then get - write the release note to say that they were all right. And of course it all had to be O.K'd by somebody above me. The engineer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You did that for six months during the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. And then I went down
 with 'flu and my husband, without consulting me at all, sent in my designation. Cheek. I couldn't very well say anything 'cos it was his job. He was on the Ministry too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I have a section here about home life after leaving school but you left to get married?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 School to get married, yes, yes. My home life started - my home life started as a married woman after I left school within a few days.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You weren't quite eighteen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were seventeen and a half?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long had you known your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh since I was fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But he'd only started courting you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
About eight months. About eight months. Dad had said to him, he gave his consent to our engagement, he said, yes, of course, you won't get married 
'til you're twenty-one you know, he said, because you know - I hear him saying it now - he said, of course you know my girls haven't been brought up to rough it and you would have to have a sound position before I could want her to get married. And he sai
d - there you are. I was - obstinate and - wouldn't take his advice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said you first met when you were fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. On the - on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 roundabouts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . Sometimes a romantic meeting on the roundabout.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 My husband - 
oh he was a North London boy. He'd - he - I know I first knew him he'd - just - he was leaving his last term at Margate College. It was Margate he was at, yes, or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Brighton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , yes, Margate College.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But he had been born and brought up in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. In - he was a Londoner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were counting for eight months, did you start saving any money or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you have any to save, or just your pocket money?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Half a crown a week, buy your gloves out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He was still at college too was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
But - he was - he was - he was at business, he'd gone into his father's business. He'd gone - he's five years older than me you see. He'd gone into his father's business, his father was in the printing line. He's gone into h
is father's business which I very much disapproved of so he finally left it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Why did you disapprove of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He left it while I was in Grays. Oh I think the old man took advantage of him, his salary wasn't as big as it ought to be because he was g
ood at his job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were courting for eight months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well I was actually engaged - no, I was engaged for eight months. I met him in - we met again in the August. At Christmas I became engaged. Dad gave his consent to the engagement, he told me af
terwards I was married, he did it because he though it was good or me to remain - to have one boy instead of a dozen. And that's really why - he thought it would steady me. He thought it would steady me. No, never thought I'd never I'd think of getting ma
rried so soon. Well - and as I said he said, of course you'll await 'til twenty-one. Give you plenty of time to get to know each other and be quite sure of yourself, that's what he thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you were only engaged for eight months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So I was - at Christmas, at Christmas I was engaged. From }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 A}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ugust 'til }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 Christmas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 he was courting me. Christmas he asked if he could be engaged and he said, yes. January, February, March, April, May, June - July - seven months afterwards I was married. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he manage to save any money at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. We - we thought we could live - two could live as cheap as one, what a mistake. And we could live on his salary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your parents help you to set up home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not really. Not willingly. First of all we got i
t on the hire system, my father heard it, from the times Furnishing and - my father heard of it and he was so horrified he rang them up and he said we were broth so under age. Which Ronal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10497238\charrsid8657389 d}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  wasn't, he was over age but dad said he was under age. And they - s
hould they - would they please fetch it all away. And then he - he bought, what he thought was necessary, bedroom suit and dining room suite and that for us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You'd found a place to live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Half - yes, a flat. Bottom flat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Having sent the furniture back he bought some more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
He bought enough to furnish it for us, yes. Well then when I fell ill which was very shortly afterwards when I fell with Ronnie, and had to go away, he stored it all for me up in the top attic at - Stapleton Hall Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where was your husband when you went away to the country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He - he came with me. He - he gave up his job and came down there and got another in the printing line down at Brighton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could you describe the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. I can
 describe the wedding all right, that's another thing that stands out. To begin with, my father - my - husband's grandfather, his mother's father was a big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 coach master}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , he used to provide carriages for the Royal Family for those outside it, and he had a very fine coach for a couple of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 footmen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 like that. Cockades, 'cos it was a justice of the Peace. And he was giving up business, selling it up and he said to me about - oh about six weeks before I was married, he said, do you know what I'm going to do for yo
u girl? He was a real country one. He said - you're going to be married in my state coach. He said, none of my own children have been married ink it, he said, but you're going to be, he said, because it's going to - he said, the whole thing's going to be 
s
old afterwards. And I was, two grey bays, two beautiful grey bay horses. And - the - coachmen and footman, with cockades up the side. And when we got to the church, it was only two minutes away from our house by car to Holy Trinity church, and when we got
 to the church and came out after the ceremony was over about eight different boys from the neighbourhood }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 seized}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  the horses}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 heads, wouldn't let go - and pulled them through the streets. Back home to our house. Yes. Yes. It caused quite a sensation I can }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ell you. Dad was a bit annoyed because he hated publicity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your father go to the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. He give me away in the end, he said he wouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He was very much against it wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. But he - in the end he said, he never we
nt to another one afterwards, and he said to me, well I suppose if I don't give you away he'll ste}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
l you. So he - he gave me away of course.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your father feel very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 bitter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  against your husband then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I think that he never liked him really. Whe
n we - I don't think he ever really liked him after - after I was married I think he never really - ever really liked him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It's funny because he got off to such a good start with writing the letter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes, yes, he did. But he blotted his copy
book several times. Dad didn't - he - dad couldn't bear people who told lies you know, he thought that was the worst thing you could do, you could lock up a thief, you could do nothing for a liar. And Ron was rather inclined to tell untruths and he - and 
had that - he trusted everybody 'til he found them out. He only had to find them out once and his trust had gone you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But in the end he gave you away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He gave - he gave me away, very very nice too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was your mother very upset about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not so much, she rather - they rather got on. She rather liked him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So she was fairly happy about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
She - she rather liked - no, she was a little bit unhappy about me going because I was young you see. She was a bit unhappy about that and we'd always been very close to each other, more so than the others perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did a lot of guests come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We had about forty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did all of them go to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 All of them went to the church, yes, they all went to church. Two - two of the
m came uninvited after having refused the invitation which made it very awkward, oh dad was annoyed about that. That was on his side. They - well they said that they couldn't come but one of them was going away or something, my - my mother-in-law's two si
sters. But - and they sent presents. But at the last minute they turned up. And you know, when you've arranged for a thing to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 catered}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  for, which this had done, what they had to do was to turn the two bridesmaids, my little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 bridesmaids}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  out to make room for them and send them up-stairs into the study to have a meal separately.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You all went back home for a reception?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. We had a reception at home catered for by Beals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Catered by Beals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They're the people down in the Holloway Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, they've gone now you know, yes, but they used to be first class people, yes, they catered for it. They sent their own - their own factotum in - read - red uniform with brass buttons and the maids in the white - red frock with a white - a
 white frilled apron.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And your own maids helped?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, they helped too but these two brought all the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 waited on}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  table you see 'cos they brought all the stuff and the stuff that wasn't cut they took back again. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the guests all send presents beforehand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. I had some rather nice - nearly all got lost in the fire. And that marvellous Queen Anne - Queen Anne teapot on it's three lovely dainty legs, that went. Of course it was stolen, there's no doubt about it, in the fire. 
Because light stuff like that was picked up by the firemen and people like that because it doesn't burn. Not to the extent - and those sort of things were all missing when my - when I got my furniture again. And of course they won't replace those, they're
 luxuries. Not the piano or anything. That's the thing I most regretted losing, my piano. See I've had such a long - since a little girl when I first began, seven. To learn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you have a honeymoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, went down to Ventnor. Ventnor. Isle of Wight. Isle of Wight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You had the flat all lined up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. To come back to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Whereabouts was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In Harringay, Sidney Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did you live there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh not long. Because - about - oh only about nine months, because I fell with Ronnie, I was so ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You became very ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. The doctor said there was only one thing to do. To go out of London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was before he was born even?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Yes. He was born at Brighton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you went to Brighton and you said your husband went down and he found a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, he got a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you let the flat in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Harringay}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  go?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. We let that go. Dad - dad had the furniture stored in the top - in the top room. One of the top rooms at Stapleton Hall Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you take a furnished flat in Brighton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When we - no, I went into digs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Both of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And the baby was born there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And baby was born there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did you stay in Brighton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - about - let me see - Ro
nnie was born in - 1909 - oh, I don't - not very long, really, about - about eighteen months to two years, then we went to Watford. Transferred to Watford. And - from Watford where did we go to now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were married in 1908?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you only spent a few months in Harringay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, that's all. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then about eighteen months or two years at Brighton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then you went to Watford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then I went to Watford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did you stay in Watford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then where did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
After that - oh dear, don't ask me the ties I've moved, oh dear to remember them all. From Watford I came back - and lived in Highbury. Grosvenor Road. Grosvenor Road for about three years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did you live then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then from there - oh I've had so many moves it'd take you a month of Sundays to remember them all. To the end of 1918 after the war?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Up to 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh the time to the war was over, that was over in 1916 wasn't it? 1914 to 1916 - 1916 - 1918 that's right, four years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So up to the end of the war you'd moved from Watford and then to Highbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Highbury}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , then from Highbury we went to Lee Green. And then from Lee Green we came back. No, from Lee Green we went up to Manchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you went to Watford it was about 1910?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you stayed there about two years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then you went to Highbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did you stay in Highbury?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We stayed in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Highbury}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  for about three years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that'd be 1915?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Then in 1915 we went up to Manchester. Because my husband was transferred, see he was on the Ministry, to - he was inspecting A B roads, he was - using the aircrafts, the war aircraft, he was on the secret - on the secret designs for aircraft.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You mentioned Lee Green?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Lee Green was during the war years. We went from Lee Green when they first - no - what year was that now - Lee Green -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was after Manchester?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Lee Green - no, we want - we went from Lee Green to Manchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you went from Highbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Highbury to Lee Green, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember how long you stayed in Lee Green?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not long. Because he was attached to the depot where - at Woolwich, we were only there for about nine months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then you went up to Manchester?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Then we went up to Manchester and - because - yes, we went up to Manchester and entered Ronnie into - young Ronnie, that's my son - into Hulme Grammar school. We tried Manchester but it - they were full and we got him into Hulme - Hulme Grammar School.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you in Manchester until the end of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No - no. No. In the end I was back here in the end of the war - up - Ronnie was still at Hulme -
 school, Grammar School, but he had started to develop a bad chest while he was up there and so we got the - Air Ministry to transfer us back to London. On - on account of his health, although we left him there until we were settled in and we came to Ridg
e Road. We took a - took a - one of the officer's flats who had been transferred somewhere else - in Ridge Road. And that was in 19 -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Quite near your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. That's right. Is that - are those dates right. Let me think, 1916, the war ended, 
no, 1918 the war ended. And - You see our Pat was born now I was in London. I was in London. No, I know where I was. We'd taken a house at Wallington. In Surry. And of course I was at Wallington then when the war ended. And it was after the war ended he -
 that my husband was in the Army up until then of course. After it was - in - after the war ended - was it Aver - no, because he went - yes, it was, after the war ended he went to Wallington to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 Churchend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  Finchley where we stayed five years. Or four and a half say, about four and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So from Manchester really when you came back to London you went to Wallington?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. And then from Wallington we went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were in Wallington when the war ended?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How old was your husband when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He'd be twenty-two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was his job at the time you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He was a commercial artist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he have any other jobs before he did that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, he'd been in - he'd been in - in the commercial art business - 
ever since he really started. He was very - he started a very short time in his - in his father's printing - printing business. And then he went in for lithographic art. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he have any other jobs after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No - yes, after he - after he gave up the art work - after he came out of the Army he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the first world war he was in the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. In the first world war. When he came out of the Army he went on the aeronautical inspections lecturer to the Air Ministry.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In peacetime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes, peacetime. He was there until - 'til he retired. Yes. He was a Civil Servant you see, he was a civil servant, he was a - a number one inspector of air - of the aeronautical inspection directorate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was that because he got training for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. No, not actually wasn't. He really got it through influence, through a brother - a brother officer after - after he came out of the war, he didn't want to go back into commercial work again and - he had a lot of friends in
 the Army and he really got it through that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever do any part time jobs besides that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. Oh yes, when I say did he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 ever}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  do any part time - of course he did, what am I talking about. He did part time job even after he - even after he g
ot onto the Air Ministry because Ronald was growing up and we wanted to - he was very delicate and we wanted to send him to boarding school which the fees were very expensive. So he used to do design for book}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 covers and that sort of thing in the lithograph
ic - at home - in the - in the lithographic world you see, and then - oh he'd had training for - he was quite expert at that, at his job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that was freelance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, freelance, oh yes. Only did it for a few years just while the - Ronnie's school
 training was going on and then he gave it up. Then the - then the chappie he used to work for became part of - the Arts Publicity and then he no longer did it of course, he didn't need to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever do anything else of that kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When he'd been working in his father's business did he do any other part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Same sort of thing, lithographed at home and ran his own little business in a basement - at the bottom of Crouch Hill. Rented a place at the bottom of - 
the basement of one - Crouch end. After my - it was before Maunders opened there, it was actually below where they - they are now. And he used to - he used to go from his - his own job, that was when he was in the - lithographic world - and run his own li
ttle business at night with a - with a - a friend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And they had premises and everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Oh people were enterprising in those days, you'd be surprised, much more that they are today. There wasn't - of course there wasn't any state help or an
ything like that, if they wanted money they'd jolly well got to earn it, there was nothing for - nothing for nothing. If people want it today they want something for nothing all the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever work after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Only for a very short period when he was on the Air Ministry, I went on the inspection department for about - four or five months only.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was in peacetime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was in - this was actually in - yes, in peacetime. In peacetime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You only did that for six months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. I didn't work - didn't work during the war at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was that the only work you ever did after you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, he sent in my resignation without my consent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did your husband feel about you doing that work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Although he was influential really, well I say he was influential he was because he had for meeting the - officers at the Masonic does because he belonged to the - the Masonic lot attached to the Air Ministry, I shouldn't have got it. But I got it, I said
 I'd try it for a time and that I'd pay for a housekeeper to look after the youngsters you see but - it didn't work out well and then I - I fell ill with influence and was taking time off and when I was better and got up I found he'd sent in my resignatio
n, it was accepted, I got a letter to say it was accepted. I was furious. Yes. Of course I couldn't do anything about it because he was part of the Ministry, it would have been washing your affairs in public, that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How do you think your husband felt about his work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh I think he liked that, I think - mind I think that he was - probably if it came to liking I think he actually liked his - the artistic - probably in the art - but of course it was - not nearly so remunerative really. And - of course 
the Air Ministry job was like all Civil Services, more or less - easy. Yes. He got on well in it - he got on well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He didn't find it boring or anything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I don't think he found it boring and he was - in a lot of ways he was very enterprising
 because I remember before he got his B certificate which is a ground certificate, a ground engineer's certificate, before he got that he didn't know anything about - special woods, and he went before the examining board and they'd got a pile of different
 
woods there like that and he made some excuse, any rate, they - he - wanted to tell them what - if they were - whether it was spruce or whether it was teak or whether it was something else - various other things. So it was getting near lunch time so he su
ggested that they break up and went to lunch and that he'd - and - and - have the - the remainder of the test after. In the meantime he went down somebody he knew and found out all about it. Then came back he knew all the woods by heart by that time.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He was quick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, he was quick, he was an opportunist. Quick when it came to it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How many children did you have?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What were their dates of birth, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh Ronnie was born in 19 - I was married in 1908, Ronnie was born in 1909. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you know which month?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, April 7th 1909. And - Joyce was born in two - two years and four months afterwards. 1911. And Pat was born in 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What month was she born in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She was born in November the 25th. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 All except Pat. She was born in hospital.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Pat is?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
The youngest. Yes. The others were born at home. Ronnie was born down at Brighton. He was - he was to have been in born in a nursing home, as I told you before, it was arranged for a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 
caesarian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 but he decided to come at - at the eighth month. In the middle of the night and he - nearly cost - nearly cost me my life, but he was born at Brighton. They were born at home and - Joyce was born at Crouch Hill her
e. Up at Crouch Hill and of course Pat was born in hospital.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you had that first baby at home did you know what to expect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well to some extent of course 'cos - 'cos I mean when I - only just before I was married my baby brother was a baby i
n arms when I got married - when I got married and of course mum had - had just had him. Oh yes, I knew - I knew what to expect. I don't - when I say - no, I didn't know what to expect, I knew all about the way babies came and all that sort of thing but t
o say that I expected anything like as dreadful as it was, I was three days and three nights and I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You hadn't known it was as bad as it could be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. I don't think I'd have got married at all if I'd have known. Not if I'd really known - it 
was going to be as bad as that, of course, it shouldn't have been really, I was too young and unformed that was the trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say it was any harder because you were surprised by the pain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I don't think it was any harder because I wa
s supposed to be an absolute model patient. Everybody congratulated me, doctor and everybody afterwards. No, I will say that - because - I say I was one of those people who could stand the pain easily. Always have been. Can now for that matter, stand more
 
pain than most people of my age could stand, they say so. Even at the hospital today. No, I wouldn't say that. I think that - I - in fact, the doctor - the doctor of course didn't - thought I ought not to have any more and when I fell with Joyce and she w
a
s coming I expected to have almost as bad a time and of course didn't. It was quicker you see the second one because it was only two years - two years and four months afterwards. But - no, no, I should say that I - actually I anticipated with the others -
 a worse time - time than I actually had. They were both pretty bad but it - not as bad as the first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When the children were born at home did you have a doctor there when they were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he just come .....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, w
hen Ronnie was born the doctor was with me - not only did he come in three times in the day he was with me all night. It was marvellous - absolutely marvellous. And he - and he had the - matron from the West Street nursing home, in Brighton and a - and a 
nurse with him too. Oh no, I had wonderful attention really although it wasn't expected as I say. It - it was just that he - he - he sort of tell, he'd been the only }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 gynecologist}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  at that - that particular nursing home for ten year and I was his first patient after he set up in private practice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your husband help at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh no. When I say he didn't help I wouldn't - the idea of having him there while the baby was being born would - have filled me with horror.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he stay with you while your were in labour or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh good gracious no, he never came near from the time - they wouldn't have let him. They shut him out. No, not in those days, couldn't let him, he was sitting on the stairs outside until the doctor - of course I didn't 
hear this until afterwards - the doctor went out and said to him, now you leave this Mr Hargrave, that you'd be for better if you went to business and occupied your mind because - he said, is she alive because I can't hear a sound? Because I didn't squeal
 or anything like that of course. My - my daughter Pat did. She gave - she gave a yell at the Northern hospital when her baby was born. But - I didn't make a sound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So he didn't know whether you were alive or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, he said, is she alive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How soon afterwards were you out of bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh I would say about - oh a long time. I was - a month in bed and then I was out for - for nearly another month, three weeks in a bath chair. It would be quite - quite seven weeks from the time I had the baby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That was because you had had a difficult time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Terrible time, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not everybody would spend that long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Oh - no, but most people - most people if - unless they were very, very poor, couldn't do anything else, spent a month in bed in 
those days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I've always - I've always declared since I don't believe in the modern way of getting them on their feed so soon, I think they're back into hospital with gynecological troubles today much - much more likely than we were in those days because we
 did have that rest. Oh no, weren't allowed to put your foot to the ground until at least a fortnight afterwards and then only to sit in a chair by the bed, it gradually - in the same way as you would after a major operation now. You always employed a nur
se for at least a - least a month. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 After a fortnight you'd sit on a chair or something and then it would be a month before you'd be up altogether?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It would be a month before - before you'd be able to do without the nurse and get about all d
ay then you'd be advised to take things gently. If you could.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you manage the house and the other children while you were in bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well you see I did - it was no difficulty with Ronald because I was - I had my home was stored. Dad had got
 it stored in Stapleton Hall Road and I was in furnished digs. And - when Joyce was born, now what happened when Joyce was born when I - well I was at home, and when I got up - oh I had help. I only - but we did it quite easily, I only had a little girl a
bout fifteen or sixteen to help me. But - to do shopping and do rough work and that sort of thing, I only really pottered about at the time. Dusting and doing things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did any of your relations or neighbours come in to help you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh they 
used to - it would be relations when I had my sometimes - used to take - the - when Joyce was born my sister - my granny, my granny had Ronnie for a time. When Joyce was born, well until I was better and - able to get about myself and - when - when Pat wa
s born one of them was with one grandmother - my - with my grandmother and the other one was with my father's mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That really was the biggest way in which they could help you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, definitely. And then I always went home to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Regina}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  in Stapl
eton Hall Road when I first got up and of course there were servants there. I went home perhaps for a week or a fortnight. And then I - I would have the children back after I left there. People - your relatives helped you much more than they do now. The W
elfare State has destroyed all that. Everybody leaves everything to the state to get on with it now. Very few, I'm not going to say parents don't go, but a very few of them think they've got any real responsibility you know today when a baby's born.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It's a little bit more like that in Ireland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 There's more family life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I was going to say the family life is gone, it's utterly destroyed you know, I - I think it's a very cruel thing, very poor thing it's happened. But I think, yes, 
but it was very strong in those days. I mean - it was classes, there was more class distinction or so they say, class distinction's still here now, - they - although they - they make out it isn't but it is because like still goes to like, looks after like
. But there was more actual class distinction them but even then the family life among the poor was - it - equally as strong as it was amongst the middle class people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You had a nurse when the babies were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long would she stay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 A month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did the nurse do to the baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Everything. Practically everything. Yes, oh they were - they were trained - they were trained of course, they had taken their C.M.B. any rate even in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would they gradually let you see to the baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, they would practically do everything until they went. Except, if you were feeding the baby of course you'd do the feeding, but if you weren't which I wasn't able to. I tried to feed Ronnie but doctor wouldn't even have - 
Joyce, who was born in Crouch Hill - he wouldn't even have her put to the breast at all. Much to the nurse's horror. When she came. But he wouldn't - he said, gave me opium to dry up the milk - the very first night. 'Cos see I'd had such a bad time before
, he knew that, he was the - he was our family doctor and brought all my mother's babies into the world except myself and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Freddie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , the other four he had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What milk did the nurse give the babies, was it cows milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - in - you see they varied '
cos my children were always difficult, they - none of them ever wanted the same thing. When - Ronnie was - being fed from bottle he nearly died because he wouldn't take anything. Glaxo had just come in then, I tried Glaxo. Dried milk. Practically - practi
c
ally every milk there was of that sort on the - including - I can't remember the names of them, but any rate he - we tried him with all the milks, he couldn't keep any of them down. He got awfully frail. I thought I was going to lose him and I - then my h
u
sband was taken ill with pneumonia and he'd be about - three month old then - and I rang his mother in London and his mother and his sister, who was a nurse - sister - came down and fetched him back and they put him on what I wanted to and Ronald wouldn't
 
let me because he said no baby of his was going to be brought up on tinned milk was put on - on Nestles Milk and barley water. And the thrived wonderfully on it. Now - of course I got a great - I began to have great belief in it and when Joyce was born th
e first thing I - she wouldn't touch it. Just vomited it up. And she was brought up on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 cow\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 milk and barley water. And Pat was brought up on - oh one of - Glaxo - yes, Glaxo. She was a Glaxo baby. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you start feeding Ronald from the bottle immediately?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. When Ronald was born I tried to breast feed him. And it wasn't until I came up here and my doctor saw me, Doctor Lutonwell met me, I came up from Brighton and he met with mother and he - he just gave one look at - and he said, let me lo
ok, at the baby. He looked at the baby, he turned round and said, well you know Grace, he said, you feeding - are you feeding the baby? So I said, yes Doctor, I'm trying to he said, well don't - don't - try any longer. He said, wean him immediately or you
'
ll both be dead within the next few months, and so of course - and he knew I was doing it because I wanted to save the money, I - I hadn't told my people how badly off we were and it was then that mother turned round and said, I'd said something about not
 want - not according it, and she said, well Grace, you - you give the baby whatever's necessary and I'll pay for it. But of course things were better afterwards, when the others were born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you tried all sorts of milk and you eventually put him on Nestles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Barley water. And he thrived wonderfully on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then Joyce you didn't try?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, Joyce I tried Nestles milk and she wouldn't touch it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You didn't try breast feeding her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. Doctor wouldn't let me. Immediately
 he gave - he dried the milk up immediately. As I said much to the nurse's disgust, she was a doctor's wife. And she said, not even to help close the uterus you know because if you - when - if you put the baby when it's first born it helps. Yes. That was 
it. So he says, not at all, he says, take her out and feed her on pap. I can hear him saying it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then Pat was born in hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well they tried in hospital, they tried in hospital to - to feed her - of course I didn't have enough milk. An
d the consequence was they put her on alternate feeds. First mother - first mother's milk and then the bottle, by the time I left she was completely on the bottle. The milk had practically turned to water. She had Glaxo, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I hope you don't mend me asking these questions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh not a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were breast feeding the babies for that sort time, did you find it very difficult?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh shocking, I'd got such - I'd got such tiny nipples. I had to have a - a shield. A nipple shield in order 
to draw out the nipple. It was so small.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That usually works doesn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, it usually works but I was very horrified because the doctor made the suggestion that my husband should break the nipple strings first. In other words he said the nippl
e strings, the strings, they call them the nipple strings, that he should - you know, draw through the - oh of course I was horrified, such thing - in those - oh I was absolutely horrified. Of course he never did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I've never heard of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. 
No, they said that - they suggested that - but of course - years ago, it's sixty years ago - sixty-one years ago and - they - as I say that - I was absolutely horrified. Ask your husband to - break the nipple strings. I looked at him, with a look of disgu
st. Oh dear, dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If you had needed advice about anything like the feeding of the baby and that who would you have asked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I think my mother. Oh yes, I think I would have asked mum. The way she - she'd had six you see. And only one a very shor
t time before I had my own, only just over two years, my brother was only just over two years old when Ronnie was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If the baby was asleep did you waken it for a feed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, never. All that silly nonsense - of timing them, no, the baby's sleep
 was more important than anything else. Never woke him. If he woke up and cried at the usual time then I should know he was hungry, gave it to him, but if he was a sleep I didn't. And I didn't believe - I didn't do - mind you I didn't do what a lot of peo
p
le did, walk about with them and rock them and that sort of thing, I never did that because even in those days my commonsense told me that shaking a - the person about after they'd eaten couldn't possibly be good. But I would take hold of him and put him 
across my shoulder and pat his back 'til he'd broken the wind and also I used to have, with all three of them, I used to have Woodwards gripe water. It's still in existence isn't it. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If it cried in the middle of the night would you pick it up and feed him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, but - yes, I used to feed them in the middle of the night at first but it - it wasn't very long before my babies went - slept through the night. I didn't really have very many bad nights, I had rather bad nights with Ronnie becaus
e he was so delicate. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 
But of - that's the first but apart from the others - no, I don't think, looking back, I as always on the qui vive to hear the cry and to - see if they needed anything but I - taking it as a whole I don't think I - can't remember havi
ng any very bad nights unless they were ill. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When they'd start cutting teeth and that sort of thing you'd get a few.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If they cried a lot before the normal time would you feed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Definitely if they thought they was hungry - you know some
how you can tell a hungry cry, in a baby. There's some difference between a paddy cry, a pain cry, it's funny how you do get to discriminate, and you can tell one between a hungry cry. It's got a peculiar little tone of its own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If it wasn't a hungry cry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It'd be an irritable cry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you used to do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh part it and turn it over on its side or something like that. Sometimes I'd take it up for a little while. If it was very persistent.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How long did you let the baby go on feeding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What - from the bottle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I think it means when they were feeding at the breast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Ah. Well you see, I didn't - do you know how long in the - in the feed you mean. Well it would depend. Well it would depend, I don't think I timed it, I
 don't think I timed it, I mean you could tell the baby'd throw the breast out of its mouth. But you see I did it for such a very short time really. I didn't - no, no, couldn't say it was established.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember when you first gave the baby solid food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I should think probably about - not - not nearly as early as they do now - I should think probably not until about - I can't remember really but I think probably - first solid food - mind, when - Joyce was born the doctor said go out and see -
 and nurse did, that was bread and milk very finely - that was pap, that's what we called pap. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 That's just bread and milk very, very finely mashed together, of course only a little. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Almost - almost liquid, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You'd give them some sort of light cereal like Farex or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And things like rusks at about six or seven months?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When would you give them mashed vegetables or things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well you see mine were - mine were pretty - pretty earl
y on top of it, they almost came together. Almost together. Before twelve months anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When did you wean the baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They mean from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 breast}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  of course don't they, from the breast. But I never - they didn't have that you see to do at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you had your first baby did you think that it was wrong to let the baby cry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, I had rather the - yes, but of course I learnt it was a fallacy but I was always afraid with Ronnie if he screamed very much he would rupture himself. Of course it's absolute }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 rubbish}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
. Old wives tale. And if I'd had another boy - so I didn't have - but of course I've had grandchildren, my daughter had the same; fear and - and I made her, when I was in Birmingham, I made her come with me to the doctor's and told her w
hat a silly - he said, if your child was to rupture itself Mrs Tedd, that was my daughter, if your son was to rupture himself it would be because he was about to rupture himself anyway. It was only the - just - just - precipitated a little. But, he said, 
nonsense.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you thought it might do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you punish the baby when it was naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I suppose - yes, I should give it a tap. Tap. Just a little tap like on his hands. When he began to run about I think my favourite place 
was to tap was on the back of his little - little legs. Oh he - oh he used to hate it. Tap his little calves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What would he get that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh only if he did anything that was - for instance - if - if he hurt the little baby - of course he never d
id it deliberately but children are }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 rough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 with a new baby when they come and that sort of thing you know, and I remember once doing a thing - a thing I never did since because he was - terribly frightened of fire and he would play about on a hob and burnt 
- nearly burnt himself and very lightly I burnt his finger with a match. Yes. Very lightly. Like so as - so as to - and - that's what going to happen only much worse if you touch that stove again, I was so afraid - I had one of those small Laver kitchen s
toves you know with all polished up. Terrible hard work. And - I was so terrified because he would go and sort of put the - grab it you know and of course he burnt himself badly. So I remember do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ng that and I remember my mother being terribly horrified whe
n I told her. Oh, she said - don't - what a dreadful thing to do. I said, well he never did it again. Only just momentary you know, just put the flame there. He squealed like the dickens. I said, it's a thousand times worse if you put your hands on there.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How much did your husband have to do with the children when they were babies under a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Not much. Not much. He right have - if I wasn't well he might get out of bed in the night and - and put the bottle in its mouth and then get back into bed again. That's about all he did do. Oh men do much more now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your husband never changed the baby in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. Yes, when I say he never changed them I'm telling a lie. He did the last one. He did the last one because I was taken ill whe
n Pat was only three months old with he two - Ronnie and - and Joy were both upstairs, this was at Finchley, they were both upstairs with measles. I couldn't get anybody in the house to help me at all because any nurse that came in would be in quarantine,
;
 the war was on, and they were - hold themselves available for war work, the soldier were coming home in their thousands, and the hospitals were full. But - well then he was wonderful. It's wonderful what a man can do, if - if - he had to because I went d
o
wn with a septic throat and nearly died. And of course he just had to. And when he eventually did get a woman she came up to me, she said, I've never seen anything like it, she said, you ought to have seen the kitchen. She said, there was the - we had one
 
of those airing racks you know to these laver kitchens, there were little piles of napkins as white as snow. And those little - little underclothing all on there to air. Well she said, you couldn't have been better if you'd been the most tidy women. He wa
s a tidy man. But - but - he didn't - I had the job - he only did it in an emergency.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He would never offer to do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, he never - he never - if I said, if I'd have said to him, will the change baby, he'd have looked at me askance. Oh no. But
 he could do it you see. Yes, he had to. The same - the same as he could cook if he had to. He didn't offer but in an emergency he could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So that means that you fed them and you changed their nappies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did everything as far as that was concerned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever get them to sleep?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. No, they - they - sometimes he'd - they'd say, tell me a story daddy. And when they were getting older and he'd do that downstairs, not up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever play with them when they were tiny babies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No
t a lot, but sometimes. But more when they got to the age of more interesting age when you could buy them an engine instead of playing - giving it to them to play with you played with it yourself. I always remember my boy saying one Christmas, I've never 
f
orgot that, he bought one of those new electric trains, they were just coming in for youngsters and he spent I think two hours one afternoon with it on the floor, of course he was playing with it himself and - Ronnie was standing by, only quite a little f
e
llow, and he said - very drolly. After a few minutes he stood watching then he said, daddy, is that Christmas - is that Christmas present mine or yours? So - and he was little tiny fellow me was and he said to him so quietly, he looked at him, daddy - wit
h
 that question mark on his face. Is that engine set - is that electric set - is that electric set mine or yours? And I said, go on - you - I said, no wonder he says that, you've been playing with it - he said, I've been showing he boy. Only of course he w
asn't, he was thoroughly intrigued with it himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever take them out when they were small babies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Without you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, not in - not at pram stage. Go out with me of course at time with the pram, but not often. But he did - wh
en they got to about - to walking age, well it was a ritual, every Sunday morning. He'd take Ronnie, not Joyce. After Joyce came - but he - Ronnie right up until after Joyce was born. He would take out every Sunday morning while I cooked the dinner - wher
ever we were living. That was quite a ritual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I would like to ask you about how you and your husband managed the housekeeping in the years before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He - that first few years of marriage he used to hand all the housekeeping back to me and all 
the money he earned he earned to me and - and then I'd give him so much back. To have in his - that was to being with. Until he began to get on better. When he began to get on - well of course not after he got on the Ministry. Then he would give me my hou
sekeeping money monthly. He'd be paid monthly himself and then he'd give me so much you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At that time did you know how much he was earning?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Pretty well. Because on the - on the Air Ministry scale of salaries for certain positions you knew pretty well what he was earning, yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember what proportion of that he would give you for the housekeeping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, I can't remember - I can't even remember that now because it went up from time to time, when he had a rise I had a rise you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So he was good about that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, he wasn't - he was good about that sort of thing. He was very good really because if it came to - even with clothes he was very good. If it came to a question of him having a new pair of s
hoes or me having a new pair or the children having a new pair it was always us. For one thing he didn't like new shoes, he couldn't bear them. I think it was the fact - it was a little bit of self there. He couldn't bear them. And he hated the look of th
e
m. I don't know where that came from because if he bought a pair of new shoes he would go out and rub dirt into them before he'd wear them and then polish them so they'd look as if they'd been worn. And one thing he loathed, it was the look of what he cal
led new shoes. Couldn't bear it, quite a - a thing with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you discuss together how the money should be spent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - in the early years until he got - he'd got on better, then I didn't so much. But you see - ours was rather different to most
 people because - when my mother died in 1926 I came into a little money of my own, about six or seven hundred pounds which was quite a lot of money in those days to what it would be today of course. And after that, you see I was married in 1908 - 1908 - 
a
nd it was about 19 - it was about 1926 before I had any money of my own, I didn't think it was as long as that, but it was. And - up to that - after that time of course he'd - he used to give me regular money but I never asked him anything for clothes or 
holidays or anything. I started to pay all my own clothes and my own - own expenses that way, not household expenses, nor holidays when I went away with him, but personal things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And also - and my father - when my father died I c
ame into some money I also - put down the - it was I who - and entered in my name. I put down the money for the mortgage on the house that I had. And - he paid the rest until the time that we broke up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the early days when the children were born and up until 1919 did you discuss how the money generally should be spent?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - more or less, yes. And we were - in the early days were on what you called a shoestring, there wasn't much surplus. Though it didn't worry - the thing was to get the bills 
paid, the light and gas and the children's clothes and their school fees when they started school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In those early days when money was tight did you discuss even like the details of the grocery bills and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no. Wouldn't have any
 of that nonsense. Good heavens no. Never accounted for - never had to account for money. Never. Oh no, I bought what I think - what I thought and I turned out to be a pretty - a pretty good - a pretty good cook so that - I - I never remember serving up a
 meal that he didn't say was all right. As far as that was concerned at any rate if he didn't - if he wasn't in the mood to say it was all right he never grumbled. And he was pretty fussy about his meals. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 And he was very, very fussy I'm glad to say, that - 
because it was good for the children, very fussy about how the table was laid and all that sort of things, whether the knives were polished you know so that you could - even he - he was terribly, embarrassing if we went to a restaurant and he'd pick up th
e knife and I've seen him pick up the end of the tablecloth and clean it before he'd use it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Which was very bad taste in a restaurant but still he - he'd he was fastidious. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Fastidious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  in table - over table manners. A bedroom and a sitting room. Bedroom, kitchen, sitting room and - a toilet of course and bathroom.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was in the little flat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. In -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At Turnpike Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were first married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That was when I was first married but I was only there for a few months be
cause directly I fell with - with Ronnie the doctor said I could no longer go on, I was very ill, had very bad carrying and we got that - stored the furniture and Ron being in the artistic world you see could - and being good at his job could change it ab
out from pillar to post}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 he got a job down at Brighton and that's how I go - got down there because it meant I hadn't any work to do, I was in diggings and I could - benefit by the sea air.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Let's take the house at East Finchley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It was East Finchley was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. Crouch End - Finchley, what did they call it, not North Finchley, not - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 Churchend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 Churchend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  Finchley.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How many rooms were there in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Three bedrooms, bathroom - bathroom and toilet and two sitting rooms and kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any relatives or any lodgers living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh no. I've never lived - I've never had lodgers, never. A short - a very short period for - an Indian officer that was lent here during the war, came - we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 put}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  him up for - but he wasn't - he wasn't living here permanently, we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 put}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 him up for about three weeks while he was finding hotel accommodation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So there wasn't anybody else living in the house at Churchend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, any ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you have any help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Any what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Any girl or anything to help you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I used to have daily help. When I could get it. And of course there's the period I was at the Air Ministry I had a housekeeper. I didn't think much of those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you had the daily help, what were her duties, what did she do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Mostly shopping and taking the baby out, I much preferred to run my own household myself. Or perhaps kitchen work now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What hours would she work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I only had her for half day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you call each other, what did you call her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Madam she used to call me. Madam and I used to call her by whatever her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 
Christian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  name was. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you had the housekeeper when you were working.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When I was at the Air Ministry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did she live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I had to - I had one, an absolute gem. Linda her name was and oh she used to keep my babies spotless. Sometimes I'd - I'd come back from the West End to Golders Green, 'cos I was living at Finchley then, and she'd meet me 
at the station and - oh she used to keep that child so beautiful, I was sorry when she went. She went because her own mother was ill, lived down in the country and she went back, then I got another one. Oh dear. She was like a Grenadier guardsman. And I c
a
me in one day unexpectedly. Oh I was horrified. I came in one day unexpected and I had my kitchen at Finchley used to lead - down two stairs from the kitchen into a scullery - separate scullery. And I came in one dinner hour unexpectedly and she was sitti
ng on those two steps eating her dinner off the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 floor.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 I never saw such a state that my baby was in with great lump of bread and jam in her hand and all over her face all over the pram. Oh it was terrible. I - of course I gave her notice, dismissed her - di
smissed her immediately and I - of course not that day. Told her to pack her things and go the next day and I remember her coming in - coming to me in the morning, standing over me - just like a Grenadier guardsman, I was so small and she was so big - and
 - she - I just told her what I thought of her and she said to me, I've never had such a character in all my life. She said - I'm a good mind to punch your husband on the nose. She didn't - but she had - she had to go, oh I was determined.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did she live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. Yes. While - when - while I was at business they - the housekeepers - the two had - Linda was a treasure. After then - then that was what really made him when I fell ill myself send in my resignation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Apart from when you were working you just had daily help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 During that time how was the washing done, the washing for the household?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well, there was a - it was a woman in - used to live up in the - I've forgot the name of the road now - but anyway she used to live near
 me, she used to take washing in. Take washing in and she'd - she'd deliver it. She delivered it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She delivered it back to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, come and deliver it back all ironed and ready too. Of course the baby's stuff I used to have to do myself. It
 was only household really because I men you want it. I used to - used to do the baby's stuff myself. And their little frocks and my own dainties 'cos I never liked anybody else to do those, I liked - I was rather fond of ironing, wasn't so fond of washin
g. 'cos I wasn't a good washer but - I was fond of ironing and I liked to iron my own things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So she would do the linen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She'd - she'd do the sheets and the pillowcases, towels and - what I call the uninteresting washing. So much a dozen they us
ed to charge in those days. They don't have anything done at so much a dozen now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you make any clothes at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not - not - at my - yes, I did for a short period. I - I never earnt - I had a - 'cos these were simple then, I remember - remembe
r making a - buying a - only a small quantity I think, about two yards, that's all it took for me then. Two yards of evergreen crepe de chine and making and absolutely plain frock with a black cord at the waist and a black butterfly there. Ever so easy to
 
make, I had a machine, a little machine, a hand - although I loathed it, I prefer hand work. And I - tried, and didn't make a bad job of it, at making clothes for Joyce. 'Cos she was a little girl you see, I never tried to make anything for the boy. Not i
n the way of little suits. But I used to do - yes, I had an attempt at it for a time, a short period. And - I'm not a bad needlewoman, I can do it. I used to hate that school but I don't mind it own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Around that period when you were living in Churchend did you buy all the family's clothes new then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh most of them. My husband used to buy most of their clothes. We'd go out on Saturdays if they want anything, together you know, and he - he'd buy their - pay for them. I'd choose them, he'd pay for them. And shoes and boots and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did you buy them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh different shops according to - sometimes you'd go to Golders Green, which has always been a good shopping centre. And sometimes to -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you ever go into the West End?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, sometimes we would but not a lot. Not a lot. No, I went into West End for my own shopping more when things got a - when things were comfortable. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 
But - I don't remember buying a lot of things for the children in the West End except toys, we used to go to Hamleys, you know, that was - sometimes we'd go to - the people in Holborn. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, Gamages. Sometimes we'd go there but more often to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Hamley's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
. For toys at Christmas, or birthdays, times like that. Otherwise I didn't do a terrible lot of shopping in the 
West End. I always found I could get what I want - Holloway's always been a first class shopping centre, much better than it is now and - so really it wasn't necessary to go to the West End for shopping. You could get what you wanted - the shops had to so
 - deteriorated so, but - Crouch End was good shopping - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Wilson\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  used to be a wonderful shop for shopping.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about shoes, were they always bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What, for the children you mean? The children, we were very particular about the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 children\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ' s
hoes. We used to have - at Clerks even in those days and those other makes of shoes, always had their shoes - their shoes measured - their feet measured and their shoes fitted. Very particular about their shoes because we thought it was essential for thei
r
 feet. It was a waster of time because immediately they got - the girls particularly, not Ronald - had got to the age where they could squeeze their feet into shoes that were too small for them and cripple themselves. They did it because there they were -
 
actually jealous of my feet, well I never had to do it because I've got tiny feet. But they're a menace now 'cos I can't get anything. Impossible unless it was made - I can't get anything to fit me. But they - we were particular while we were able to cont
rol their shoe wear - about their feet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you bought them for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Oh until - 'til they got to the age where they went to business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you buy the shoes locally too, in Golders Green or Crouch End?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - at any of the stores t
hat - Myholmes or anywhere that - that did the standard shoes like - where you measured them. There was a particular make. I've forgotten the name of the make now that we used to buy them, they had four different fittings. I've forgotten the make of shoes
, they're quite a well known make too, they still make them. Yes. Startrite. That's right. Startrite. Yes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Startrite}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
, that was the - those were the shoes we used to buy them, they were small, for them, Startrite. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your husband help in the house at all with anything like cleaning or cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh only if I was - I'd have to be very ill, wouldn't - oh no. Oh no, he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I was thinking about the house in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 Churchend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Don't remember him doing anything there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 would he make up a fire?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh if the coal was there, 'cos we had coal fires in those days - if - the coal - and he'd go out of course if I - if I was - hadn't filled it myself which nine o times out of ten I did. Or one of the girls did you see when they were growing up, perha
ps Ronnie would. And he'd do - I'd do that and of course he'd put coal on the fire but he spent most of his time fiddling about with the wireless. From the time it first came in he - he was obsessed with it. Twiddling the knobs and making the most ghastly
 sounds. While I went out with Joyce to the club and dancing and that sort of thing. That was my eldest daughter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever do any decorating in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very seldom. He did once or twice. He could do it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 
But very,very seldom he - but he'd - he'd rather pay somebody else to do it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
But he could do it of course, having been a - a commercial artist he naturally could. And he could mix his own paints and make his own colours you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever do any repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Or improvements?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Not often. Very seldom. One period he got rid of it very quickly, he did have a proper bench for making things. It was a new toy though, he soon got rid of it. I think he could have done it. He did - did make one or two things although I d
on't know what happened to them, they weren't very important because I haven't got any of them now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever help with the children by way of dressing them or undressing them or bathing them or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Ronnie he did once - yes. Ronnie when 
he was about nine years old it was awfully funny 'cos of course I'd thought nothing of it I'd go bathing him, and; then suddenly when he was nine years old one night he struck, Ronnie did. He went into the bath - mummy I don't want you to come into the ba
t
hroom, I can do it myself. So I - it suddenly struck me you see that he was nine and he was growing up so I went down to his dad. So he said, well he said, that's perfectly natural dear, I'll go up and see that he washes himself properly. And not until th
en, only with Ronnie. Oh the girls wouldn't have let him bath them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever tell them stories or read aloud to them or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He would sometimes, and he would play a bit with them because he'd - he used to tickle them and that sort of thin
g you know and play about - when he felt in the mood. Sometimes he'd feel in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 mood}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
, sometimes he wouldn't. Didn't do much of it 'til the - in the latter days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Did a bit more of it in the early days.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did he ever take them out on their own without you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
He did - oh he used to take Ronnie out sometimes, yes, he had taken them out without me. Particularly - particularly Ronnie. You see, being a boy I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would he ever look after the children when you were out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not until they were g
etting older. When they were getting older yes. Yes, he would then. But not often. Yes, he has, he has in the early days said to me, oh I - I'll - I shall be at home today, or something like that, go over and see your mother, but very seldom. I wouldn't s
ay he never had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the children have regular household tasks to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes. That's - definitely. Yes they did - they were given their - given pocket money for doing - doing a tasks. If they didn't do it they didn't get the pocket money. So there'd
 be a huge rush at the end of the week to get that task in. At the last minute, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time did they go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Fairly early. Until they - were quite old, they were in bed by the time he came in at quarter past six. Until they were quite old.
 And when I say quite old I mean 'til they were - 'til they were probably about - six or seven. And - and they were never in bed until they got really - to - ten or eleven or twelve - they were never in bed after about half past eight even then. Oh no, we
 
didn't - they were quite regular about that. It was a habit in those days if you were - middle class - to get the children in bed before your husband came in and then sit down and have your meal and you'd go up and kiss the children goodnight you see and 
talk to them up in bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They'd still be awake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did your husband used to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He used to do that. When they were young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They would still be awake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They'd still be awake and you'd allow them to take picture books to b
ed and that sort of thing. It was quite a regular have it to get washed and bathed and - in bed by about six or half past. Then we'd have our dinner together.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then he'd go and see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. And - until the - go up and talk to them for a mi
nute or two and then say goodnight. He'd have to be in a very bad mood not to. Or late. Late in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the children put themselves to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - pretty quickly, yes. They were self reliant in that way. Joyce and - Pat of course, she was the baby,
 I suppose she was the - longest to be - to be put to bed by me particularly and she had one habit only and that was she would not go to bed until she turned out - I hadn't any voice - but she turned to have a lovely voice and she used to say to me - no m
ummy, not go to sleep 'til you sing. And I'd have to sing one song always - oh how tired I got of it. And she'd roar with laughter, that was - quite up 'til she was about five years of age. And that was Katie at the kitchen door. K-K-K- Katie. And she }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 wouldn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 go to sleep. If I was going out to a dance or anything and - perhaps I was late, I'd know there'd be a screaming set out until I'd sung that song to her, sat and hold her hand and say that song to her then she'd go off to sleep. Children are creatures 
of habit you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They like their habits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. They like their habits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they share a bedroom together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Shared a bedroom, oh yes, the girls. Of course Ronnie always had his own bedroom, that's why we needed the three you see. The g
irls would have a bedroom to themselves and Ronnie would - have the - the small room. Where we were living he'd have a little room on his own. And always separate beds, I never slept in a double bed, always had separate beds from the time they were - yes,
 all the children had separate beds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where did the children bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the bathroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How often would they have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Two or three times a week when they were small. Sometimes - then they gradually got to the stage when they - I don't k
now, I've come to the conclusion - conclusion that children are not too fond of water and then they - they took on a weekly bath and hate it you know. Not the girls so much, the boy particularly. Boys used to hate water, washing behind their ears and that
 sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When did the children have clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Every week, every Sunday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where were the meals eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In then - in the morning room usually because you see I'd got two - when I'd got a house I'd got two sitting rooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there any time when you age in any other room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When I'd only got one room do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the house in Churchend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. No. I had the two sitting rooms and the kitchen of course, two sitting rooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you ever eat in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, very seldom. I might have a snack if I was on my own but we wouldn't dine in - oh no, the children always went into the room with their meal break.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you do some cooking yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Always. I did all the cooking. Unless I w
as ill I did every bit of the cooking. My husband liked - might do a bit if I was ill but - I always did the cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Where?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In the kitchen, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you cook on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh, when I first got there I had a Layer stove as I told you, an ordinary kitchen, small kitchen range but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 With coal do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, yes, with ordinary coal. And - then I had it changed 'cos we had it changed to an Ideal boiler and then of course had a gas stove. I've - and I've always liked gas stove cook
ing, I still do. Although I had for about seven or eight years I used the electric - electric cooking. I loathed it. Too dry. Too dry altogether, I hate that business of waiting for the residuary heat too. So when I got away from - the Manor house where i
t was an all electric set up there I went back to gas again. Gas stove.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I can't manage the electric cooker at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I love gas stove cooking, I like it. I think food's nicer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time was breakfast eaten in the house at Churchend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Bre
akfast, well of course - when the children had got to get to school at nine it had to be somewhere about - my husband - of course he didn't have to get to the Ministry until ten. But I used to have breakfast somewhere about eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who would be sitting down for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh the children would sit - always sit down together. Their - their father would be down very often with them. I didn't sit own very often, I was too busy getting them off. I didn't eat much breakfast, I don't eat much breakfast now, 
you get in the habit of not eating breakfast, not wanting it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you usually have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 for}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh my husband had eggs and bacon, a good old English breakfast, and toast and marmalade. And now and again I'd have sausages for a chance.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh more or less the same, toast and marmalade always so course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh the children would have the same, either an egg, not the both always, they always did on Sundays, they had both, isn't it funny
 how you get - stick to habits. But in the week they'd have something other - sometimes be bacon and tomatoes, sometimes be a boiled egg for the children. But I think my husband's breakfast was almost inevitably the same and he would have porridge first. 
He would have porridge to start off it. The children got to loathe it but they used to have it when they were young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you have anything different for breakfast on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - no, usually much about the same. Sometimes we'd have - perhaps kidneys and bacon or something like that, but it'd be similar. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 There'd be switches and changes and very, very seldom, but they didn't like it at breakfast time, we would have it for teatime sometimes - sometimes kippers. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, but they - they never liked kippers - fish - they're not fish eater, never liked fish in the morning. Any of them, not even my husband.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What time would lunch be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh after school time you see, it'd have to be somewhere around one o'clock. And usually my husband of course had hi
s lunch out, lunch out at the canteen attached to the Ministry. And - they would come home to luncheon because they'd want a meal with going to school midday but then they'd have high tea, and my husband wouldn't have a - a - any - have a high tea when he
 came home because he got a good luncheon in the midday at the - at the Air Ministry canteen. So I wouldn't do another big meal cooking only Saturdays and Sundays at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When the children were at school came home for lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And then went back to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
They - then they went back to school and then they came home then they'd have high tea. And a midday luncheon. Then my husband would have a - from Monday to Friday - he'd have a luncheon in town you see and then when he came home
 he'd have a high tea, something cooked. So that's when you'd have perhaps kippers for a change or - a - a sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 potato}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 pie or a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 shepherds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  pie or something like that, for high tea. And cake and jam and all that sort of thing and butter and bread.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You said that was during the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
During the week. Well on Saturdays we'd have midday dinner and Sundays we'd have midday dinner, yes, it wasn't until they went out and business that we started having evening meal. Which is the best time to eat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So all the time the children were young at school?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 We had midday dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And a high tea in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's right. That's right. They hated school dinners, now and again I'd make them stay for a school dinner you know, especially when 
Pat was at the convent but - they didn't like it. Couldn't bear to stay to school dinner. And when she was at Latimer she didn't like it either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you make any bread yourself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Only an attempt now and again. I might attempt it but it was - not too good, too successful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about any jam or pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh I did that, I still do, I've just made some apple and - and tomato chutney. Oh yes, I still do that. When I've got - when I'm feeling like cooking. And of course I made all the cak
es and all the cooking. All the cooking really. There's not much I can't cook. Jugged hare and everything. I liked it. My; girls are good cooks bug they don't like it. They don't like it but they're not - no, it's because they've copied me and they still 
c
ook in the same way but they still don't like it. If I go there and do it for them, which I did for a great number of years at holiday times and that, no good now, I'm past it, I don't - can't do it for big crowd - family - they - they love me to do it. O
h yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So you used to make pickles and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. Fruit, jam, pickles. Not because I couldn't buy it in jars I could, it was because I liked it better, they liked it better, the only thing was it was extravagant because it went so 
quickly. They liked it sufficiently and I'd say, well that's gone, you're not going to get any more. So don't eat it all at once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever make any wines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Except punch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was that for a party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's for parties, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Any beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, I've never made any beer, I'm never a beer drinker, didn't like it. I've got two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Guinness\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  - bottle of guiness in there, been there nearly a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. My mother did. More like brimstone and tre
acle and all that stupid - horrible things, and licorice powder, none of which could I take because I had - always used to retch against them. The others of the family'd have to have them and they'd have to give me something different. Like syrup of figs 
or something like that with - slip down easily.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you bottle any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I have done. You know, things like beetroots and - beetroot and onion and pickled onions I have done. But really they're made so well now and so cheaply it's not worth the time doing them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you were in the house in Churchend did you grow any vegetables or fruit in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, I let the children have that to play in, it was quite a big garden too but really it was more of a playground for
 them, just lawn and flowers just around you see for - of course I had several fruit trees. And - no, I used - used not to bottle it but I used to make a lot of pies and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you use any tinned or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not 
dried vegetables, no, always had fresh vegetables but - I've used them since I've - latter years now more since I've been older but not the family and - not a lot of tinned either, I like fresh fruit, you could get it easily then, it wasn't so expensive. 
No, I preferred fresh fruit, still do. If I make a flat I still prefer - prefer fresh fruit to put in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you keep any hens or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. I always had a dog, but not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was the dog a pet for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 More or less Always - always belonged to one or other of the children whatever pet I had, and of course a cat. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who looked after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I think we all had a say - all had a bit of looking after them. But there I mean there was - there was food got re
ady for them, I'd probably prepare the food and they always knew what time they were going to be fed. Animals are creatures of habit too. They'll jolly well ask you if you've forgotten it by any chance. And - and a bird. Oh yes. Birds. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 You see, the children even pets know - even had - even had pet mice, Joyce had pet mice until, she put one in the oven because she thought it was ill and burn it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It was so funny, it had new ones - new little ones you see. And she had the two, she bought the two from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Wood Green}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  market, she came in with these two white mice. And after they had them a short time they gave birth to these - these little tiny ones, just like baby's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 
fingers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  without any hair on, horrible looking things, and - do you know that there was the - I didn't
 know that you mustn't touch then. I opened cage and went to touch the little things, do you know, the father ate them all. Ate them. The father. 'Cost I'd touched them. I checked - the chap at the Wood Green market told me I ought not to have touched the
m
. I forget how long it was, but it was, but it was a certain period, about seven days I think. And he ate - he - he - he actually ate them. And I got - took a violent dislike to it. I told her to jolly well get rid of it. I'm not going to keep a cannibal.
 
I'm not going to keep a cannibal in - in my house. Horrible. And do you know that she - she was terribly upset about that and then one of them, the mother mouse seemed to be ill one night. Well I was out or it wouldn't have happened. And - she put it in h
er breast to keep it warm. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 And that didn't - it didn't seem to get any better and so she'd - lit the oven very, very low and put it in there and forgot it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I came in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 most vile}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  smell. It was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 burned }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 to a cinder. I made her - I made out a horrible - my ove
n - I was weeks getting it to what I call - really - really fit to put food in. And - then of course she went and sold the male one up in the market, got - got rid of it. But they were wonderful those mice and they must have been awfully fond of her becau
s
e before this happened the female mouse got out and we thought had lost it and she - she put the little mouse cage down where we knew there was a hole, you know, where the piping was. And do you know, after three days it came back. It came back and went i
n
 - and we - we'd given up all hope of the blessed thing ever coming back again and - when suddenly we heard a funny little squeak about three nights after she'd - put it down. Went in and there was the little thing come back again. I said that the others 
gave it such a time, the wild mice, that it decided that it was better off in your cage. Oh yes, oh we had some fun with animals, we bought the children up to have animals. The children - we had a rabbit too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember how many times a week you would eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 At midday?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Every day at the midday when we had the midday meal we had meat every day. Of some - oh except the days when we had fish, we might have fish sometimes. But meat or fish. Meat fish or poultry, one o
r the - other. Yes. 'Cos you could get it - food was cheaper in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever have any meat sent to you from the country or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, well you see we had plenty of meat sent to - sent to me by - while my granddad was alive. He use
d to get it from - he used to go up to Billingsgate you see and - up to the market every week and he'd buy stuff and then bring it down to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever go short of food yourself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Often. If there wasn't enough for the - if there wasn't enoug
h to go round mother always went short. Yes. Although my - my husband didn't like it because he'd very often say - I'm not eating unless you sit down. Oh I don't feel like it. He'd cut it in half and put it on my plate. That was if we were - if I sat down
,
 that's why I got out of the way of sitting down with them because he'd often do that. Well if there wasn't enough to go round it was always the - always mother who went - I think it always is don't you, even today. Yes. I think if anybody goes short - th
at - or if a visitor comes unexpectedly. Yes. Give your portion up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you find that your husband needed to have larger portions just because he was a man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I always gave him a larger portion, although he hadn't a big appetite, in fact he hated i
t. If - if you was to say - if you happened to give him a full plate, I hate my plate full, I'd rather come again. You see, he was that type you see. Oh no, put him right off. Yes. No, I never piled his - plate but he'd say, if I wanted more I can come ag
ain. But you - I - I had a tendency to - the tendency is to give your husband the best I think. If there is a best, yes. I think most people do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were you particular about table manners with the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Very. Very.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they expected to behave themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. They were made to leave the table if they didn't. There was no grabbing like the children do today. I want this, I want that. Oh - well you carry on very much as you get brought up yourself you see, we were brought up lik
e that, particularly me and - because we were a lot of girls then and - dad thought girls particularly manners were a - an essential. And I suppose you carry on the same. Of course my husband didn't like bad table manners either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you allow your children to talk at all during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, we got past the stage - we weren't always allowed - although mostly we did talk as girls, but - if mother and dad were talking or they'd got a visitor and they were talking and we butted in dad'd then say, 
children should be seen and not heard. And sort of - damp you down so that you didn't - sometimes he'd say, speak when you're spoken to. But if there wasn't anybody - any particular conversation going on we talked. Passed comments.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your children were allowed to?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, I never said they mustn't talk at table, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were your children able to choose what they wanted to eat from what was cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 to an extent, to - what was cooked - what was non the table, to an extent they were. But as a
 rule I brought them up to eat what was put in front of them. The - there was - they got to the stage like all children do hen they don't like green vegetables or they won't eat flat. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 
Well - my husband had the attitude that my father had, well if you don't eat that you don't get any sweet. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
But I - I got out of that after a time because I think that - force food down a child is bad. Better let it go without than that. Because it'll eat when it's hungry. Sot that - that died down. He started off a little bit,
 you'll eat what's given to you. But we soon stopped it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was your attitude if they left some food on their plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - the next time you're going to get half the quantity whether you like it or whether you do not. I'm not going to have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was your attitude if they left some food on their plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I used to say, all right next time you have half the quantity, if you can't eat it you can't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And would you keep to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. You wouldn't find they'd leave much after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they have to wait until things on the table like the salt were offered or could they ask people to pass them things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh they ask you to pass. Would you mind passing the salt mum?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes, if they thought there was a second helping there to have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they asked to hold their knife and fork in a particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they asked to sit in a particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, sit up. No lounging at table, as their father would say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were they allowed to bring a toy or a book to the table?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When could they leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 After the - they would usually - unless there was something particular on, for instance they might be a bit late with their meal and go
t to go to school. Can I be excused they'd say and we'd say, yes. But if they just wanted to go - if it was a Sunday or anything like that you'd say well, you're father - daddy'd say, well wait 'til your mother's finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did all the family present sit down for the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Weekends. All present. Oh yes, if we were all in, if we were all there together we'd all sit down together. But of course there'd be sometimes when - one would be perhaps out - especially after they started of course going to b
usiness, which was pretty late.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And a breakfast time you yourself might not sit down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Never sat down at breakfast - never - I seldom ate any breakfast except perhaps I'd snatch a piece of toast. While I was - while I was really preparing more th
an anything else, a little bit of marmalade, but actually I didn't sit down at breakfast time except at the weekend, and then I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they have regular places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They went to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who would serve the meal up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I would. Even the - even - I used to even carve on Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
When the children were small babies and weren't able to feed themselves properly were they allowed to sit at the table in a high chair or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And who would feed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I would. The baby - the high chair would be put near where I was sitting at the head of the table or the bottom of the table as she case - usually }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 daddy'd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  sit at the head, I'd be at the bottom.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you would feed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
 'Til we taught the baby - my children fed themselves pretty quickly you know. Even in the high chair. Very quick they were, used to teach them to use the spoon as soon as I possibly could. Because - it was that feeling wanting them to handle knife and fo
rk and feed - and know what it was for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the children ever eat separately when they were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not often. Very seldom. I mean if one was - if one had been kept in at school or something like that, yes. But not otherwise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When your children were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 young}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  did you feel that there was a right or a wrong way of binging up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I thought there was a right way to bring them up. I thought the way to bring them up in my opinion was to - to bring them up as - to know - for me particularly, 
what I'd said I meant. And they - they were - they were pretty adaptable, they got to the stage where they knew how far they could go and how far they couldn't. The certain things that I never overlooked. And some things that my husband wouldn't overlook 
if he wasn't there I would probably would - would do so because I didn't think they were worth making a fuss about. But I never - we - I never went against him when he was there and he never went }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 against}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  me. Which I - when you were in front of the children, we might say - go afterwards when the children weren't about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you and your husband have the same ideas about bringing up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Very much. That was one - about the only thing we did have in common I think. Yes, I think - think that was p
robably why we kept together so long, 'til they were grown up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you talk about this, about hat was the right thing to do with children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I think we talked about that, although we were so young when we got married I think we talked about t
hat, looking back now, even before we were married. Because we used to see examples that we didn't think were good in front of children, you get the way of saying, well if we had any - so and so and so and so you see, and it used to happen that way. He us
ed to undo everything because he used to get in rages so easily you see, that'd upset all these different things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there anyone you used to talk to if you were worried about the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, not - I made pretty much my own decisions. Sometime
s I talked to granny and sometimes of course I'd talk to mother. When I was near. But actually at the time I'd make my own decisions. And very much resent anybody else interfering really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your mother was alive of course when your children were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes. She died when - no, of course Pat was very small when she died. She was - Joyce was only fifteen so Pat was ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How often did you see your mother when they were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh often, 'cos I was living near you see, living in the neighbour - every day nearly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ask her advice in bringing up the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Only very, very - very occasionally. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
She'd ask me little questions and I'd answer them you know and that soft or - it was more }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 conversational}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  than seeking advice.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did she have the same ideas as you about bringing up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
She was - perhaps she was a tiny bit - what shall I say - in some ways - looking back, you see, people mellow with age. When my children came along she got much softer than she was with
 us. And I used to say that to her when she used to sort of make excuses and say so and so and so and so. I used to say, well you used not to say that when we were young. I think age does that, you get - you get - you're much more tolerant with your grand
c
hildren than you are with your own. Yes. That's what happens. I think that's a natural - state of ever - evolution. And more my father. I actually took more - now what can I say - now I - I love my mother very much but I - and - was more I wasn't scared o
f
 my father but - I respected him so much, perhaps it was an over - overdose to respect, it would be as children think today any rate - that - and yet I valued - I knew he was so sound that anything really serious, I would just - I would ask his advice. An
d he would give it as advice, he wouldn't give it as a sort of order and - or sort of - la}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
ing down the law. He'd say, well you know Grace, if I were in your place so and so and so and so. And I'd - most of the times I'd agree with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about your mother-in-law?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well - when I first started - I - I never - I got on with her well as a matter of fact but I didn't like her very much when I was first married. Then in the end she'd - especially after my husband and I broke up, you'd have thought I w
as her daughter, he wasn't her son. She had no use for him after we broke up at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Because of the children perhaps?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She was - she - she wouldn't even go away for a holiday when she was left - when daddy died and she was left a widow for a goo
d many years, because her husband, was seven years older than her any rate and - she lived to be eighty-five. And she - when she wanted to go away on hole - she couldn't go away on her own in the summer, and her family was grown up you see and they'd all 
g
ot their own families, but the boys wanted to pay for a holiday for her to go away for a holiday and they paid for me to go with her too because she wouldn't go away with anybody else. She preferred to come to me - come with me than she'd go away with one
 of her own daughters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever employ a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 nanny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, well Linda was nothing more than a nanny really to - to Pat. She was a very charming one too. Very good one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you talk with her about how you wanted the children brought up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
I think don't I had to very much because I was so satisfied I think she was almost an example to me more than anything else. She had such wonderful patience. And of course Pat was pretty and she loved her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you ever disagree with Linda about the way shed managed the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Never once remember having to disagree with Linda. I think that was one of the great disappointments - silly things - we say that's one of the great - but it was disappointment when she was going. I knew I was los
ing - losing a treasure. She went home, her mother was ill and she went home to her own mother to nurse her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You don't often find someone like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. Very seldom, the only one I ever did find. And it was short lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 tell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  me some of the things that you felt you ought to do for your children, did you feel you ought to show them affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I think children need - I think all children need affection. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 
You mustn't treat them as if do - do - what you mustn't do and you can do, oh yes.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you fell that you ought to give them safety - in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What - see that they didn't get - oh yes. Turning kettles away and all that sort of thing you mean. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were conscious of that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you think food was important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Very important to feed them regularly and very important to give them - little and good if necessary, but always the best, I never bought anything but the best in food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And discipline?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I - oh I thought discipline wa
s very necessary but I thought that - too much discipline wasn't - wasn't too good. You see my husband was erratic, he'd - he'd be terribly disciplinarian, then all - when he was feeling good tempered, for the same thing he'd stopped them doing he'd let t
hem do you see, wasn't consistent. It went according to his mood. Which I thought was bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Children do realize that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh - they play one off against the other. Oh yes, you want to watch for that. But I've never seen - I don't think you can pick ou
t any - body people that are grown up that are more artful than children about that. They know just how to play one off against the other if you let them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you want them to share their worries with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh always talked to - oh my girls alway
s used to come and tell me everything from they time they had a first sweetheart right to the end, oh yes. I should think it was because I was married so young you sort of grow up with them, it's not so easy - although I've found it fairly easy - not quit
e as much as my girls - to talk to my mum, certain things I didn't find it - easy to talk about. I couldn't have talked about sex matters with my mother. But my girls could with me, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you want them to behave towards you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 With respect. 
Wouldn't put up with impudence. I wouldn't hesitate, however big they were, if they were really rude impudent to give them - Joyce said she could remember my ring. She looked at my ring she was home from Australia this time. Mum, she said, you've still go
t
 grandma's ring mum. I said yes. She said, my word, I can remember that ring. Although they wouldn't talk to me now like that, they - I'd get up something and throw at them. If you ever talk to me as I - some of these little children talk to their parents
,
 I couldn't stand for it. I never did with my own people and I won't stand - and I' don't think they'd ever do it though. It - they - either Joyce all the way from Australia, 'cos I noticed it several times, there's still that little bit of - respect ther
e that you don't often find. When she sees me getting - getting annoyed about something she knew just when to - which I did from time to time because when you've got all the family meeting all sorts of funny things happen, she'd know just when to stop.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you had Linda how did you want them to behave towards her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
To do what they were told. If you put somebody in control of them - it's the same thing at school - there's no coming - good coming home and complaining to us about the teachers, becau
se they get told very quickly that if they'd been punished they - they hadn't been punished for nothing and - and not to come home telling tales of their teachers because they'd - only get punished again. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 So they - very, very soon stopped it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, I don't t
hink it's right to put a - a child under somebody's care and then rob them of any authority. I think that's all wrong, and there's too much of that going on today. It's all wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When the children were young and you didn't have a nanny or anything, d
id you both ever manage to leave them so that you could go out together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Very seldom, but I did once or twice. When they were - because I was pretty sure of them and once they were in bed - but I never - I never was at ease 'til I got back again and saw everything was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 all right}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
. We did a bit of - we started a bit of that when we were younger but the elder we got the less we did instead of more. Less. Because you began to realize what accidents could happen and it spoilt your enjoyment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The few times you did do that who looked after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I did - nobody, I would go out - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You felt sure they wouldn't move once they were asleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 They didn't - I'd feel pretty sure they wouldn't wake up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you let your children join in the conversation when grown ups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. Not when they were small, when they got old enough to join in a conversation that was an entirely different thing, fourteen or fifteen years of age. But when they were - I wouldn't - no, well you see 
we were lucky, unlike most people today we always had a second sitting room so the consequence was that when grown up people were there talking they - you - the children knew that - when they were small you - you'd say, oh do you play or do what you want 
to do - daddy and I and so and so and so and so are going into the lounge. And - they might run in and out and ask you something while we were there but we - no, we never talked really grown up stuff in front of the children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What would you say you brought them up to consider important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Truthfulness. Above all things. Truthfulness and a respect for their elders. And we used to tell them that - that - I thought - which my father had told me, that I thought a lie was one of the worst things
 you do, that you can never trust a liar. You could lock up from a thief but you often - were unfair to a liar because when they did tell you truth you just didn't believe them. Drummed that well into them and also said that if you tell the truth you - yo
u don't get punished but if you're found out telling a lie you do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you tell them to hit back or not if another child hurt them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. We used to say - like - well you see it was - having one boy and two girls. Used to say to Ronnie of course, h
e was the elder, you don't hit little girls. Cowardly. You want to hit somebody, hit somebody your own size. And a boy, you don't hit little girls and of course the girls - there was five years and a half difference between them and they didn't - that occ
a
sion didn't really arise. When I was thinking - only saying so earlier when they were here together now as women with - with families, I said - Joyce was more like a mother to - to Pat. She wouldn't have thought of hitting, oh they never - never fought. T
h
ey'd argue. Especially when they got to the age of - and Pat'd get to be about sixteen or seventeen and have a few boyfriends, and Joyce was five and a half years older but you - of course she was more - more advanced in her conversational prowess and the
y
'd quarrel over these boys, perhaps Pat'd say you spend time talking to so and so and so and we were going so and so and that sort of things you know. But which - likely to go on in any family but as a matter of fact as children - they were particularly d
evoted. In fact, I think Pat would really much rather do what Joyce told her than she'd do what we told her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any other children that you discouraged them from playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I used to say play with the children that I considered were
 decent children.; Oh yes. And I let them go - let them come in the garden and play with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there some children in the neighbourhood that you didn't want them to play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Didn't make any effect, they still played with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was it you didn't like about those children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
They spoke badly. And - I suppose I'm rather fond of good English. Still am. Still rather listen to a commentary on there than look at a - a Liverpool film or something like that. Just - just the sound
 of the voice. But - I think it's wrong - now, as an older woman I think you should let them mix with all sorts. I think it's good to let them mix with all sorts because although they may pick up a - a bad way of speaking they revert to type sooner or lat
e
r as they grow older. I've changed my opinion with the years, but in those days I - I'd - as I say I carried out what I was brought up to probably myself. Myself - it was better to be selective and in their companions as I could, but I say it makes no dif
f
erence. The only difference it makes is that they mix with them at - behind your back whereas if you have the other attitude you see and you see if any - if the result of it is bad habits or not, then it's time to check it. If you've got some definite rea
son - I - well it's unfair to the child. Because you're bringing the child up to be - in effect very snobbish too, I - I can't speak to you, you don't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 talk}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  properly or something like that, well that's very - I began to realize that was something the child couldn't help, it was rather hurtful to the other child. So if I had my time over again I wouldn't have done that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If your children did something you disapproved of what would happen, would they be punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 In some sort of way, it would depend 
on their age you see. Then most - most of the times it would deprivation of something that they wanted. Not to go here or not to go - all right, you're not going so and so and that'd be far more hurtful than going in - for violence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How often might they be punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Very seldom really. Very seldom. Looking back I think my children - I thought not at the time - because I've never had sort of dust in my eyes about my children but looking back I think I was particularly lucky. They were really - on 
the whole. Very obedient.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who would do the punishing, you or your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13464736\charrsid8657389 Ronald}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 wasn't capable - he'd punish. He might punish Ronnie, he never tried to punish the girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He'd refer them to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes, he never tried to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you had Linda working for you would she ever punish them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, she was too - she was only really nanny Pat you see, the others were - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 Joyce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  was - when Pat was born Joyce was five and half so the time Linda came to me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 J}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 ce was getting on for nine 
and at school. You see, really she only had Pat. And I can't imagine - I don't think she ever punished, don't think she ever wanted to, she loved her so much and Pat loved her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember any particular occasion when you punished them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No,
 not particularly. No, I don't remember. I can't remember any particular occasion. I can't remember anything very - dreadful that called for - but I can remember my husband once or twice - twice with Ronnie. Of course it - it sounds awful now but he was o
n
ly a little boy, you see, I had a habit, I ran a bill with grocers at the corner of - oh I've forgotten the name - the name - they used to be at Churchend. And - I found, they sent me in a bill - one day for about twenty-five shillings over what I'd order
ed. So I took it back to Mr }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 Phillips}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 and he said to me, oh young Ronnie's been her, he's been in there ordering sardines and all sort of things and taking them to school. They - they'd been having bean feasts there in the lunchtime, he was only about eight 
or nine. I think it was nearly two pounds he run it up to for me. Oh his father was furious about that, I think - he gave him a hiding. Gave him a hiding about that but I often look back and I - because he did it so innocently. Because I used to send him 
down sometimes with my order you see. So - he used to add to it. Well Mr Phillips of course if he'd known that he was doing it on his own wouldn't have supplied him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did the child know he was doing wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I think - I don't know if he knew th
e extent, that it was sort of a form of stealing which was pointed out to him afterwards. No, I think that he thought oh mummy gets it from here, I'll get it from here. Yes, that's it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you say that your children got the ideas they had about how 
to behave from both parents or did one of you play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Yes, they only had one bad - one bad example, of course that was the shouting and raving and that, and they don't - they do a little bit of it amongst themselves
 but I mean they don't - do it in the way that the did. Not even in their own homes. No, I thin - it probably - it probably had the effect of making them hate it rather than make them copy it. I should say really and truly looking back - one of them I can
 see, one of them - one of them only I can see certain of their father's characteristics, but they're mostly his good ones. I'm lucky. They're mostly his good ones. And the others I think are all like me, the other two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When Pat had Linda looking after her what influence did she have on her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well I think that she - she was so young, I think that it was only a sort of - emotional one, she got - grew fond of her and - would put her arms round her nick, in fact I got quite jealous. Although I knew th
at Pat was happy 'cos she looked it. I don't think I would have - let Ronald send in my resignation if I'd have had Linda to keep on. But I would have got - felt - that she - she was getting too big a hold on her if it lasted longer I don't know. But some
times I'm certain.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She looked after Pat while you went to work and the other children went to school did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you feel about leaving Pat with somebody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Didn't like it. Was glad when I came home, I really didn't
 like it. Never felt that it was - and when the lady next door said to me, oh dear, she said, I don't think that the - she started - she said, I don't think that the housekeeper you've got now you would approve of Mrs Hargrave, she said, she's been - she 
puts the baby out in the front in the pram and give her great lumps of bread and jam to eat, right on my nice pram. No wonder it's getting so dirty. And of course of which I would have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 
utterly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  have disapproved of because of the proper times for children to 
have their meals. And I generally came to the conclusion that - she - too young to be left. So that I really didn't raise any objection when I - my husband said to me, I've sent in - no, he didn't actually say it. I got a letter to say that my resignation
 was accepted, he didn't tell me anything about it. And I knew what had happened then and I said, whatever made you do that? Well, he said, you don't - now don't tell me - after what you told me about so and so, this was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 Grenadier}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  guardsman - that' you're happy about it either. And he said, there's no necessity for you to - to go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you think at the time that it was a good idea for children to be with their mother all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. I don't think it's good for the child to be with its
 mother all - the time, I think it becomes - it becomes too motherised. And - not sufficiently independent. To - too dependant. Of course I was always believed in cultivating independence, I was a naturally independent person on my own, nothing to do with
 bringing up, it was hereditary. A naturally independent person, I think I wanted them to be. I wanted them - I didn't want them to be rude and aggressive like children are today but I wanted them to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 independent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , to stand on their own feet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When your children had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did they get presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh - presents on their birthday, and when they were younger somebody in to tea, in to tea and that sort of things, oh yes, I - I certainly did that. They had to have their special days, we had ours.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Some would come in to tea, would there be special things to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh they'd have all sorts - my Pat - oh yes, party mum. Jellymanges, Jellymanges. I can hear her saying it now. Jellymanges.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Can you remember anything you did with your husband and children on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No. Most Christmas Days were not too bright, too happy, there was nearly always a row of some sort on Christmas - I hated them. I hated them after we stopped 
going home, you see, there was a period - it wasn't until my mother died that we ceased going home for Christmas. We used to go to dad's always, the married ones and the children as well. And of course we used to have lovely Christmases there and it wasn'
t 'til we started - and everything'd be very nice and he'd go out and spend money and we'd have Christmas trees and decorate it and make the place and nearly always every Christmas dinnertime there was a row.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Why was that I wonder?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I don't know. 
Shall never know. We were only saying that the other week, talking about that the other night too. I don't know, it seemed to be - I don't know whether with - with having so many and getting excited, they got on one another's nerves, or what - it was or -
 
I don't know, but it didn't - it was a smaller house. We'd been used to a big - when we had our Christmases at home we had a bigger house with plenty of room. Whether it was that in a small house you're too congested and you get - and you're - I suppose I
'
d get a bit irritable, I'd done a lot of cooking. With - and he being with the children 'cos they'd been round to him all the time and perhaps he wanted to get at his blooming radio or something of that sort. But it - I - I didn't look forward to Christma
s - at all. I didn't look forward Christmas until we started - we decided we weren't going to have any more Christmases at home and we went down to - Brighton, we had friends - go down to a hotel down there. And we used to go down there at Christmas.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you enjoyed that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And naturally - oh yes, we enjoyed that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, my piano. I had that. Didn't have any other instruments except a violin that Ronnie had and he threw in the lake, after
 he'd had about - after I'd paid for a quarter's lesson. One day he came home and said he'd lost it. He'd thrown it in the lake. He came in when he went to business, it was so funny, when he first went to business he used - he was eighteen too. He - well 
of course he had a little bowler hat you know like the little proper }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 conventional}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  little - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 job}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 as my - my husband used to call the young office boy and - threw that - came home and said he'd lost it, threw it out of the train window. Because he hated a hat,
 he doesn't wear one now, unless he's - if he's going up to meet some of the directors and then he'll wear a trilby but he never wears a hat in the ordinary way. And that dates from his boyhood when hats were worn.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Who played the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did any of the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I - I had - no, Pat sang. I used to play for her, used to play her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11032391\charrsid8657389 
accompaniment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 . See, she snowed she'd got a lovely - nice voice while she was at Latimer. The - when they tested her voice for the - concerts you know, used 
to get up - go up some of the musical comedies and that at school. The mistress sent for me, the music mistress and she said, you know, that daughter of yours has got a lark in her throat. And I paid a guinea a lesson for her to be trained for a time but 
s
he wanted to be an opera singer and - but she started to get cold upon cold and the - master she was under, she was terribly disappointed, said to me, you know Mrs Hargrave, her health will never stand up to it. Prior to the - the health. And I think it w
as, he said, she - she - it'd be wonderful recreation for her. Don't encourage her to go professionally, because her health won't stand up to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 It is tough isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh very tough. And you've got to be awfully - awfully healthy, I didn't realize how much until I interviewed him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did any of you sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
No, not my children no. Oh what am I talking about, that was in - Pat sang, she had a beautiful voice. Oh not - not - no, I didn't, my husband now and again did, I'd join in of course. I m
ean I don't reckon I've go any voice but - nor I reckon Joyce has got any voice. Pat has and Ronnie did when was he was small because they - we thought - we thought at one period we would try and get him in Winchester, in school. But it - they found they'
d
 got to chant the psalms. Go get in there they'd got to chant the psalms before they were nine. And he was just on nine and he - he wasn't sufficiently advanced to chant the psalms - the - and we had another boyfriend of his who did - chant the psalms and
 the - the friend of - still}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389  a - friend right up 'til the w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
ar when - I think he must have been - he disappeared, I think he must have been killed - and he went to Salisbury and his brother went to Winchester, both for their voices. And for education. You se
e, they go to Winchester College, simply on their voices alone.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Your eldest child, the boy, his first job was an assistant secretary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. In - so near - in a hospital. Then he went into buying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then he became a buyer of aeronautical equipment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then your next child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Then my next daughter started business in the Post Office. She was there for about two and - two years and then she went to the Prudential. From the Prudential she went to the Ancient Order of Forresters where she remained until she married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Doing clerical work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Clerical work, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then your next child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then my daughter Patricia, when she left school at eighteen she went into the - for a year she was at the Church Assembly
. Then after that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What is that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
The Church Assembly, oh well it's were the - they assemble to make all their - their rules and regulations for the Clerical Authorities throughout the year. Oh she well known, she was actually there, she was in 
the office. Attached to - doing clerical work. And - then after that the war broke out and - she joined first of all the W.A.A.F.S. Then she came home on compassionate grounds because was ill. And - after a short time at home she joined the W.R.E.N.S. whe
re she remained until she married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's all isn't it, your three children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's all, that's the three of them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Now your own brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I had two brothers, the eldest was a - a - my brother and the youngest was a boy. My elder brother was an auctioneer and surveyor.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Right through. And - my younger brother an actuary. Still is out in South Africa, perhaps it's a result of actuary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And he began as an actuary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, he began studying, of cours
e he wasn't an actuary 'til he'd passed his exams. And then he became an actuary - passed his exams and became an actuary. For a short time he left it, he came into a little bit of money and started a hotel in Devonshire during the war years for five year
s he did that. Then he decided he - he was fed up with that, so he went in for his final exam which he hadn't passed, he was then over forty, passed it and - took up actuarial work again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Both your daughters married didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. Both married. And eldest one married a friend of her brother's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What was his first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh I wouldn't - couldn't - wouldn't know what his first job was, haven't the faintest idea. But - he - he's - supplier of household equipment. He's in Australia of course now, has been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 there}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  some years. And my younger daughter married - an officer in the - in the Army during the war. Later on she - she divorced him and married again a - an architect and surveyor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you know what her first husband had done before going into the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
He went straight into the Army, he was at Cambridge. He was at Cambridge when she met him. But - she - he was still at Cambridge when she met him and then he took a commission and went to war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And her second husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And her second husband -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you know what his first job was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh always in the same firm, architect, except for the six years of war when he was at the war but went back again to his original firm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then your own sisters, did any of them work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh they - yes, they went - I was the only one that didn't go. My two sisters went to business, both in the Prudential. My second - the - my youngest sister remained until she married and my - the next one, the one next to me, left after two or three ye
ars, after she became }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 charge hand}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  of a department she left and went to the Bank of India, which she remained in 'til she married.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That's both of them doing clerical work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. All on clerical work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about their husbands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The - my
 youngest sister married a fellow who was on the Stock Exchange but as he was of foreign birth and it was shut to foreigners after the war he then went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 Schroeder\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  bank as foreign manager. That was my younger sister. But previously to that he had marrie
d my other sister. Because - I'll tell you what happened. He married my other sister, he'd known her the longest too, but she'd married in between. A cousin. And - they weren't very happy because she wanted children and he was - he didn't want them becaus
e
 he was afraid of the blood. Afraid of the blood affecting the youngster. And so - in the end, after about six or seven years, they agreed to a divorce and during that time Hilda had died and she married her brother-in-law. And brought up his three childr
en and had three more of her own. A lovely happy family now too, wonderful family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 This was the same man who was in the Bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, he was - at Schroeders, foreign manager.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So it was the same man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Except for the first husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
He's dead now. Yes, except for the first time he married. Married Hilda first of all. Then during the war years of course he had to go into the Army for a time. Then he came out and got the managerial position at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 Schroeder\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  Bank.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Then the other sister meanwhile had married a cousin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 The other sister - had - had - he had - early, yes, she married a cousin before; the war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did the cousin do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oscar - oh he was a - I don't know what he was in, export, yes, an exporter. In exports.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 A businessman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were married before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, I was married on 1908. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When your children were young did you feel there was a right way and a wrong way of bringing them up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Oh within r
eason, I mean, each child had to be really taken according to his character, you can't bring them all up exactly the same, you must have rules and regulations but there are some who want sterner punishment than others. Some are easier to manage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you and your husband have the same ideas about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 About children - yes, definitely. That was something in which we - were consistently agreed upon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Was there someone you could talk to if you were worried about the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I never wante
d to - particularly. I might have - I might have from time to time discussed it with my mother who I saw a great deal of when they were young. But - I don't know that I particularly wanted to, no, I didn't do very much of it and - I never discussed my }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 children\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
' faults with anybody. But mind I didn't take their part when they were in the wrong, in fact I used - I never thought they were angels, like some mothers do. Like - I could see when they were in the wrong, but - I never discussed them with other peo
ple at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When they were small how often did you see your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh quite a lot. When they were really - except for - of course there was periods when I didn't because of course we travelled about a lot, my husband being in the - it being in 
the - on the Air Ministry and - we went to different parts of England. So that we were away sometimes for two years. But when we were close by, when we were down - we always }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 came back}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  to the old North London. When we came back here then I saw them a lot of my mother you see. That - two years }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 before}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  she died particularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you and she have the same ideas on bringing up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, she would have spoilt them a little bit more than I would perhaps.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 She tried to spoil your children although she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 hadn't}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  spoilt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, she hadn't spoilt a lot oh her own yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about your husband's mother, did you see much of her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. Not so - yes, even in the beginning I did. There were gaps. There were gaps. But I saw her - yes, I s
aw a very great deal of her, and the more I - more we saw of each other the closer we grew together, I mean, after my husband and I separated you'd have thought I was the daughter, not him, she didn't see anything much of him at all. But - I saw a lot of 
her, used to go away for holidays together and that sort of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you ask for her advice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No. I wouldn't have taken her advice I don't think. I don't think our ideas would have been exactly the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 At one stage you did have a nanny didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well - what do you mean, myself I did but for my children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 I meant for your own children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, I didn't, I had - on and off, I had a housekeeper once or twice. But otherwise I brought them up myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When you had housekeepers did they take much part in looking after the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Linda - Linda - yes, Linda was very good, she was the one who was so good to Pat, who was so good and so fond of her. But - I didn't let the others, they had something to do with the children but not with their bringing up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So they weren't really nannies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No, not nannies in the true sense of the word.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Could you tell me some of things you felt you ought to do for your children like did you feel you ought to give them affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes, I think children need affection, I'd no more think of my children going to bed without I - when they were small - without I went up to them and - never could sing but pretend to - sing to them or read them story, and Pat never went
 to sleep without she'd - held my hand 'til she'd gone off to sleep. Oh yes, I believed in - I believed in giving them affection and I believed in - also insisting on certain things being done. I suppose I was a bit of - my son says I was disciplinarian s
o I suppose I was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you believe in safety being very important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Oh yes. I think you should take every - every possible action you could to stop accidents such as - turning the kettle away and - putting guards in front of the fire and all that sort of thing, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I'd been brought up myself to have all that sort of thing - caf\'e9 so it came naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 You were aware of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. It came naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What about food, did you think that was important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Food? Very important, all the best - I never bought anything but the best, however - sometimes I was very short of money, but what I bought was good, always the best. And of course I was very lucky in as much as I had such wonderful grandparents. If
 they saw the least sign of shortage they bought me a lot, I had a lot given to me in the way of - even in the way of food. They never went short of anything in food, that's why they're - fairly healthy I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 And you were keen on discipline?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, to a certain - to a certain extent. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 
But - the sort of disciplinarian, we hear rubbish on there, on that blessed television, that of course wasn't exercised either in my family or else where. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
There - there was always a certain amount of freedom in -
 in the class of people that I - that I mixed with. I mean all this nonsense about never being allowed to do this, it was rubbish. Just rubbish. I suppose there was some families like that, there is probably some today. But - it wasn't - it wasn't the maj
o
rity, mind we were more protected than girls are today. We were never allowed to visit a house without our parents knew exactly where we were going and very often the first time we went there - some - dad or mum would come and fetch us. Or send somebody t
o do so, see what sort of - household it was. Of course that didn't - that didn't prevent us getting hold of some bad companions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you want your children to share their worries with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well what - I don't know that they had any particular wo
rries to share really. I mean they used to come home and tell me all their episodes with their different sweethearts and all that sort of thing. And - we were more - well I was so young when I married and so we really grew up more like sisters, or friends
 really, the mother and daughter. With the girls particularly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How did you want them to behave towards you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well I wanted proper respect. There were certain things that - certain liberties they wouldn't - well they wouldn't have thought taking, 
that's all I can say, I didn't lay down any laws about it but - if they were - were impudent I'd say, who do you think you're speaking to? And they'd know. They'd know that I was annoyed. No to be - I didn't have much trouble that way. No, I can't say I d
id.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 When the children were young did you ever both manage to leave them so that you could go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes, we'd have somebody used to come down and mind them, I had one very - lovely family, the Reverend }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 Marsden}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 , was the Minister of the Highbury, 
he had a maiden sister and she used to come every week for one whole day so that I could go out. She stayed until quite late in the evening. And - from time to time of course I had friends that would come in and stay and leave them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 How often would you say you managed to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Well I went out with my husband every Friday night, I never missed. Always went somewhere, out to dinner or something like that. Except in illness of course, when there was illness about then you couldn't come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So it would be friends mostly then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, mostly. There weren't such things as - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 babysitters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would the people that came in stay in the house or just look in or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh no, no, they'd stay when they were very small, when they got
 older, when Joyce was about fifteen I didn't worry at all, I'd leave her with - and she'd look after them, but then we'd never be very late if she was left in charge. If we were going to be very late we'd rather somebody older was there. Providing we cou
ld get them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you let your children join in when grown ups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Not when they were small - no. No, well we never discussed things in front of - not private matters, in front of them because we were fortunate enough to always have two 
sitting rooms you see. Where now it's almost unheard of to have two isn't it. You've got to make - find it - they haven't got the same advantages of bringing children up, children know everything today, which - very much goes against the grain when I hear
 them - they just join in grown up peoples' conversation, they know all about it, but, no, mine - I didn't until they got eighteen or - when they got to seventeen or eighteen it was different then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 What did you bring them up to consider important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
Truthfulness first of all. Honesty and truthfulness, they were the two most important things, I hated lying. And - the - feeling of doing unto others as you'd like to be done by. In other words - I taught them decent behaviour and that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Those were your father's beliefs too weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh yes. My father was - even more so, yes, very keen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Did you tell them they should hit back or not if another child hurt them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I think I'd say - I think I told Ronnie not to - not to put up with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 
bullying}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
, if somebody hit him, yes, yes, definitely. And I would say so again, even today. Providing it wasn't somebody smaller than myself. I pointed but to them how cowardly it was to hit somebody smaller than themselves but - yes, I think 
that I did bring him up to - stand up for himself. 'Cos girls didn't fight. In those days. They might have a - a span amongst themselves you know but - they didn't fight. It's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 \endash }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6035631\charrsid8657389 unladylike.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 Would have thought so unladylike in those days. Although it isn't - I have smacked somebody's face before now. When they've been impudent. I don't mean women, I mean young fellows, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Were there any other children that you discouraged your children from playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes. I don't know that I was wise, I was 
wrong I think. Yes, I think I was wrong. Yes I think I was wrong. As the years have gone on I've felt that children should mix with all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 types}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  of children because you never know when they're going to - what's going to happen to them later on. But I didn't. 
I was some - somewhat - selective about it. If they bought round - I remember on family and they all turned out to be very - very successful. About six boys out of Finchley, and I was living in Crouch End, and they were - but they were coarsely spoken and
 rough and I very much objected - the Penny's - people named Penny - I very much objected to the - children mixing with them, the two, that was Joyce and Ronald. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 
But - you - you can't always be behind them and I think they did a bit of mixing just the same, as they years went on they all turned out to be very, very successful boys. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
And - I've taken my sister at Wembley, I've watched her bring up - 'cos of course she was married much later than me, to her brother-in-law her second husband. And - she - to her 
- yes, her brother-in-law her second husband. She - she married relatives didn't she when I look at Dolly. First she married a cousin then she married her brother-in-law. Yes. But - no, not a blood relative but - she did - and he - believed in making welc
o
me anybody they liked to bring round, it didn't matter whether they were black, yellow, what they were. And - it's worked out. They've all turned out very nice people, very nice people indeed. And - so I think that my way was wrong and hers was right. But
 
you see you - the thing is that you don't - you - characters alter so. You take my granddaughter. She's got into bad company, you see she's been mixing with people and taking drugs, now that I mean - that - that should have been nipped in the bud, Jack to
ok that rather - her father rather took the attitude that you can't rob a girl of her friends. But they were the wrong friends. Especially today, I think it's more important than ever to find out what type of people you're mixing with.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If your children did something you approved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 If they did something specially decent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 That you disapproved of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Oh I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would you punish them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well it would depend how old they were of course, when they were small yes. Oh giv
e them a smack occasionally tool. Somewhere where it wouldn't hurt them, I don't believe in boxing children's ears that you used to hear such a lot about because I think it can injure them. But I think a - a whack - a whack round - I - I had a little cane
 - a whack round the calves of the legs or somewhere like that where you couldn't do them any damage didn't - do any harm either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Would your husband ever do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Not with the girls. He has with the boy once or twice. No, he was - although he'd h
ad - been in the Army and rather brought the barrack room into the house he never really was violent with the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Do you remember any particular occasion when you punished them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Yes, I remember him being }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 furious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  with Ronald, he was only seven for going - he was in the habit - he was in - no, he was a bit older than seven, he was about nine I think. No, he couldn't have been, he must have been younger than that because he had }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389  when he was nine. No, he must have been about seven. We had a big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 grocer\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 hill in one day, it was while he was going to the Finchley Grammar school, and - for groceries. He'd only been going in and ordering them and having them put on my account and taking them up to school and dishing them out to his pals in
 - in their luncheon hour. Of course since I've laughed about it many times, but he did it quite innocently, he thought -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 He didn't think it was wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 No. No, he didn't think it was wrong. He thought it was quite a good idea, mother - mum sent
 him down now and again with an order written down you know and he'd go in and Mr Phillips knew him and he'd say he wanted a tin of sardines or he'd wanted something like that he could take and open at school, something that had got an opener with it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So what did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
When I look back at that - oh his father gave him a whacking. But I was - of course inwardly I was amused. I couldn't help it, because he was - he wouldn't - it's the same thing as when he played truant from school for about a fo
rtnight. I didn't know. He was at the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 Etchingham}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 college for boys in - Churchend, a private school and my next door neighbour came in - a gorgeous summer - came into me one day and she said - has Ronnie got a holiday Mrs Hargrave? So I said, a holiday? No.
 He'd been - used to go out and come in at the proper times. And - he'd been - and she said, well I've seen him every morning in the park. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 I said, in the park, Etchingham Park? }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 So she said, yes, playing tennis. So - oh, I thought, has he? So out - back I w
alked to the headmaster and - said to him, you know. He said, well Mrs Hargrave, what are you going to do? Are you going to leave it with me to deal with him or do you wish Mr Hargrave to deal with it himself. I said, well I think it would be better for y
ou, thought it wasn't, because he was - he dealt with him very gently indeed and he told me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid798957\charrsid8657389 afterwards}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 
 that the - prize giving, he said, well Mrs Hargrave, if you'd have seen his little face, he said, I asked him what he meant by - such - misconduct and he 
looked at me and he said, well sir, it was so fine - he said I felt a certain amount of sympathy for him. So I suppose the - the sharpness took him. But he didn't do - discipline him really in any way, but I don't think he ever did it again. I think the -
n
o, I think that he spoke to him in such a way that he probably won his confidence you know, thought he wouldn't let him down after that. I think perhaps his way was the right way. But I never had any really serious trouble with them. Not really, no. No, t
hey were quite good. They - there wasn't the temptations that there are now. I dread - I would - I'm glad I'm not a parent today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 There are a lot because they can meet so many people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 Well my granddaughter's a terrible trouble to her parents, she
's now on for the - gone into a - a place run by the - what they call the - what is it - Teenage Challenge. There are a lot of young people who open their homes to these drug addicts. Under supervision, by license. She was recommended by the probation off
i
cer and - but she had to go voluntarily you see, she consented to go, that's why she wasn't at home at Christmas. And she never regrets - she never goes out without she's got somebody with her, mind she's only been there less than a month. But during that
 time she's had no drugs. So that - oh we're keeping our fingers crossed. Doctor said that - he doesn't think that they'll do any good, they think she's gone too far.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9111045 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 But still a month is quite a long time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3612923 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14316909\charrsid8657389 To go without. Yes, considering that s
he had - when she went I told you she had both her arms and she looked at them and said, there's not a vein left to inject. Her poor mother, I felt so sorry for her mother.
\par }}